{"title_page": "Scott Horton (radio host)", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the issue is settled -->\n{{AfDM|page=Scott Horton (radio host) (2nd nomination)|year=2020|month=March|day=24|substed=yes|origtag=afdx|help=off}}\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Distinguish|Scott Horton (lawyer)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               =  Scott Horton\n| image              = Scotthorton.jpg\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Author, Podcaster, Radio host\n| organization       =  [[Antiwar Radio]], The Libertarian Institute\n| spouse             = [[Larisa Alexandrovna|Larisa Alexandrovna Horton]]\n| website            =  [http://scotthorton.org ScottHorton.org]\n}}\n'''Scott Horton''' is the author of the book ''Fool's Errand: Time to End the War in Afghanistan''<ref name=HortonFoolsErrand>Scott Horton, 2017, ''[[Fool's Errand: Time to End the War in Afghanistan]],'' [[The Libertarian Institute]] ({{ISBN|1548650218}})</ref> and founder and director of the Libertarian Institute.<ref>[https://libertarianinstitute.org/author/scotth/ \"Scott Horton\"], ''The Libertarian Institute''</ref> He hosts ''[[Antiwar Radio]]'' for Pacifica Radio's [[KPFK]] 90.7 FM in [[Los Angeles]] and [[KUCR]] in [[Riverside, California]],<ref>[https://www.kpfk.org/on-air/anti-war-radio/ \"Anti-War Radio\"], ''KPFK 90.7 FM''</ref> as well as the foreign policy interview podcast ''The Scott Horton Show.''<ref>[https://scotthorton.org/ \"Scotthorton.org\"], ''The Scott horton Show''</ref> Horton conducts interviews with journalists, politicians, pundits, lawyers and other experts on foreign policy and armed conflict, recording more than 5,000 interviews since 2003. \n \nHorton is the editorial director of the non-interventionist news portal [[Antiwar.com]].<ref>[http://antiwar.com/who.php \"Who We Are\"], ''Antiwar.com''</ref> He was previously the host of ''Say It Ain't So'' on Free Radio Austin 97.1 FM, the ''Weekend Interview Show'' and the KAOS Report on Radio KAOS 95.9 FM \u2013 for which he won ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'''s Best of Austin award in 2007 for \"Best Iraq War Coverage\"<ref>[http://www.austinchronicle.com/best-of-austin/year:2007/poll:critics/category:media/anti-war-radio-95-9-92-7fm-best-iraq-war-insight-and-play-by-play/ \"Best of Austin 2007\"], ''The Austin Chronicle''</ref> \u2013 and co-hosted the [[KOOP (FM)|KOOP]] Evening News.\n\n==Works==\n''\u2022 Fool's Errand: Time to End the War in Afghanistan.'' 2017.<ref name=HortonFoolsErrand></ref>   \n\n''\u2022 The Great Ron Paul: The Scott Horton Show Interviews 2004 \u2013 2019''. 2019.<ref name=\"HortonGreatRonPaul\">Scott Horton, 2019, ''[[The Great Ron Paul:  The Scott Horton Show Interviews 2004 - 2019]],'' [[The Libertarian Institute]] ({{ISBN|1733647317}})</ref>  \n\n''Fool's Errand'' was reviewed in multiple print and digital publications, including ''The Sandusky Register'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanduskyregister.com/news/11292/book-time-for-the-us-to-get-out-of-afghanistan/|title=Book: Time for the U.S. to get out of Afghanistan|website=sanduskyregister.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> ''The Future of Freedom'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fff.org/explore-freedom/article/bin-laden-won/|title=Bin Laden Won|website=The Future of Freedom Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and ''The American Conservative'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/fools-errand-a-guide-to-the-new-forgotten-war/|title='Fool's Errand': A Guide to the New Forgotten War|website=The American Conservative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> which described the work as a \"masterful account of America\u2019s prolonged Afghan engagement.\"  \n\nA presentation on ''Fool\u2019s Errand'' delivered to the Libertarian Party of Pennsylvania was featured on C-SPAN\u2019S ''BookTV'' series in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?441886-2/fools-errand|title=[Fool's Errand] {{!}} C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Horton was also invited to present a talk on the book for the Middle East Books and More bookstore in Washington, DC, which was covered favorably in the ''Washington Report on Middle East Affairs''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrmea.org/music-and-arts/scott-horton-on-why-the-u.s.-war-in-afghanistan-is-unwinnable.html|title=Scott Horton on Why the U.S. War in Afghanistan is Unwinnable|website=Washington Report on Middle East Affairs|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>  \n\nHorton has been sought out for commentary on US foreign policy in several other forums. He spoke at the 2019 Ron Paul Symposium,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mises.org/events/ron-paul-symposium-state-propaganda-2020-election|title=Ron Paul Symposium: State Propaganda & the 2020 Election|last=Chad|date=2018-12-18|website=Mises Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> hosted by the Ludwig von Mises Institute in Lake Jackson, Texas, and appeared in the 2019 documentary film ''An Endless War? Getting Out of Afghanistan'',<ref>{{Citation|last=Coen|first=Bob|title=An Endless War? Getting Out of Afghanistan|date=2018-11-16|url=https://vimeo.com/301322266|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> which was later screened before members of Congress on Capitol Hill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fcnl.org/updates/join-a-special-screening-of-an-endless-war-getting-out-of-afghanistan-2096|title=Join a Special Screening of \"An Endless War? Getting Out of Afghanistan\"|website=Friends Committee on National Legislation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>   \n\nHorton's writing has also been published in a number of periodicals, among them ''The Christian Science Monitor,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/Commentary/Opinion/2010/0917/Reality-check-Iran-is-not-a-nuclear-threat|title=Reality check: Iran is not a nuclear threat|date=2010-09-17|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2020-04-09|issn=0882-7729}}</ref> ''The American Conservative,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/war-without-a-rationale/|title=War Without a Rationale|website=The American Conservative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> ''The Future of Freedom'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fff.org/explore-freedom/article/u-s-government-to-blame-for-somalias-misery/|title=U.S. Government to Blame for Somalia's Misery|website=The Future of Freedom Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fff.org/explore-freedom/article/stupidity-or-plan/|title=Stupidity or Plan?|website=The Future of Freedom Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and ''The National Interest''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/why-attacking-iran-insane-idea-65841|title=Why Attacking Iran Is an Insane Idea|last=Robert Gaines|first=Scott Horton|date=2019-07-06|website=The National Interest|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/middle-east-watch/america-cannot-save-afghanistan-55142|title=America Cannot Save Afghanistan|last=Robert Gaines|first=Scott Horton|date=2019-04-30|website=The National Interest|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHorton is married to investigative reporter [[Larisa Alexandrovna]].<ref name=\"2018NJ\">{{Cite web |url=https://njlp.org/index.php?option=com_civicrm&task=civicrm/event/info&reset=1&id=15 |title= 2018 NJ Libertarian Party Convention>Speaker Biographies: Scott Horton |website=njlp.org |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nIn 2004, Horton served as foreign policy adviser to [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] presidential candidate [[Michael Badnarik]].<ref>{{cite AV media | people=Horton, Scott | date=December 18, 2017 | title=The Scott Horton Show - Episode 200 | publisher=Horton, Scott}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2008 Republican Presidential Primaries|2008 Presidential Primary]] season, Horton drew attention as a vocal defender of then-presidential candidate [[Ron Paul]] and his criticism of foreign intervention, arguing that Paul did not \"blame\" the American people for the September 11th attacks, and concluded that \"foreign occupation \u2013 American foreign policy \u2013 is a 'major contributing factor' in creating terrorism today, just as it was in the years before September 11th.\"<ref name=\"interested\">{{Cite web |url=https://original.antiwar.com/scott/2007/05/19/for-those-interested-in-facts-they-hate-our-foreign-policy/ |title=For Those Interested in Facts: They Hate Our Foreign Policy |last=Horton |first=Scott |date=May 5, 2007 |website=Antiwar.com Original |access-date=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2019, Horton officially joined the Libertarian Party as a lifetime member to support [[Jacob Hornberger]]\u2019s presidential campaign.<ref>[https://scotthorton.org/stress/i-just-joined-the-libertarian-party/ \"I Just Joined the Libertarian Party\"], ''The Scott Horton Show''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://scotthorton.org/ Scott Horton's home page]\n* [https://scotthorton.org/archives/ Full Interview Archive]\n* [http://original.antiwar.com/scott/?a=1 Scott Horton Articles for Antiwar.com]\n* [https://libertarianinstitute.org/scotthortonshow Scott Horton Archives at The Libertarian Institute]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horton, Scott}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American anti-war activists]]\n[[Category:American foreign policy writers]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:American political journalists]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American radio journalists]]\n[[Category:California Libertarians]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Texas]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Opinion journalists]]\n[[Category:Texas Libertarians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the issue is settled -->\n{{AfDM|page=Scott Horton (radio host) (2nd nomination)|year=2020|month=March|day=24|substed=yes|origtag=afdx|help=off}}\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Distinguish|Scott Horton (lawyer)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               =  Scott Horton\n| image              = Scotthorton.jpg\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Author, Podcaster, Radio host\n| organization       =  [[Antiwar Radio]], The Libertarian Institute\n| spouse             = [[Larisa Alexandrovna|Larisa Alexandrovna Horton]]\n| website            =  [http://scotthorton.org ScottHorton.org]\n}}\n'''Scott Horton''' is the author of the book ''Fool's Errand: Time to End the War in Afghanistan''<ref name=HortonFoolsErrand>Scott Horton, 2017, ''[[Fool's Errand: Time to End the War in Afghanistan]],'' [[The Libertarian Institute]] ({{ISBN|1548650218}})</ref> and founder and director of the Libertarian Institute.<ref>[https://libertarianinstitute.org/author/scotth/ \"Scott Horton\"], ''The Libertarian Institute''</ref> He hosts ''[[Antiwar Radio]]'' for Pacifica Radio's [[KPFK]] 90.7 FM in [[Los Angeles]] and [[KUCR]] in [[Riverside, California]],<ref>[https://www.kpfk.org/on-air/anti-war-radio/ \"Anti-War Radio\"], ''KPFK 90.7 FM''</ref> as well as the foreign policy interview podcast ''The Scott Horton Show.''<ref>[https://scotthorton.org/ \"Scotthorton.org\"], ''The Scott horton Show''</ref> Horton conducts interviews with journalists, politicians, pundits, lawyers and other experts on foreign policy and armed conflict, recording more than 5,000 interviews since 2003. \n \nHorton is the editorial director of the non-interventionist news portal [[Antiwar.com]].<ref>[http://antiwar.com/who.php \"Who We Are\"], ''Antiwar.com''</ref> He was previously the host of ''Say It Ain't So'' on Free Radio Austin 97.1 FM, the ''Weekend Interview Show'' and the KAOS Report on Radio KAOS 95.9 FM \u2013 for which he won ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'''s Best of Austin award in 2007 for \"Best Iraq War Coverage\"<ref>[http://www.austinchronicle.com/best-of-austin/year:2007/poll:critics/category:media/anti-war-radio-95-9-92-7fm-best-iraq-war-insight-and-play-by-play/ \"Best of Austin 2007\"], ''The Austin Chronicle''</ref> \u2013 and co-hosted the [[KOOP (FM)|KOOP]] Evening News.\n\n==Works==\n''\u2022 Fool's Errand: Time to End the War in Afghanistan.'' 2017.<ref name=HortonFoolsErrand></ref>   \n\n''\u2022 The Great Ron Paul: The Scott Horton Show Interviews 2004 \u2013 2019''. 2019.<ref name=\"HortonGreatRonPaul\">Scott Horton, 2019, ''[[The Great Ron Paul:  The Scott Horton Show Interviews 2004 - 2019]],'' [[The Libertarian Institute]] ({{ISBN|1733647317}})</ref>  \n\n''Fool's Errand'' was reviewed in multiple print and digital publications, including ''The Sandusky Register'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanduskyregister.com/news/11292/book-time-for-the-us-to-get-out-of-afghanistan/|title=Book: Time for the U.S. to get out of Afghanistan|website=sanduskyregister.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> ''The Future of Freedom'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fff.org/explore-freedom/article/bin-laden-won/|title=Bin Laden Won|website=The Future of Freedom Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and ''The American Conservative'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/fools-errand-a-guide-to-the-new-forgotten-war/|title='Fool's Errand': A Guide to the New Forgotten War|website=The American Conservative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> which described the work as a \"masterful account of America\u2019s prolonged Afghan engagement.\"  \n\nA presentation on ''Fool\u2019s Errand'' delivered to the Libertarian Party of Pennsylvania was featured on C-SPAN\u2019S ''BookTV'' series in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?441886-2/fools-errand|title=[Fool's Errand] {{!}} C-SPAN.org|website=www.c-span.org|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Horton was also invited to present a talk on the book for the Middle East Books and More bookstore in Washington, DC, which was covered favorably in the ''Washington Report on Middle East Affairs''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrmea.org/music-and-arts/scott-horton-on-why-the-u.s.-war-in-afghanistan-is-unwinnable.html|title=Scott Horton on Why the U.S. War in Afghanistan is Unwinnable|website=Washington Report on Middle East Affairs|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>  \n\nHorton has been sought out for commentary on US foreign policy in several other forums. He spoke at the 2019 Ron Paul Symposium,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mises.org/events/ron-paul-symposium-state-propaganda-2020-election|title=Ron Paul Symposium: State Propaganda & the 2020 Election|last=Chad|date=2018-12-18|website=Mises Institute|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> hosted by the Ludwig von Mises Institute in Lake Jackson, Texas, and appeared in the 2019 documentary film ''An Endless War? Getting Out of Afghanistan'',<ref>{{Citation|last=Coen|first=Bob|title=An Endless War? Getting Out of Afghanistan|date=2018-11-16|url=https://vimeo.com/301322266|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> which was later screened before members of Congress on Capitol Hill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fcnl.org/updates/join-a-special-screening-of-an-endless-war-getting-out-of-afghanistan-2096|title=Join a Special Screening of \"An Endless War? Getting Out of Afghanistan\"|website=Friends Committee on National Legislation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>   \n\nHorton's writing has also been published in a number of venues, among them ''The Christian Science Monitor,''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/Commentary/Opinion/2010/0917/Reality-check-Iran-is-not-a-nuclear-threat|title=Reality check: Iran is not a nuclear threat|date=2010-09-17|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2020-04-09|issn=0882-7729}}</ref> ''The American Conservative,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theamericanconservative.com/articles/war-without-a-rationale/|title=War Without a Rationale|website=The American Conservative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> ''The Future of Freedom'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fff.org/explore-freedom/article/u-s-government-to-blame-for-somalias-misery/|title=U.S. Government to Blame for Somalia's Misery|website=The Future of Freedom Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fff.org/explore-freedom/article/stupidity-or-plan/|title=Stupidity or Plan?|website=The Future of Freedom Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and ''The National Interest''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/buzz/why-attacking-iran-insane-idea-65841|title=Why Attacking Iran Is an Insane Idea|last=Robert Gaines|first=Scott Horton|date=2019-07-06|website=The National Interest|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalinterest.org/blog/middle-east-watch/america-cannot-save-afghanistan-55142|title=America Cannot Save Afghanistan|last=Robert Gaines|first=Scott Horton|date=2019-04-30|website=The National Interest|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHorton is married to investigative reporter [[Larisa Alexandrovna]].<ref name=\"2018NJ\">{{Cite web |url=https://njlp.org/index.php?option=com_civicrm&task=civicrm/event/info&reset=1&id=15 |title= 2018 NJ Libertarian Party Convention>Speaker Biographies: Scott Horton |website=njlp.org |access-date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nIn 2004, Horton served as foreign policy adviser to [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] presidential candidate [[Michael Badnarik]].<ref>{{cite AV media | people=Horton, Scott | date=December 18, 2017 | title=The Scott Horton Show - Episode 200 | publisher=Horton, Scott}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2008 Republican Presidential Primaries|2008 Presidential Primary]] season, Horton drew attention as a vocal defender of then-presidential candidate [[Ron Paul]] and his criticism of foreign intervention, arguing that Paul did not \"blame\" the American people for the September 11th attacks, and concluded that \"foreign occupation \u2013 American foreign policy \u2013 is a 'major contributing factor' in creating terrorism today, just as it was in the years before September 11th.\"<ref name=\"interested\">{{Cite web |url=https://original.antiwar.com/scott/2007/05/19/for-those-interested-in-facts-they-hate-our-foreign-policy/ |title=For Those Interested in Facts: They Hate Our Foreign Policy |last=Horton |first=Scott |date=May 5, 2007 |website=Antiwar.com Original |access-date=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2019, Horton officially joined the Libertarian Party as a lifetime member to support [[Jacob Hornberger]]\u2019s presidential campaign.<ref>[https://scotthorton.org/stress/i-just-joined-the-libertarian-party/ \"I Just Joined the Libertarian Party\"], ''The Scott Horton Show''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://scotthorton.org/ Scott Horton's home page]\n* [https://scotthorton.org/archives/ Full Interview Archive]\n* [http://original.antiwar.com/scott/?a=1 Scott Horton Articles for Antiwar.com]\n* [https://libertarianinstitute.org/scotthortonshow Scott Horton Archives at The Libertarian Institute]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Horton, Scott}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\