e news|title=Raba ukuntu SAT \u2013 B ategura Video nshasha yitwa SATURA AMABAFLE irimwo abantu barenga 5000|url=http://www.ikirere.com/?p=1855|accessdate=29 September 2014|publisher=Ikirere}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Amasanamu y\u2019indirimbo Satura amabafle ya Sat-b yarafashwe|url=http://www.kumwanya.com/entertainment/amasanamu-yindirimbo-satura-amabafle-ya-sat-b-yarafashwe/#sthash.4fculneF.dpbs|accessdate=16 September 2014|publisher=Kumwanya}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Kanyosha:Isanamu Satura ama bafle ya Sat-B yafashwe |url=http://greatlakesmix.com/news/2014/09/15/kanyoshaisanamu-satura-ama-bafle-ya-sat-b-yafashwe/|accessdate=15 September 2014|publisher=GLM Mix}}</ref>\n| Kent-P<ref>{{cite news|title=SATURA AMABAFLE yaraye ifashwe amasanamu.|url=http://umuravyo.com/?p=1182|accessdate=17 September 2014|publisher=Umuravyo}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Impemburo\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2015\n| Kent-P\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Generation Moto Moto ft Nizzo Kaboss\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2015\n| Gilbert Benjamins & Kent-P\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Nyampinga\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2016\n| Gilbert Benjamins & Kent-P\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"African Girl\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2016\n| Meddy Menz & Kent-P\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Love You ft [[Urban Boyz]]\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2016\n| Grate Pest\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Too Much\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2017\n| Kent-P\n|-\n! Scope=\"row\"| \"Ivyo Bintu Ft [[Producer Washington| Magic Washington]]\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2017\n| Kent-P\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Feel Love\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2017\n| Sasha Vybz\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"No Love\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2018\n| Joowzey\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Karabarya\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2018\n| Sasha Vybz\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"50-100 (Amabuno) ft [[Best Life Music]], Belle 9ice, [[Clementine Kavy]] and Bain Turo\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2019\n| Kent-P\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Love Controller\"\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2019\n| Taty Lameck\n{{end}}\n{{-}}\n\n====Featuring videos====\n* Katoto Rmx by Dj Pro ft Mkombozi<ref name=\"Katoto Rmx by Dj Pro ft Sat B & Mkombozi Official Video Music\">{{cite web|title=Katoto Rmx by Dj Pro ft Sat B & Mkombozi Official Video Music|url=http://isaacproduction.com/katoto-rmx-by-dj-pro-ft-sat-b-mkombozi-official-video-music/|website=http://isaacproduction.com|publisher=Isaac|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref>\n* Stay With Me by Alida B<ref>{{cite web|title=Stay With me \u2013 SAT B ft ALIDA (Official Video)|url=http://www.eastafricanhit.com/stay-sat-b-ft-alida-official-video/|website=http://www.eastafricanhit.com|publisher=East African Hit|accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref>\n*\n\n==Awards==\n===[[Buja Music Awards]] ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Prize\n!Work/Recipient\n!Result\n|-\n|2019\n|''Artist Of The Year''\n|\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|-\n|2019\n|''Song of the Year''\n|No Love\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|-\n|2019\n|''Best Performance''\n|\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|-\n|2019\n|''Best Male Artist''\n|\n|{{win}}\n|-\n|-\n|2019\n|''Video Of The Year''\n|Karabarya directed by Sasha Vybz\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n{{-}}\n\n===Afrima===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2016\n|Sat-B\n|Most Promising Artist\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n{{Infobox musician awards\n| name = Sat-B\n| image = \n| image_size = 220px\n| alt =\n| caption = \n| collapse = yes\n| wins = 8\n| nominations = 3\n\n| award1 =  Afrima\n| award1W = 0\n| award1N = 1\n| award2 =  Top Ten Music Awards\n| award2W = 1\n| award2N = 0\n| award3 = Radio Achievement\n| award3W = 3\n| award3N = 0\n| award4 = Ikoh Multiservice\n| award4W = 1\n| award4N = 0\n| award5 = [[Buja Music Awards]]\n| award5W = 3\n| award5N = 2\n}}\n\n===Ikoh Multiservice===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2014\n|Sat-B\n|Artist of the Year<ref>{{cite news|title=Ikoh Awards|url=http://ubmnews.com/hamenyekanye-impanvu-ikomeye-yatumye-sat-b-yanka-kwakira-agashimwe-kadasanzwe-bari-bamuhaye-soma-ngaha-wunve/|accessdate=23 December 2014|publisher=UbmNews}}</ref>\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n===Top Ten Tube Music Awards===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2013\n|Ikinyamugigima<ref>{{cite news|title=AMASENGESHO YA SAT-B YARAYE YUMVIWE|url=http://indundi.com/news/page/33383|publisher=Indundi}}</ref>\n|Video of the Year<ref>{{cite news|title=REVUE: TOP TEN TUBE MUSIC AWARDS 2013|url=http://art-rhythm.blogspot.com/2013/09/revue-top-ten-tube-music-awards-2013.html|accessdate=6 September 2013|publisher=art-rhythm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u00d4 joie !, les Top Ten Tube Music Awards remettent le couvert \u00e0 l\u2019IFB|url=http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/top-ten-tube-music-awards-musique-ifb/|accessdate=6 September 2013|publisher=Iwacu Burundi}}</ref>\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n===Radio Achievement ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Award Ceremony\n!Prize\n!Work/Recipient\n!Result\n|-\n|2017\n|Buja Fm Hits Connection\n|''Song of the month January''\n|Too Much\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|-\n|2017\n|RFM\n|''Artist of the Year''\n|Feel Love\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|-\n|2018\n|Buja Fm\n|''Song of the Year''\n|No Love\n|{{won}}\n|-\n\n|}\n\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2 }}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/pages/Sat-b-satlight/325080860937529?ref=hl Sat-B on Facebook]\n\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Burundian singers]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Kora Entertainmentclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sat-B"}
{"title_page": "Ernest Berry Webber", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = Ernest Berry Webber\n| image                 = Ernest Berry Webber.jpg\n| image_size            = <!-- if image is smaller than 250px -->\n| caption               = \n| birth_date            = {{Birth date|1896|4|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place           = [[Walworth]], London \n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1963|12|19|1896|4|19|df=yes}}\n| death_place           = [[Brighton]], [[Sussex]]\n| alma_mater            = \n| practice              = \n| parents               = \n| significant_buildings = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Southampton Civic Centre]]\n* [[Civic Centre, Dagenham|Dagenham Civic Centre]]\n* [[Hammersmith Town Hall]] \n* [[King Edward VI School, Southampton]]\n}}\n| significant_projects = \n| significant_design    = \n| awards                = \n}}\n\n'''Ernest Berry Webber''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|size=100%|FRIBA}}<ref>\"Southampton's Art Gallery\", ''The Sphere'', 13 May 1939, p. 29.</ref> (29 April 1896<ref>The National Archives; Kew, London, England; ''1939 Register''; Reference: RG 101/638F</ref> \u2013 19 December 1963)<ref name=\"PROBATE\">''England & Wales, National Probate Calendar (Index of Wills and Administrations), 1858\u20131995'', p. 130.</ref> was an English architect, surveyor and town planner, best known for his designs of municipal buildings, including those in [[Southampton]] in [[Hampshire]], and [[Dagenham]] and [[Hammersmith]], both in London.\n\nBorn in London, and after attending the London School of Building, Webber studied under [[Arthur Beresford Pite]] and then became articled to the architect [[Robert Atkinson (architect)| Robert Atkinson]].  During the war years, Webber moved to the office of [[Vincent Harris]], a prolific designer of public buildings, and from whom he drew much inspiration. His work there involved entering his practice into architectural competitions by undertaking urban planning drafts and municipal buildings. \n\nIn 1925, aged 29, Webber won a competition to design a new art gallery and museum in [[Manchester]], to be constructed on the site now occupied by [[Piccadilly Gardens]]. The plans never went ahead, but it brought him much attention from his peers. His first major municipal design was the [[Southampton Civic Centre|Guildhall Civic Centre]] in Southampton, which was built over a ten-year period.  Other civic centres followed, including the Civic Centres at [[Civic Centre, Dagenham|Dagenham]] (1936\u201337), and [[Hammersmith Town Hall|Hammersmith]] (1939\u201340). Together with his municipal structures, his designs total at around 50 buildings, including schools, offices, museums and libraries.\n\nWebber retired to [[Brighton]] in the 1950s where he died in 1963 aged 67.\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:Southampton-CivicCentre-South.jpg|thumb|right|Civic Centre and Guildhall, [[Southampton]] (1929\u201339)]]\nWebber was born at 47 St. Paul's Road, [[Walworth]], [[Surrey]].<ref name=\"FREEDOM\">London Metropolitan Archive; ''Freedom of the City Admission Papers, 1681\u20131930'', Reference Number: COL/CHD/FR/02/2764.</ref> He was the youngest of three children, and the second son to Henry Webber, a shopkeeper,<ref name=\"FREEDOM\"/> and his wife, Clara.<ref>''1901 England Census'', Class; RG13; Piece: 375; Folio: 29; p. 50.</ref>\n\nErnest attended the London School of Building and studied under [[Arthur Beresford Pite]]. After leaving, he became articled to [[Robert Atkinson (architect)| Robert Atkinson]], and in 1914 he moved to the office of [[Vincent Harris]], a prolific designer of public buildings.<ref name=\"LDP4\">\"Young Architect's Triumph: Design for new Manchester Art Gallery selected\", ''Lancashire Daily Post'', 11 June 1925, p. 4.</ref> The [[World War I|war]] intervened and Webber served his four year service in France.<ref>\"Young Architect's Triumph\", ''[[The Liverpool Echo]]'', 10 June 1925, p. 8.</ref> After the war, he resumed his apprenticeship with Harris where his work focused on preparing designs for competitions; he stayed with Harris for 11 years.<ref name=\"LDP4\"/>\n\n==Designs==\n[[File:Peterborough Town Hall 1.jpg|thumb|left|Peterborough Town Hall (1929\u201333)]] \nWebber became an Associate of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] (RIBA) in 1923 and was able to set up his own practise three years later.{{sfn|Neal|2014|p=128}}\n\nAt the age of 29, Webber won a competition to design a new art gallery and museum in [[Manchester]], to be constructed on the site now occupied by [[Piccadilly Gardens]]. The design would also have doubled as a memorial to casualties of the [[First World War]]. The competition, which had over 100 entrants, some of whom were already well-established architects,<ref name=\"LDP4\"/> was held in 1925 by Manchester Council to fill the space left by the demolition of [[Manchester Royal Infirmary]].<ref name=\"MEN2018\">[https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/how-piccadilly-gardens-could-looked-15541219 \"This is how Piccadilly Gardens could have looked\"], ''[[Manchester Evening News]]'', 15 December 2018.</ref> A reporter for the ''Lancashire Daily Post'' listed the win as Webber's \"first great success\" and the moment when he jumps from \"comparative obscurity to a position of high distinction in his profession.\"<ref name=\"LDP4\"/> Despite the success, the project was cancelled due to the post-war financial crash and the [[Great Depression]] of 1929.<ref name=\"MEN2018\"/>\n\n[[File:Dagenham civic center london.jpg|thumb|right|[[Civic Centre, Dagenham]] (1937\u201337)]]\nIn 1929 Webber won a competition to design the [[Southampton Civic Centre|Guildhall Civic Centre]] in [[Southampton]],<ref name=\"RIBA1\">[https://www.architecture.com/image-library/ribapix/image-information/poster/guildhall-civic-centre-southampton-one-of-the-doors-into-the-assembly-hall/posterid/RIBA73802.html \"Guildhall, Civic Centre, Southampton: one of the doors into the assembly hall\"], [[Royal Institute of British Architects]], accessed 5 April 2020.</ref> which required his relocation to the city as the construction period was to last for 10 years, which he was to oversee. It was built to a cost of \u00a3620,000<ref name=\"TEG17\">\"Well known architect: New resident in Eastbourne\", ''[[Eastbourne Gazette|The Eastbourne Gazette]]'', 28 December 1938, p. 17.</ref> and completed in 1939.<ref name=\"RIBA1\"/> [[Pevsner Architectural Guides|Pevsner's]] ''Hampshire: South'' describes the guildhall as \"the most ambitious civic building erected in the provinces in the interwar years\".{{sfn|O'Brien|Bailey|Pevsner|Lloyd|2018|p=614}} The building was designated as a Grade II* [[listed building]] in 1980.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1092036|desc=Southampton Civic Centre|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Alongside this, he completed the new [[King Edward VI School, Southampton|King Edward VI School]], also in the city.<ref name=\"TEG17\" />{{sfn|O'Brien|Bailey|Pevsner|Lloyd|2018|p=672}} \n\nIn 1928 Webber won a competition to design a new town hall in Peterborough. The foundation stone was laid in June 1929 and it was officially opened in October 1933.<ref>[https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-peterborough-evening-telegraph/20170706/282888025716379 \"Blue Plaque Stories\"], ''The [[Peterborough Evening Telegraph]]'', 6 July 2017, p. 11. </ref> The building was designed in the \"[[Baroque Revival architecture|English Baroque]]\" style.{{sfn|O'Brien|Pevsner|2014|p=623}} A reporter for the ''Architect and Building News'' described the design as being from someone who was \"at the top of his form\".<ref>Quote from the ''Architect and Building News''; Neal, p. 128.</ref> The building was completed and opened in 1933.{{efn|[[Nikolaus Pevsner]], although appreciating Webber's efforts to place Peterborough Town Hall in its context, did not wholly approve of his chosen architectural style; \"The choice of the style at so late a date may be deplorable, but the building is tactfully fitted into the street architecture of Peterborough. The architect has resisted the temptation to set his work up as a monument to compete with the [[Peterborough Cathedral|cathedral]]\".{{sfn|O'Brien|Pevsner|2014|p=623}}}}<ref>[https://www.peterborough.gov.uk/asset-library/imported-assets/ListOfHeritageAssetsInPeterborough2019.pdf \"Local List of Heritage Assets: Draft for consultation 2016\"], Peterborough City Council, p. 60.</ref>\n\n[[File:Hammersmith Town Hall in daylight - geograph.org.uk - 800796.jpg|thumb|left|[[Hammersmith Town Hall]] (1939\u201340)]]\nWebber designed the [[Dagenham Civic Centre]], built from 1936 to 1937.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lbbd.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Infosheet48-Dagenham-Civic-Centre.pdf |format=PDF |title=London Borough of Barking and Dagenham Local Studies Information Sheet No.48 : Dagenham Civic Centre |website=Lbbd.gov.uk |accessdate=19 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305141322/https://www.lbbd.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Infosheet48-Dagenham-Civic-Centre.pdf |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Civic Centre's foundation stone was laid by [[Harry Snell, 1st Baron Snell]] on 11 July 1936.<ref>[http://www.britishpathe.com/video/dagenham-civic-centre \"Dagenham Civic Centre 1935\"], [[Path\u00e9 News]], accessed 8 April 2020.</ref> Pevsner describes the centre as \"Dagenham's best building by far\".{{sfn|Cherry|O'Brien|Pevsner|2007|p=150}} It is constructed in the [[Modern architecture|Modernist]] style, which Webber also used for the adjacent fire and ambulance station.{{efn|Webber's fire station was demolished and a replacement constructed on the site in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/2016-news/dagenham-crews-move-into-brand-new-fire-station/|title=Dagenham crews move into brand new fire station|publisher=London Fire Brigade|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|date=26 January 2016}}</ref>}} The Civic Centre was opened on 16 October 1937 by [[Kingsley Wood|Sir Kingsley Wood]].<ref>\"Tribute to Local Government\", ''The [[Nottingham Evening Post]]'', 16 October 1937, p. 5.</ref> A later, 1964, extension to the civic centre was completed by his firm after Webber's death.{{sfn|Cherry|O'Brien|Pevsner|2007|p=152}}  \n\nAlso in 1936, Webber won a competition to build the parliamentary buildings in [[Southern Rhodesia]].<ref>[http://wiredspace.wits.ac.za/bitstream/handle/10539/18845/Journal%20of%20SAAI-December-1936-001-jpeg.pdf?sequence=18&isAllowed=y \"The South Africa Architectural Journal\"], p. 426.</ref>\n\nThe following year, he undertook the designs for [[Hammersmith Town Hall]] in King Street, [[Hammersmith]], London, which were completed in 1939.  Pevsner calls the town hall \"an unfortunate building\", regretting both the loss of the \"picturesque character\" of the area which occurred as a result of its construction, and the \"ill-judged\" extensions of the 1970s.{{sfn|Cherry|Pevsner|2002|p=208}} It became a Grade II listed building,<ref name=\"NHLE\">{{NHLE|num=1079785|desc=Hammersmith Town Hall|accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> together with the Civic Centre in Dagenham,<ref>{{NHLE|num=1064422|desc=Main Building and Council Chamber of Dagenham Civic Centre|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> in 1981.<ref name=\"NHLE\"/>\n\nWebber was appointed by the [[Royal Navy]] as the consulting architect for improvements to their barracks, [[HMNB Portsmouth]] and [[HMNB Devonport]], in 1947.<ref>\"Architect for Barracks Modernization\", ''[[The Hampshire Telegraph and Post]]'', 3 October 1947, p. 1.</ref>\n\nIn 1955 Webber undertook a \u00a31.5million rebuild of the [[Portsmouth Guildhall]], which had received substantial bomb damage during [[World War II|the war]].{{sfn|Groombridge|2017|p=??}} It was reopened by [[Elizabeth II]] on 10 June 1959.<ref>\"Guildhall rises from rubble\", ''Hampshire Telegraph and Post'', 22 March 1957, p. 3.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWebber married Gladys {{nee}} Bellis Roberts (1896\u20131984) on 22 November 1922 at [[Bow Church|St Mary and Holy Trinity Church]] in [[Stratford, London|Stratford]].<ref>''Church of England Marriages and Banns, 1754\u20131932'', London Metropolitan Archives, p. 89.</ref> They had a son named Geoffrey.{{sfn|Neal|2014|p=126}} On 25 June 1929 Webber was given the [[Freedom of the City of London]].<ref name=\"FREEDOM\"/> He was a president of the [[Eccentric Club]] during the 1940s,<ref>\"The Variety Stage\",''The Stage'', 21 April 1949, p. 3.</ref> and in 1960 he was made a companion of the entertainment charity, the [[Grand Order of Water Rats]].<ref>\"The Grand Order of Water Rats\", ''The Stage'', 7 January 1960, p. 13.</ref>\n\nWebber retired to [[Brighton]] in the 1950s.{{sfn|Neal|2014|p=128}} He was taken ill at his house, 2 Arundel Terrace, and died shortly after at the [[Royal Sussex County Hospital]] on 19 December 1963. His probate was set at \u00a318,611<ref name=\"PROBATE\"/> (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|18611|1963|r=-4}}}} in {{Inflation/year|UK}} adjusted for inflation).{{inflation-fn|UK}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book\n| last1= Cherry | first1 = Bridget\n| last2 = Pevsner | first2 = Nikolaus\n| authorlink1 = Bridget Cherry\n| authorlink2 = Nikolaus Pevsner\n| title = London 3: North West\n| series = The Buildings of England \n| year = 2002\n| url = https://www.worldcat.org/title/london-3-north-west/oclc/983761260&referer=brief_results\n| publisher = [[Yale University Press]]\n| location = New Haven, US and London \n| isbn = 978-0-300-09652-1 \n| ref = {{sfnRef|Cherry|Pevsner|2002}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1= Cherry | first1 = Bridget\n| last2 = O'Brien | first2 = Charles\n| last3 = Pevsner | first3 = Nikolaus\n| authorlink1 = Bridget Cherry\n| authorlink3 = Nikolaus Pevsner\n| title = London 5: East\n| series = The Buildings of England \n| year = 2007\n| url = https://www.worldcat.org/title/london-5-east/oclc/983755807&referer=brief_results\n| publisher = [[Yale University Press]]\n| location = New Haven, US and London \n| isbn = 978-0-300-10701-2  \n| ref = {{sfnRef|Cherry|O'Brien|Pevsner|2007}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Groombridge | first = Garth \n| title = Portsmouth in 50 buildings\n| year = 2017\n| url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rDMqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT73&lpg=PT73&dq=portsmouth+guildhall+e+berry+webber&source=bl&ots=x0IawyZ9zG&sig=ACfU3U17K1LC7TlYJ6i1LVTvfFltzXoC0A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjst8DGttjoAhXkQhUIHTMGACkQ6AEwAnoECAsQMg#v=onepage&q=portsmouth%20guildhall%20e%20berry%20webber&f=false\n| publisher = Amberley Publishing\n| location = Stroud, UK \n| isbn = 978-1-445-66406-4 \n| ref = {{sfnRef|Groombridge|2017}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = Neal | first1 = Peter \n| title = Story of Southampton\n| year = 2014\n| url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sZtvAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT195&ots=gVk-WaTxXx&dq=Reading%20Ernest%20Berry%20Webber&pg=PT195#v=onepage&q=Reading%20Ernest%20Berry%20Webber&f=false\n| publisher = The History Press\n| location = Stroud, UK \n| isbn = 978-0-750-95861-5\n| ref = {{sfnRef|Neal|2014}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = O'Brien | first1 = Charles\n| last2 = Pevsner | first2 = Nikolaus\n| authorlink2 = Nikolaus Pevsner\n| title = Bedfordshire, Huntingdonshire and Peterborough\n| series = The Buildings of England \n| year = 2014\n| url = https://www.worldcat.org/title/bedfordshire-huntingdonshire-and-peterborough-the-buildings-of-england/oclc/881612533&referer=brief_results\n| publisher = [[Yale University Press]]\n| location = New Haven, US and London \n| isbn = 978-0-300-20821-4  \n| ref = {{sfnRef|O'Brien|Pevsner|2014}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = O'Brien | first1 = Charles\n| last2 = Bailey | first2 = Bruce \n| last3 = Pevsner | first3 = Nikolaus\n| last4 = Lloyd | first4 = David W. \n| authorlink3 = Nikolaus Pevsner\n| title = Hampshire: South\n| series = The Buildings of England \n| year = 2018\n| url = https://www.worldcat.org/title/hampshire-south/oclc/1078192100?referer=br&ht=edition \n| publisher = [[Yale University Press]]\n| location = New Haven, US and London \n| isbn = 978-0-300-18507-2  \n| ref = {{sfnRef|O'Brien|Bailey|Pevsner|Lloyd|2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Webber, Ernest Berry}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English architects]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox architect\n| name                  = Ernest Berry Webber\n| image                 = Ernest Berry Webber.jpg\n| image_size            = <!-- if image is smaller than 250px -->\n| caption               = \n| birth_date            = {{Birth date|1896|4|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place           = [[Walworth]], London \n| death_date            = {{Death date and age|1963|12|19|1896|4|19|df=yes}}\n| death_place           = [[Brighton]], [[Sussex]]\n| alma_mater            = \n| practice              = \n| parents               = \n| significant_buildings = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Southampton Civic Centre]]\n* [[Civic Centre, Dagenham|Dagenham Civic Centre]]\n* [[Hammersmith Town Hall]] \n* [[King Edward VI School, Southampton]]\n}}\n| significant_projects = \n| significant_design    = \n| awards                = \n}}\n\n'''Ernest Berry Webber''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|sep=,|size=100%|FRIBA}}<ref>\"Southampton's Art Gallery\", ''The Sphere'', 13 May 1939, p. 29.</ref> (29 April 1896<ref>The National Archives; Kew, London, England; ''1939 Register''; Reference: RG 101/638F</ref> \u2013 19 December 1963)<ref name=\"PROBATE\">''England & Wales, National Probate Calendar (Index of Wills and Administrations), 1858\u20131995'', p. 130.</ref> was an English architect, surveyor and town planner, best known for his designs of municipal buildings, including those in [[Southampton]] in [[Hampshire]], and [[Dagenham]] and [[Hammersmith]], both in London.\n\nBorn in London, and after attending the London School of Building, Webber studied under [[Arthur Beresford Pite]] and then became articled to the architect [[Robert Atkinson (architect)| Robert Atkinson]].  During the war years, Webber moved to the office of [[Vincent Harris]], a prolific designer of public buildings, and from whom he drew much inspiration. His work there involved entering his practice into architectural competitions by undertaking urban planning drafts and municipal buildings. \n\nIn 1925, aged 29, Webber won a competition to design a new art gallery and museum in [[Manchester]], to be constructed on the site now occupied by [[Piccadilly Gardens]]. The plans never went ahead, but it brought him much attention from his peers. His first major municipal design was the [[Southampton Civic Centre|Guildhall Civic Centre]] in Southampton, which was built over a ten-year period.  Other civic centres followed, including the Civic Centres at [[Civic Centre, Dagenham|Dagenham]] (1936\u201337), and [[Hammersmith Town Hall|Hammersmith]] (1939\u201340). Together with his municipal structures, his designs total at around 50 buildings, including schools, offices, museums and libraries.\n\nWebber retired to [[Brighton]] in the 1950s where he died in 1963 aged 67.\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:Southampton-CivicCentre-South.jpg|thumb|right|Civic Centre and Guildhall, [[Southampton]] (1929\u201339)]]\nWebber was born at 47 St. Paul's Road, [[Walworth]], [[Surrey]].<ref name=\"FREEDOM\">London Metropolitan Archive; ''Freedom of the City Admission Papers, 1681\u20131930'', Reference Number: COL/CHD/FR/02/2764.</ref> He was the youngest of three children, and the second son to Henry Webber, a shopkeeper,<ref name=\"FREEDOM\"/> and his wife, Clara.<ref>''1901 England Census'', Class; RG13; Piece: 375; Folio: 29; p. 50.</ref>\n\nErnest attended the London School of Building and studied under [[Arthur Beresford Pite]]. After leaving, he became articled to [[Robert Atkinson (architect)| Robert Atkinson]], and in 1914 he moved to the office of [[Vincent Harris]], a prolific designer of public buildings.<ref name=\"LDP4\">\"Young Architect's Triumph: Design for new Manchester Art Gallery selected\", ''Lancashire Daily Post'', 11 June 1925, p. 4.</ref> The [[World War I|war]] intervened and Webber served his four year service in France.<ref>\"Young Architect's Triumph\", ''[[The Liverpool Echo]]'', 10 June 1925, p. 8.</ref> After the war, he resumed his apprenticeship with Harris where his work focused on preparing designs for competitions; he stayed with Harris for 11 years.<ref name=\"LDP4\"/>\n\n==Designs==\n[[File:Peterborough Town Hall 1.jpg|thumb|left|Peterborough Town Hall (1929\u201333)]] \nWebber became an Associate of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] (RIBA) in 1923 and was able to set up his own practise three years later.{{sfn|Neal|2014|p=128}}\n\nAt the age of 29, Webber won a competition to design a new art gallery and museum in [[Manchester]], to be constructed on the site now occupied by [[Piccadilly Gardens]]. The design would also have doubled as a memorial to casualties of the [[First World War]]. The competition, which had over 100 entrants, some of whom were already well-established architects,<ref name=\"LDP4\"/> was held in 1925 by Manchester Council to fill the space left by the demolition of [[Manchester Royal Infirmary]].<ref name=\"MEN2018\">[https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/how-piccadilly-gardens-could-looked-15541219 \"This is how Piccadilly Gardens could have looked\"], ''[[Manchester Evening News]]'', 15 December 2018.</ref> A reporter for the ''Lancashire Daily Post'' listed the win as Webber's \"first great success\" and the moment when he jumps from \"comparative obscurity to a position of high distinction in his profession.\"<ref name=\"LDP4\"/> Despite the success, the project was cancelled due to the post-war financial crash and the [[Great Depression]] of 1929.<ref name=\"MEN2018\"/>\n\n[[File:Dagenham civic center london.jpg||thumb|right|[[Civic Centre, Dagenham]] (1937\u201337)]]\nIn 1929 Webber won a competition to design the [[Southampton Civic Centre|Guildhall Civic Centre]] in [[Southampton]],<ref name=\"RIBA1\">[https://www.architecture.com/image-library/ribapix/image-information/poster/guildhall-civic-centre-southampton-one-of-the-doors-into-the-assembly-hall/posterid/RIBA73802.html \"Guildhall, Civic Centre, Southampton: one of the doors into the assembly hall\"], [[Royal Institute of British Architects]], accessed 5 April 2020.</ref> which required his relocation to the city as the construction period was to last for 10 years, which he was to oversee. It was built to a cost of \u00a3620,000<ref name=\"TEG17>\"Well known architect: New resident in Eastbourne\", ''[[Eastbourne Gazette|The Eastbourne Gazette]]'', 28 December 1938, p. 17.</ref> and completed in 1939.<ref name=\"RIBA1\"/> [[Pevsner Architectural Guides|Pevsner's]] ''Hampshire: South'' describes the guildhall as \"the most ambitious civic building erected in the provinces in the interwar years\".{{sfn|O'Brien|Bailey|Pevsner|Lloyd|2018|p=614}} The building was designated as a Grade II* [[listed building]] in 1980.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1092036|desc=Southampton Civic Centre|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Alongside this, he completed the new [[King Edward VI School, Southampton|King Edward VI School]], also in the city.<ref name=\"TEG17/>{{sfn|O'Brien|Bailey|Pevsner|Lloyd|2018|p=672}} \n\nIn 1928 Webber won a competition to design a new town hall in Peterborough. The foundation stone was laid in June 1929 and it was officially opened in October 1933.<ref>[https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-peterborough-evening-telegraph/20170706/282888025716379 \"Blue Plaque Stories\"], ''The [[Peterborough Evening Telegraph]]'', 6 July 2017, p. 11. </ref> The building was designed in the \"[[Baroque Revival architecture|English Baroque]]\" style.{{sfn|O'Brien|Pevsner|2014|p=623}} A reporter for the ''Architect and Building News'' described the design as being from someone who was \"at the top of his form\".<ref>Quote from the ''Architect and Building News''; Neal, p. 128.</ref> The building was completed and opened in 1933.{{efn|[[Nikolaus Pevsner]], although appreciating Webber's efforts to place Peterborough Town Hall in its context, did not wholly approve of his chosen architectural style; \"The choice of the style at so late a date may be deplorable, but the building is tactfully fitted into the street architecture of Peterborough. The architect has resisted the temptation to set his work up as a monument to compete with the [[Peterborough Cathedral|cathedral]]\".{{sfn|O'Brien|Pevsner|2014|p=623}}}}<ref>[https://www.peterborough.gov.uk/asset-library/imported-assets/ListOfHeritageAssetsInPeterborough2019.pdf \"Local List of Heritage Assets: Draft for consultation 2016\"], Peterborough City Council, p. 60.</ref>\n\n[[File:Hammersmith Town Hall in daylight - geograph.org.uk - 800796.jpg|thumb|left|[[Hammersmith Town Hall]] (1939\u201340)]]\nWebber designed the [[Dagenham Civic Centre]], built from 1936 to 1937.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lbbd.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Infosheet48-Dagenham-Civic-Centre.pdf |format=PDF |title=London Borough of Barking and Dagenham Local Studies Information Sheet No.48 : Dagenham Civic Centre |website=Lbbd.gov.uk |accessdate=19 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305141322/https://www.lbbd.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Infosheet48-Dagenham-Civic-Centre.pdf |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Civic Centre's foundation stone was laid by [[Harry Snell, 1st Baron Snell]] on 11 July 1936.<ref>[http://www.britishpathe.com/video/dagenham-civic-centre \"Dagenham Civic Centre 1935\"], [[Path\u00e9 News]], accessed 8 April 2020.</ref> Pevsner describes the centre as \"Dagenham's best building by far\".{{sfn|Cherry|O'Brien|Pevsner|2007|p=150}} It is constructed in the [[Modern architecture|Modernist]] style, which Webber also used for the adjacent fire and ambulance station.{{efn|Webber's fire station was demolished and a replacement constructed on the site in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.london-fire.gov.uk/news/2016-news/dagenham-crews-move-into-brand-new-fire-station/|title=Dagenham crews move into brand new fire station|publisher=London Fire Brigade|website=www.london-fire.gov.uk|date=26 January 2016}}</ref>}} The Civic Centre was opened on 16 October 1937 by [[Kingsley Wood|Sir Kingsley Wood]].<ref>\"Tribute to Local Government\", ''The [[Nottingham Evening Post]]'', 16 October 1937, p. 5.</ref> A later, 1964, extension to the civic centre was completed by his firm after Webber's death.{{sfn|Cherry|O'Brien|Pevsner|2007|p=152}}  \n\nAlso in 1936, Webber won a competition to build the parliamentary buildings in [[Southern Rhodesia]].<ref>[http://wiredspace.wits.ac.za/bitstream/handle/10539/18845/Journal%20of%20SAAI-December-1936-001-jpeg.pdf?sequence=18&isAllowed=y \"The South Africa Architectural Journal\"], p. 426.</ref>\n\nThe following year, he undertook the designs for [[Hammersmith Town Hall]] in King Street, [[Hammersmith]], London, which were completed in 1939.  Pevsner calls the town hall \"an unfortunate building\", regretting both the loss of the \"picturesque character\" of the area which occurred as a result of its construction, and the \"ill-judged\" extensions of the 1970s.{{sfn|Cherry|Pevsner|2002|p=208}} It became a Grade II listed building,<ref name=\"NHLE\">{{NHLE|num=1079785|desc=Hammersmith Town Hall|accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> together with the Civic Centre in Dagenham,<ref>{{NHLE|num=1064422|desc=Main Building and Council Chamber of Dagenham Civic Centre|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> in 1981.<ref name=\"NHLE\"/>\n\nWebber was appointed by the [[Royal Navy]] as the consulting architect for improvements to their barracks, [[HMNB Portsmouth]] and [[HMNB Devonport]], in 1947.<ref>\"Architect for Barracks Modernization\", ''[[The Hampshire Telegraph and Post]]'', 3 October 1947, p. 1.</ref>\n\nIn 1955 Webber undertook a \u00a31.5million rebuild of the [[Portsmouth Guildhall]], which had received substantial bomb damage during [[World War II|the war]].{{sfn|Groombridge|2017|p=??}} It was reopened by [[Elizabeth II]] on 10 June 1959.<ref>\"Guildhall rises from rubble\", ''Hampshire Telegraph and Post'', 22 March 1957, p. 3.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWebber married Gladys {{nee}} Bellis Roberts (1896\u20131984) on 22 November 1922 at [[Bow Church|St Mary and Holy Trinity Church]] in [[Stratford, London|Stratford]].<ref>''Church of England Marriages and Banns, 1754\u20131932'', London Metropolitan Archives, p. 89.</ref> They had a son named Geoffrey.{{sfn|Neal|2014|p=126}} On 25 June 1929 Webber was given the [[Freedom of the City of London]].<ref name=\"FREEDOM\"/> He was a president of the [[Eccentric Club]] during the 1940s,<ref>\"The Variety Stage\",''The Stage'', 21 April 1949, p. 3.</ref> and in 1960 he was made a companion of the entertainment charity, the [[Grand Order of Water Rats]].<ref>\"The Grand Order of Water Rats\", ''The Stage'', 7 January 1960, p. 13.</ref>\n\nWebber retired to [[Brighton]] in the 1950s.{{sfn|Neal|2014|p=128}} He was taken ill at his house, 2 Arundel Terrace, and died shortly after at the [[Royal Sussex County Hospital]] on 19 December 1963. His probate was set at \u00a318,611<ref name=\"PROBATE\"/> (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|18611|1963|r=-4}}}} in {{Inflation/year|UK}} adjusted for inflation).{{inflation-fn|UK}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book\n| last1= Cherry | first1 = Bridget\n| last2 = Pevsner | first2 = Nikolaus\n| authorlink1 = Bridget Cherry\n| authorlink2 = Nikolaus Pevsner\n| title = London 3: North West\n| series = The Buildings of England \n| year = 2002\n| url = https://www.worldcat.org/title/london-3-north-west/oclc/983761260&referer=brief_results\n| publisher = [[Yale University Press]]\n| location = New Haven, US and London \n| isbn = 978-0-300-09652-1 \n| ref = {{sfnRef|Cherry|Pevsner|2002}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1= Cherry | first1 = Bridget\n| last2 = O'Brien | first2 = Charles\n| last3 = Pevsner | first3 = Nikolaus\n| authorlink1 = Bridget Cherry\n| authorlink3 = Nikolaus Pevsner\n| title = London 5: East\n| series = The Buildings of England \n| year = 2007\n| url = https://www.worldcat.org/title/london-5-east/oclc/983755807&referer=brief_results\n| publisher = [[Yale University Press]]\n| location = New Haven, US and London \n| isbn = 978-0-300-10701-2  \n| ref = {{sfnRef|Cherry|O'Brien|Pevsner|2007}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last = Groombridge | first = Garth \n| title = Portsmouth in 50 buildings\n| year = 2017\n| url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rDMqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT73&lpg=PT73&dq=portsmouth+guildhall+e+berry+webber&source=bl&ots=x0IawyZ9zG&sig=ACfU3U17K1LC7TlYJ6i1LVTvfFltzXoC0A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjst8DGttjoAhXkQhUIHTMGACkQ6AEwAnoECAsQMg#v=onepage&q=portsmouth%20guildhall%20e%20berry%20webber&f=false\n| publisher = Amberley Publishing\n| location = Stroud, UK \n| isbn = 978-1-445-66406-4 \n| ref = {{sfnRef|Groombridge|2017}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = Neal | first1 = Peter \n| title = Story of Southampton\n| year = 2014\n| url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=sZtvAwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT195&ots=gVk-WaTxXx&dq=Reading%20Ernest%20Berry%20Webber&pg=PT195#v=onepage&q=Reading%20Ernest%20Berry%20Webber&f=false\n| publisher = The History Press\n| location = Stroud, UK \n| isbn = 978-0-750-95861-5\n| ref = {{sfnRef|Neal|2014}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = O'Brien | first1 = Charles\n| last2 = Pevsner | first2 = Nikolaus\n| authorlink2 = Nikolaus Pevsner\n| title = Bedfordshire, Huntingdonshire and Peterborough\n| series = The Buildings of England \n| year = 2014\n| url = https://www.worldcat.org/title/bedfordshire-huntingdonshire-and-peterborough-the-buildings-of-england/oclc/881612533&referer=brief_results\n| publisher = [[Yale University Press]]\n| location = New Haven, US and London \n| isbn = 978-0-300-20821-4  \n| ref = {{sfnRef|O'Brien|Pevsner|2014}}\n}}\n* {{cite book\n| last1 = O'Brien | first1 = Charles\n| last2 = Bailey | first2 = Bruce \n| last3 = Pevsner | first3 = Nikolaus\n| last4 = Lloyd | first4 = David W. \n| authorlink3 = Nikolaus Pevsner\n| title = Hampshire: South\n| series = The Buildings of England \n| year = 2018\n| url = https://www.worldcat.org/title/hampshire-south/oclc/1078192100?referer=br&ht=edition \n| publisher = [[Yale University Press]]\n| location = New Haven, US and London \n| isbn = 978-0-300-18507-2  \n| ref = {{sfnRef|O'Brien|Bailey|Pevsner|Lloyd|2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Webber, Ernest Berry}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English architects]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Unbalanced quotes in ref name or illegal character. - Bogus image options)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernest_Berry_Webber"}
{"title_page": "A Crow Looked at Me", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = A Crow Looked at Me\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Mount Eerie]]\n| cover      = Mount Eerie - A Crow Looked at Me.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        = Male hand holding [[Joanne Kyger]] poem \"Night Palace\" in the foreground. Background is of a house illuminated by an orange light\n| released   = {{startdate|2017|3|24}}\n| recorded   = August 31&nbsp;\u2013 December 6, 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Home recording]], [[Anacortes, Washington]]<ref name=\"now\"/>\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Indie folk]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=41|s=30}}\n| label      = P.W. Elverum & Sun\n| producer   = [[Phil Elverum]]\n| prev_title = [[Sauna (Mount Eerie album)|Sauna]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = [[Now Only]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = A Crow Looked at Me\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Real Death\n | single1date = January 18, 2017\n | single2     = Ravens\n | single2date = February 15, 2017\n}}\n}}\n'''''A Crow Looked at Me''''' is the eighth studio album by [[Mount Eerie]], the solo project of American musician [[Phil Elverum]]. The album is a [[concept album]] about the death of Elverum's wife, the Canadian cartoonist and musician [[Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e]]. The album was written and produced entirely by Elverum, who recorded the album using mostly Castr\u00e9e's instruments in the room in which she died and features minimal production and sparse instrumentation which was a departure from Elverum's previous work. ''A Crow Looked at Me'' was released on March 24, 2017 on Elverum's own label, P.W. Elverum & Sun.\n\nPrior to the release of the album, Elverum released two singles, \"Real Death\" and \"Ravens\", released on January 18, 2017, and February 15, 2017, respectively. Both songs deal with Castr\u00e9e's death and Elverum dealing with the aftermath. Both songs received critical acclaim each earning best new track by [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] with \"Real Death\" being number three on the \"100 Best Songs of 2017\" list. ''A Crow Looked at Me'' was an immediate and widespread critical success, appearing on numerous best of year lists. In the years following its release, the album has appeared in multiple best of decade lists. Some critics found that due to the nature of the album, reviewing it was difficult and disrespectful.\n\n==Background and composition==\n[[File:Gary Snyder, Mark Kozelek, Julie Doiron, Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd.jpg|thumb|250x250px|left|From left to right: Poet Gary Snyder, American musician Mark Kozelek, Norwegian writter Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd and Canadian singer-songwriter Julie Doiron all of which Phil Elverum took inspiration from]]\n\nIn 2015, [[Phil Elverum]]'s wife, Canadian cartoonist and musician [[Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e]], was diagnosed with [[pancreatic cancer]] four months after the birth of their first child. Castr\u00e9e died at their home on July 9, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yoo|first1=Noah|title=Genevi\u00e8ve Elverum Has Died|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/66697-genevieve-elverum-has-died|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=July 10, 2016|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Taking inspiration from the [[Gary Snyder]] poem \"Go Now\",<ref name=\"exclaim_gormely\">{{cite web |last1=Gormely |first1=Ian |title=Microphones, Mount Eerie and Melancholy: The Career of Phil Elverum |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/microphones_mount_eerie_and_melancholy_the_career_of_phil_elverum |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate= November 16, 2018 |date=November 5, 2018}}</ref> Elverum realised that he did not have to find any meaning in Castr\u00e9e's death but could write songs that described the experience.<ref name=\"atlantic\">{{cite web |last1=Kornhaber |first1=Spencer |title=The Pointlessness and Promise of Art After Death |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/03/mount-eerie-now-only-interview-phil-elverum/555485/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> He also found inspiration in the work of Canadian singer-songwriter [[Julie Doiron]], American rock band [[Sun Kil Moon]] and Norwegian author [[Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd]].<ref name=\"pearce\">{{cite web |last1=Pearce |first1=Sheldon |title=Mount Eerie Announces New Album, Shares New Song \"Real Death\" |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/70642-mount-eerie-announces-new-album-shares-new-song-real-death-listen/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=November 21, 2018 |date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Elverum recorded the album from August 31, 2016 to December 6 of the same year.<ref name=\"Folk radio\"/> He wrote the songs over a six-week period<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> starting in September 2016.<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\">{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Jayson |title=Death Is Real: Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Copes With Unspeakable Tragedy |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/profile/10034-death-is-real-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-copes-with-unspeakable-tragedy/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 13, 2017}}</ref> Utilising some notes that he had written during Castr\u00e9e's illness and treatment,<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/> He wrote the lyrics down longhand on her notepaper<ref name=\"tmt\">{{cite web |last1=Lin |first1=Marvin |title=Mount Eerie - A Crow Looked At Me |url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/mount-eerie-crow-looked-me |website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]| date=2017 |accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> and recorded the songs in the room where she died using an acoustic guitar, one microphone and a laptop computer<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/> alongside some of Castr\u00e9e's own instruments.<ref name=\"cos\"/> Since he had become the primary carer for his daughter, Elverum recorded the songs at night while his daughter was asleep or during times when she was visiting friends.<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/> Elverum recorded the songs from August 31, to December 6, 2016.<ref name=\"Folk radio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.folkradio.co.uk/2017/01/mount-eerie-real-death/|title=Mount Eerie Shares Song From New Album: Real Death|website=Folk Radio|last=Gallacher|first=Alex|date=January 26, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> He stated that the songs \"poured out quickly in the fall, watching the days grey over and watching the neighbors across the alley tear down and rebuild their house\", making and releasing the record in order to \"multiply my voice saying that I love her. I want it known.\"<ref name=\"fact_announce\">{{cite web |last1=Bowe |first1=Miles |title=Mount Eerie addresses his wife's death on new album A Crow Looked At Me |url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/01/25/mount-eerie-phil-elverum-crow-looked-at-me-real-death/ |website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Elverum found recording process as positive, calling it \"therapeutic\" and saying it felt as if he was \"hanging out with her [Castr\u00e9e]\" and feeling by the end as if he had healed.<ref name=\"Mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2997421/phil-elverum-mount-eerie-interview/|title=Phil Elverum On Life, Death And Meaninglessness|publisher=[[MTV]]|last=Garvey|first=Meghan|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"kexp\">{{cite web|url=https://kexp.org/read/2020/2/13/music-heals-phil-elverum-expressing-grief-through-music-and-remembering-his-late-wife-genevieve-castree/|title=Music Heals: Phil Elverum on Expressing Grief Through Music and Remembering His Late Wife Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e|website=Kexp|last=Fox|first=Emily|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n[[File:Mount_Eerie,_Real_Death.ogg|thumb|260x300px|right|The album opener introduces the theme that \"death is real\" which Elverum once said \"could be the name\" of the album.<ref name=\"fact_announce\" />]]\n\nThe lyrics are delivered in a [[Sprechgesang|speak singing]] style and conversational manner and deal with Castr\u00e9e's illness and death, and Elverum's ensuing grief, which is the thematic concept of the album.<ref name=\"exclaim_after\">{{cite web |last1=Gormely |first1=Ian |title=Phil Elverum Reveals How Mount Eerie Live Album '(After)' Puts Mourning to Rest |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/phil_elverum_reveals_how_mount_eerie_live_album_after_puts_mourning_to_rest |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=September 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/><ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|last1=Gotrich|first1=Lars|title=Stream Mount Eerie's Heartbreaking New Album, 'A Crow Looked At Me'|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/03/16/520013269/first-listen-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me |publisher=[[NPR]]|date=March 16, 2017|accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SC\"/> The words take the form of a diary with Elverum intending for each song to reflect a time in his grieving, and include references to specific events and dates throughout. Elverum said that \"each song is anchored to a very specific moment\". Writer Thomas Britt wrote that this showcases \"the way that death hangs over each day that follows\".<ref name=\"Stosuy\" /><ref name=\"popmatters\"/> Each song refers to Castr\u00e9e, sometimes directly by name, Elverum frequently uses pronouns such as \"our\" when referring to Castr\u00e9e despite her absence, one critic noted that this is because Elverum \"struggles to adjust to the undesired change\".<ref name=\"tmt\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\" /> The final song \"Crow\" is however addressed prominently to their daughter.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |last1=Caramanica |first1=Jon |title=The Sound of Sadness Overwhelms and Inspires Mount Eerie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/22/arts/music/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate= November 28, 2018 |date=March 22, 2017}}</ref> The lyrics have been described to \"combine emotional intimacy and tonal frankness to a degree rarely heard in contemporary music\" and as \"unspooling pieces of prose\"<ref name=\"New Yorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/in-a-room-listening-to-phil-elverum-sing-about-his-wifes-death|title=In A Room Listening To Phil Elverum Sing About His Wife's Death|website=[[The New Yorker]]|last=Baker|first=Peter C|date=September 6, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/nov/14/mount-eerie-review-phil-elverum|title=Mount Eerie review \u2013 truth defeats beauty on stark songs of death|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Hann|first=Michael|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref> The songwriting has been described as \"brilliant examples of breaking the fourth wall\" and that the term itself does not align with the style of the material claiming it's \"too precise\", noting the blurred lines \"between singing, speaking and raw emotional data dump.\"<ref name=\"berkle\">{{cite web|url=https://online.berklee.edu/takenote/mount-eerie-expressing-emptiness-in-songwriting/|title=Death is Real: Mount Eerie and the Art of Expressing 'Emptiness' through Songwriting|publisher=[[Berklee]]|last=Zavada|first=Eric|date=2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt\"/>\n\nOpening track \"Real Death\" features spoken-word Esque vocals which are \"whispered from a void of hurt\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.treblezine.com/34446-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review/|title=Mount Eerie A Crow Looked At Me Review|website=Treblezine|last=Roesler|first=Brian|date=2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The opening lyrics are \"death is real\" and this theme continues throughout the record, as well as the theme of the album not being an artistic statement, with Phillip Green of Cisternyard Media speculating the reason behinds Elverum's aversion is that to do so \"would be taking advantage of Genevieve\u2019s passing\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/><ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\" /> The song also refers to Elverum opening mail packages addressed to Castr\u00e9e that were delivered after her death, with one critic saying that the moment \"limns the space between the living and the dead\"<ref name=\"nyt\"/> Elverum discusses scattering Castr\u00e9e's ashes and the house they intended to build on \"Seaweed\". The song also introduces the theme of Castr\u00e9e's \"Spiritual omnipresence\" and Elverum remembering her beyond the physical, choosing to immortalize her as the sunset, instead of as ashes.<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> Writer Molly Beauchemin stated that the song \"stands apart for its crushing invocation of nature as a place of solace and refuge\u2013 a place to see purpose in the midst of loss\"<ref name=\"Garden\">{{cite web|url=https://gardencollage.com/heal/mind-spirit/mount-eeries-seaweed-heartbreaking-reflection-love-death-nature/|title=Mount Eerie\u2019s \"Seaweed\" Is A Heartbreaking Reflection on Love, Death, and Nature|magazine=Garden Collage|last=Beauchemin|first=Molly|date=May 28, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> \"Ravens\" describes Elverum giving away Castr\u00e9e's clothes.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> \"Ravens\" standing apart from the other songs features multiple tempo changes.{{efn|\"Soria Moria\" also features tempo changes.<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/>}}<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> Sam Sodomsky of Pitchfork called the song a \"seven-minute exploration of the horrors of this world\".<ref name=\"pitchfork ravens\" /> The track \"Forest Fire\" describes Elverum's feelings of death, decay, and absurdity in relation to the world around him. As well as apologizing to Castr\u00e9e for attempting to move on.<ref name=\"nyt2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/04/magazine/new-sentences-from-forest-fire-by-mount-eerie.html|title=New Sentences: From 'Forest Fire,' by Mount Eerie|website=[[The New York Times]]|last=Abebe|first=Nitsuh|date=April 4, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"No ripcord\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.noripcord.com/reviews/music/mount-eerie/crow-looked-me|title=A Crow Looked at Me|website=No Ripcord|last=Smith|first=Matthew|date=March 23, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> \"Swims\" details Elverum's experiences with [[grief counseling]] and the sudden death of his counselor in light of Castr\u00e9e's death. It features minimal guitars, simple piano chords and what has been described as \"Elverum's most naked vocal performance\".<ref name=\"npr\" /> \n\n[[Image:Theodor Kittelsen, Soria Moria.jpg|right|thumb|260x280px|''Soria Moria'' by [[Theodor Kittelsen]] (1881) inspired the track by the same name]]\n\n\"My Chasm\" describe Elverum's difficulty in talking about his loss in public which has been described as \"a tribute to their everlasting love\".<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"fact_announce\" /> \"When I Take the Garbage Out At Night\" invokes mundane imagery with one writer drawing comparisons to [[Sun Kil Moon]]'s ''[[Benji (album)|Benji]]''.<ref name=\"SC\"/> \"Emptiness pt. 2\" deals with the idea of \"conceptual emptiness\". Thomas Britt of [[PopMatters]] wrote that \"This self-reflexive commentary reframes even the most powerful pictures of wind-hewn, frosted, blackened solitude in the past Microphones/Mount Eerie songbook as products of comparative comfort; luxuries of imagination\".<ref name=\"now\">{{cite news|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/mount-eerie-album-review/|title=Mount Eerie's A Crow Looked At Me is unsettlingly personal| newspaper=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]|last=Greene|first=Sarah|date=March 27, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"popmatters\" /> Elverum discusses the fading familiar memories of Castr\u00e9e on the song \"Toothbrush/Trash\" which has been described as a \"horrible realization that time will not relent\".<ref name=\"nyt\"/> Its sudden sound cue of a door closing (which elverum recorded himself) was described by Brian Roesler as \"a haunted chamber of memory and connection that now seems more real than ever\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> The track \"Soria Moria\" takes its name from a painting of the [[Soria Moria Castle|same name]] by [[Theodor Kittelsen]], incorporates elements of [[black metal]]<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> and details Elverum's relationship with Castr\u00e9e before her death as well as referencing Elverum's time in a Norwegian cabin, in which he wrote his 2008 album [[Dawn (Mount Eerie album)|Dawn]].<ref name=\"brainwashed\">{{cite web|url=https://brainwashed.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7529:phil-elverum-qdawn-winter-journalq&catid=17:books&Itemid=134|title=Phil Elverum, \"Dawn: Winter Journal\"|website=Brainwash|last=Spencer|first=Matthew|date=May 2, 2009|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"npr\" /> The final song \"Crow\" is addressed to his daughter as Elverum ponders all the ways in which Castr\u00e9e lives on, such as a crow that was following them on a hike in the Pacific Northwest. It's the only song to have references to events beyond Elverum's life, as he describes the world as \"Smoldering and fascist\", comments which were inspired by the [[2016 United States presidential election]].<ref name=\"Mtv\"/> The song has been described as an \"epilogue of sorts\" which \"offers a new and hopeful perspective\" and as \"One of the more poetic tracks on the album\"<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\">{{cite web|url=https://cisternyard.com/2017/03/30/24689/|title=\"A Crow Looked at Me\" By Mount Eerie-An Album Review|website=Cistern Yard|last=Greene|first=Phillip|date=March 30, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> \n\nMany of the lyrics feature references to nature<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> with one reviewer noting that \"tragedy hasn't stopped [Elverum] from noticing the world; if anything, it seems to have pried his eyes open for good.\"<ref name=\"Powell\"/> Musically, the album is reminiscent of his 2008 work ''[[Lost Wisdom]]''<ref name=\"now\" /> with the songs featuring sparse instrumentation with acoustic guitar and simple percussion<ref name=\"portlandmercury\">{{cite web |last1=Salmon |first1=Ben |title=On A Crow Looked at Me, Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Processes the Death of His Wife |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/music/2017/04/12/18944358/on-a-crow-looked-at-me-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-processes-the-death-of-his-wife |website=[[The Portland Mercury|Portland Mercury]] |accessdate=December 18, 2018 |date=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/> which Elverum referred to as \"barely music\".<ref name=\"Powell\"/> Elverum wanted to release the album quickly, so he used minimal [[Record producer|production]].<ref name=\"beatroute\">{{cite web |title=A Crow Looked at Me Gives Mount Eerie a Worthy Eulogy |url=https://archive.beatroute.ca/2017/08/12/crow-looked-gives-mount-eerie-worthy-eulogy/ |website=Beatroute|date=August 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\nElverum considered not releasing the album at all, or changing his band name entirely but ultimately decided to do neither.<ref name=\"Stosuy\">{{cite web |last1=Stosuy |first1=Brandon |title=Phil Elverum on creating art from grief |url=https://thecreativeindependent.com/people/phil-elverum-on-creating-art-from-grief/ |website=The Creative Independent |accessdate=December 10, 2018 |date=March 15, 2017}}</ref> He had originally planned for a small scale release of the record on his own website, but as the album took shape he felt that it was good and wanted it to reach a wider audience.<ref name=\"noisey\">{{cite web |last1=Currin |first1=Grayson |title=How Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Faced Grief on His Devastating New Album |url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/wn9z54/a-conversation-with-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-on-his-devastating-new-album |website=[[Vice_(magazine)#Website|Vice]]|date=March 28, 2017 |accessdate=November 19, 2018}}</ref> Despite this he still found releasing the album and promoting it to be \"gross and weird from a lot of perspectives\".<ref name=\"Stosuy\" /> On January 5, 2017, he announced that he would go on tour, and release a new album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yoo|first1=Noah|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/70707-phil-elverum-please-dont-come-to-tomorrows-mount-eerie-show/|title=Phil Elverum: \"Please Don't Come\" to Tomorrow's Mount Eerie Show|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=January 5, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> The next day, he played his first concert since September 2014 at a record store in [[Anacortes, Washington]]. Elverum, while choosing to perform, also asked fans to stay away as the response was \"overwhelming\" and the store could only hold 50 people.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Strauss|first1=Matthew|title=Mount Eerie Performing New Music at First Show in 2 Years|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/70637-mount-eerie-performing-new-music-at-first-show-in-2-years/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=December 30, 2016|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Elverum performed the show with his eyes closed and left immediately afterwards.<ref name=\"larecord\">{{cite web |last1=Child |first1=Tom |title=Mount Eerie: Stay Sincere |url=http://larecord.com/archive/2017/04/10/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-phil-elverum-interview |website=[[L.A. Record]] |accessdate= November 21, 2018 |date=April 10, 2017}}</ref> The first single from ''A Crow Looked at Me'', \"Real Death\", was released on P.W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd.'s [[SoundCloud]] page on January 18, 2017, to widespread acclaim, netting the \"Best New Track\" distinction from [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Currin|first1=Grayson|title=\"Real Death\" by Mount Eerie Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/18708-mount-eerie-real-death/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"paste single\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/mount-eerie/mount-eerie-releases-music-video-for-ravens-announ/|title=Mount Eerie Releases Devastating \"Ravens\" Video, Announces West Coast Tour Dates|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|last=Rohrback|first=Paul|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The second single, \"Ravens\", was released on February 15, 2017, alongside a music video uploaded to Mount Eerie's official [[YouTube]] account, again earning the \"Best New Track\" distinction from ''Pitchfork'', writing that \"Elverum makes no attempts to find metaphor or meaning; when he sees two ravens flying overhead, he knows it's an omen, but he can't say what for.\"<ref name=\"pitchfork ravens\">{{cite web|last1=Sodomsky|first1=Sam|title=\"Ravens\" by Mount Eerie Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/18780-mount-eerie-ravens/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"paste single\"/> The cover of the album features a photograph of the [[Joanne Kyger]]{{efn|Kyger would die of lung cancer two days before the album's release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/books/article/Joanne-Kyger-trailblazing-Beat-poet-dies-at-82-11021799.php|title=Joanne Kyger, trailblazing Beat poet, dies at 82|author=John McMurtie|accessdate=March 25, 2017|date=March 23, 2017|publisher=[[San Francisco Gate]]}}</ref>}} poem \"Night Palace\", which Castr\u00e9e had pinned above her desk.<ref name=\"observer\">{{cite web |last1=Joffe |first1=Justin |title=Beyond Grief: How Mount Eerie Made an Album About His Wife's Death |url=https://observer.com/2017/03/mount-eerie-phil-elverum-interview/ |website=[[observer.com|Observer]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> Elverum had taken the photograph while he was cleaning out her room after she died and realised that the poem encapsulated the theme of the album. Castr\u00e9e's copy of [[Herg\u00e9]]'s ''[[Tintin in Tibet]]'' can be seen in the background.<ref name=\"bandcamp\">{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Erin Lyndal |title=Mount Eerie on Intimate Grief and the Creative Impulse |url=https://daily.bandcamp.com/2017/03/21/mount-eerie-interview/ |publisher=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=November 29, 2018|date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the release of the album, Elverum embarked on a North American tour in September 2017, playing solo shows accompanied only by his acoustic guitar in intimate venues that included \"concert halls, churches, and theaters\".<ref name=\"geslani\">{{cite web |last1=Geslani |first1=Michelle |title=Mount Eerie announces North American tour dates |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/05/mount-eerie-announces-north-american-tour-dates/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=May 31, 2017}}</ref> The tour was extended to include Europe in November 2017.<ref name=\"TMTsmart\">{{cite web |last1=Smart |first1=Dan |title=Mount Eerie announces European tour dates in November |url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/news/mount-eerie-announces-european-tour-dates-november |website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=September 20, 2017}}</ref> While performing at [[Jacobikerk]] as part of [[Le Guess Who?]] festival in [[Utrecht]], a sound engineer recorded Elverum's set without his knowledge. Elverum liked the recording so much that it was subsequently released as the live album ''[[(after)]]'' in 2018.<ref name=\"pitchforkafter\">{{cite web |last=Reese |first=Nathan |title=Mount Eerie: (after) |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/mount-eerie-after/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=October 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Critical Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 8.8/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/8559/Mount-Eerie-A-Crow-Looked-at-Me.aspx|title=A Crow Looked at Me by Mount Eerie reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| MC = 93/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/a-crow-looked-at-me/mount-eerie|title=Reviews and Tracks for A Crow Looked at Me by Mount Eerie|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-crow-looked-at-me-mw0003032380|title=A Crow Looked at Me \u2013 Mount Eerie|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Phares|first=Heather|date=2017|accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/live/craig-finn-mount-eerie-pallbearer-and-more-weeks-m-252416|title=Mount Eerie confronts death on its saddest album to date|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Corcoran|first=Nina|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev3score = A\u2212<ref name=\"cos\">{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2017/03/album-review-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie \u2013 A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Sackllah|first=David|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev4score = 9/10<ref name=\"exclaimfenech\">{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/mount_eerie-a_crow_looked_at_me|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[Exclaim!]]|last=Fenech|first=Zach|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|last=Male|first=Andrew|issue=284|date=July 2017|page=91}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n| rev6score = 9.2/10<ref name=\"paste\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/03/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review.html|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked At Me Review|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|last=Fink|first=Matt|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 9.0/10<ref name=\"Powell\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22970-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked At Me|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Powell|first=Mike|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev8Score = 10/10<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[PopMatters]]|last=Britt|first=Thomas|date=March 20, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev9score = 9/10<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|journal=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|issue=240|date=May 2017|page=35}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]''\n| rev10score = A<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/8xvyqv/expert-witness-with-robert-christgau-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me|title=Robert Christgau on Mount Eerie's 'A Crow Looked at Me,' a Brutal Listen|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=January 27, 2018|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''A Crow Looked at Me'' received widespread critical acclaim upon release. At ''[[Metacritic]]'', which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from [[music critic]]s, the album has received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 93, indicating \"universal acclaim\", based on 18 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> Aggregator ''[[AnyDecentMusic?]]'' gave ''A Crow Looked At Me'' 8.8 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref name=\"adm\"/> Elverum found this \"reaffirming\" although was frustrated by those who viewed it as a tribute.<ref name=\"atlantic\"/> Heather Phares from [[AllMusic]] called the album \"remarkably powerful and pure\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''{{'}}s David Sackllah said that it was \"overwhelming and humbling\" and wrote that \"A Crow Looked at Me stands as a remarkable example of the restorative power of music, an intimate display of love, daring both in concept and execution.\"<ref name=\"cos\"/> Zack Fenech from ''[[Exclaim!]]'' said that \"this record possesses immense power to make listeners reflect on their own relationships and mortality. A Crow Looked at Me is a grim memento of the grand injustice of losing those most precious to us.\"<ref name=\"exclaimfenech\"/> ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''{{'}}s Matt Fink said that it was \"beautifully and simply arranged, but it is not an entertaining album to listen to in any conventional sense, nor can it be shaken off easily. It is, however, the kind of album that makes all others seem frivolous\" and that \"there is no album quite like it.\"<ref name=\"paste\"/>\n\nBen Malkin from GIGsoup described the album \"art in its most pure, human form\", a \"showcase of weakness and cruel reality, prose of lost love,\" and \"perhaps the saddest album ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gigsoupmusic.com/reviews/album-reviews/mount-eerie-crow-looked/|title=Mount Eerie 'A Crow Looked at Me'|website=Gigsoup|last=Malkin|first=Ben|date=April 3, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In his review for ''[[Spectrum Culture]]'' John Paul said that \"Heartbreaking doesn\u2019t even begin to describe ''A Crow Looked at Me''\" and described the album as \"pure grief delivered in a voice in which you can hear the weight of loss\".<ref name=\"SC\">{{Cite web|url=https://spectrumculture.com/2017/03/28/mount-eerie/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|website=[[Spectrum Culture]]|last=Paul|first=John|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Sarah Greene, writing for ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now Toronto]]'' described ''A Crow Looked At Me'' as \"a lovingly crafted album, with gentle melodies that linger in the air, pretty, memorable guitar lines and a subtle but persistent approach to percussion\" and concluded that despite it may being an uncomfortable and harrowing listen it was also a \"tribute to an amazing 13-year love story\".<ref name=\"now\" /> Brian Roesler, from Treblezine, despite enjoying the record considerably, demanded that readers \"Don\u2019t call it art. Don\u2019t call it music even. Call it a documentation of suffering and loss as an experience, and treat it as such\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/>{{efn|A sentiment echoed by Elverum himself.<ref name=\"Powell\"/>}} In a [[essay]] written for [[The Spinoff]], Murdoch Stephens crowned Elverum \"the saddest musician in the world\", compared ''A Crow Looked At Me'' to the poetry of [[Auschwitz]] survivor [[Primo Levi]] and pondered how the listener should interact with a piece of art of such a visceral nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/music/15-01-2018/how-to-listen-to-mount-eerie-the-saddest-musician-in-the-world/|title=How to listen to Mount Eerie, the saddest musician in the world|website=[[The Spinoff]]|last=Stephens|first=Murdoch|date=January 15, 2018|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Elverum would go on to denounce the title, calling it absurd and that he sought out to inject beauty into the record.<ref name=\"atlantic\"/>\n\nSome reviewers said that it was difficult to review the album. In his positive review for ''[[Drowned in Sound]]'', JR Moores did not give the album a score because \"even awarding this work the full ten-out-of-ten would feel too callous given the tragic circumstances of the record's gestation and its heartbreaking subject matter.\"<ref name=\"dis\">{{cite web |last1=Moores |first1=JR |title=Mount Eerie - A Crow Looked at Me |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/19863/reviews/4150889 |website=[[Drowned in Sound]] |accessdate=November 18, 2018 |date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> Reviewer Matthew Smith of ''No Ripcord'' said that \"assigning a score to a project like this is reductive...it's almost insulting to rank something as open and raw as this.\"<ref name=\"noripcord\">{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Matthew |title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me |url=http://www.noripcord.com/reviews/music/mount-eerie/crow-looked-me |website=No Ripcord |accessdate=December 5, 2018 |date=March 23, 2017}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]'' reviewer Thomas Britt called the album a \"masterpiece\" but noted that it went beyond \"the limits of conventional music criticism.\"<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> Marvin Lin from ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]'' did score the album but said that his rating meant \"absolutely nothing\".<ref name=\"tmt\"/>\n\n===Accolades===\n''A Crow Looked at Me'' appeared on numerous year-end top lists.<ref name=\"Mc3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-released-in-2017|title=The Best Albums Of 2017|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Such as [[The Atlantic]],<ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/> [[Consequence of Sound]],<ref name=\"COS\"/> Earbuddy,<ref name=\"Earbuddy\"/> [[Exclaim!]],<ref name=\"Exclaim\"/> [[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]<ref name=\"paste_best\"/> and [[Tiny Mix Tapes]]<ref name=\"TMT 2\"/>. The lead single \"Real Death\" was third on Pitchfork's list of 100 \"Best Songs\" of 2017.<ref name=\"Pitchfork Best\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-100-best-songs-of-2017/?page=9|title=The 100 Best Songs of 2017|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|date=December 9, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref> Metacritic, which collates reviews of music albums, named it the second best-reviewed album of 2017<ref name=\"Mc3\"/> and the seventh best reviewed album of decade.<ref name=\"Mc2\" />{{efn|Its appearance on the list made it the highest rated [[Contemporary Folk Music|folk]] album of the decade.<ref name=\"Mc2\" />}} According to [[Acclaimed Music]], the album is eleventh most critically album of 2017, eightieth of the 2010s and eight hundred twenty-sixth of all time.<ref name=\"Acclaimed Music\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A5951.htm|title=Mount Eerie A Crow Looked at Me|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>{{efn|The tenth highest ranking for an [[Indie Folk]] album.<ref name=\"Acclaimed Music2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/genre/genre261.htm|title=Top Indie Folk Albums|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>}} The album is the eleventh highest rated album on [[AnyDecentMusic?]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/chart/AllTime.aspx|title=All Time Chart|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> \n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|+Year-end lists\n|-\n! Publication\n! Accolade\n! Rank\n|-\n|''[[The Atlantic]]''\n| The 10 Best Albums of 2017\n| 6<ref name=\"atlanticbest\">{{cite web |last1=Kornhaber |first1=Spencer |title=The 10 Best Albums of 2017 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/12/best-albums-2017/547451/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]''\n| Clash Albums Of The Year 2017\n| 54<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/clash-albums-of-the-year-2017|title=Clash Albums Of The Year 2017|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|last1=Clash Staff|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| Top 50 Albums of 2017\n| 8<ref name=\"COS\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/12/top-50-albums-of-2017/5/|title=Top 50 Albums of 2017|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last1=Cos Staff|date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Earbuddy''\n| Earbuddy\u2019s 100 Best Albums of 2017\n| 1<ref name=\"Earbuddy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.earbuddy.net/70003/earbuddys-100-best-albums-of-2017.html/albums-of-the-year|title=Earbuddy\u2019s 100 Best Albums of 2017|website=Earbuddy|last=Krenn|first=Nick|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| Top 10 Folk and Country Albums of 2017\n| 2<ref name=\"Exclaim\">{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/exclaim_s_top_10_folk_and_country_albums-best_of_2017/page/2|title=Top 10 Folk and Country Albums of 2017|last=Staff|first=Exclaim!|work=Exclaim!|date=December 4, 2017|accessdate=Jan 10, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 14<ref name=\"fact_best\">{{cite web |last1=Horner |first1=Al |title=The 50 best albums of 2017 |url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/12/20/best-albums-2017/ |website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Guardian]]''\n| The Best Albums Of 2017\n| 47<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/05/the-best-albums-of-2017|last1=Guardian staff|title=The Best Albums Of 2017|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 5, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 9<ref name=\"paste_best\">{{cite web |last1=Paste staff |title=The 50 Best Albums of 2017 |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/11/the-50-best-albums-of-2017.html?p=5 |website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=November 27, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Pigeons & Planes]]''\n| Best Albums of 2017\n| 32<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2017/12/best-albums-of-2017-end-of-year/mount-eerie-crow-looked-at-me||title=Best Albums of 2017|website=[[Pigeons & Planes]]|last=Price|first=Joe|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Popmatters]]''\n| The 60 Best Albums of 2016\n| 24<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/60-best-albums-of-2017-2516162820.html|title=The 60 Best Albums of 2016|website=[[Popmatters]]|last=Britt|first=Thomas|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 14<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-50-best-albums-of-2017/?page=4|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2017|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|author=Pitchfork Staff|date=December 12, 2017|accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Noisey]]''\n| The 100 Best Albums of 2017\n| 23<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/pazbwn/noisey-100-best-albums-of-2017|title=The 100 Best Albums of 2017|website=[[Noisey]]|last=Joyce|first=Joyce|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''No Ripcord''\n| The Best Albums Of 2017\n| 11<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noripcord.com/features/best-albums-2017|title=The Best Albums Of 2017|website=No Ripcord|last=Coleman|first=David|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[NPR]]\n| The 50 Best Albums Of 2017\n| 31<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/12/12/568400855/the-50-best-albums-of-2017|title=The 50 Best Albums Of 2017|publisher=[[NPR]]|last1=NPR Staff|date=December 12, 2017|accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Spectrum Culture]]''\n| Top 20 Albums of 2017\n| 12<ref>{{cite web|url=https://spectrumculture.com/2017/12/19/top-20-albums-2017/2/|title=Top 20 Albums of 2017|website=[[Spectrum Culture]]|last1=Spectrum Culture Staff|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| 50 Best Album of 2016\n| 23<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/featured/50-best-albums-2017/|title=50 Best Album of 2016|website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|last=Berman|first=Judy|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Sputnikmusic]]''\n| Staff\u2019s Top 50 Albums of 2017\n| 14<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/blog/2017/12/21/staffs-top-50-albums-of-2017-30-11/|title=Staff\u2019s Top 50 Albums of 2017: 30 \u2013 11|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|last=Robertson|first=Alex|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Stereogum]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/featured/the-50-best-albums-of-2017/|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2017|author=''Stereogum'' Staff|work=[[Stereogum]]|date=December 5, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]''\n| 2017: Favorite 50 Music Releases\n| 1<ref name=\"TMT 2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/features/2017-favorite-50-music-releases?page=4|title=2017: Favorite 50 Music Releases|last1=TMT Staff|work=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]|date= December 18, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]''\n| Under the Radar\u2019s Top 100 Albums of 2017\n| 19<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.undertheradarmag.com/lists/under_the_radar_top_100_albums_of_2017/|title=Under the Radar\u2019s Top 100 Albums of 2017|website=[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]|last=Wyatt|first=Stephen|date=December 30, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| The Top 100 Albums of 2017\n| 15<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/22/pazz-jop-the-top-albums-and-singles-of-2017/|title=Pazz & Jop: It\u2019s Kendrick\u2019s and Cardi\u2019s World. We\u2019re All Just Living in It|website=[[The Village Voice]]|last1=The Editors|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|+Decade-end lists\n|-\n! Publication\n! List\n! Rank\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| ''Pitchfork''\n| The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s\n| {{center|45}}\n| {{center|<ref name=\"pitchfork2\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-200-best-albums-of-the-2010s/|title=The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=October 8, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''Metacritic''\n| The Best Albums of the Decade (2010\u20132019)\n|{{center|7}}\n| {{center|<ref name=\"Mc2\">{{cite web |last1=Dietz |first1=Jason |title=The Best Albums of the Decade (2010-19) |url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-of-the-decade-2010s |publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020 |date=November 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115223758/https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-of-the-decade-2010s |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n|- \n|''Tiny Mix Tapes''\n| 2010s: Favorite 100 Music Releases of the Decade\n|{{center|22}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/features/2010s-favorite-100-music-releases-decade?page=3|title=2010s: Favorite 100 Music Releases of the Decade|last1=TMT Staff|work=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks are written and produced by Phil Elverum.<ref name=\"dis\"/>\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 41:30\n| title1 = Real Death\n| length1 = 2:27\n| title2 = Seaweed\n| length2 = 3:01\n| title3 = Ravens\n| length3 = 6:39\n| title4 = Forest Fire\n| length4 = 4:15\n| title5 = Swims\n| length5 = 4:07\n| title6 = My Chasm\n| length6 = 2:22\n| title7 = When I Take Out the Garbage at Night\n| length7 = 2:25\n| title8 = Emptiness pt. 2\n| length8 = 3:28\n| title9 = Toothbrush/Trash\n| length9 = 3:52\n| title10 = Soria Moria\n| length10 = 6:33\n| title11 = Crow\n| length11 = 2:21\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from the album's liner notes.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|others=Phil Elverum|title=A Crow Looked at Me|year=2017|publisher=[[Phil Elverum #Career|P. W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd]]}}</ref>\n*Phil Elverum{{spaced en dash}} songwriting{{spaced en dash}} vocals{{spaced en dash}} production{{spaced en dash}}  acoustic guitar{{spaced en dash}} electric guitar{{spaced en dash}} drum machine{{spaced en dash}} bass{{spaced en dash}} piano{{spaced en dash}} accordion\n\n==Release history==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Region\n! Label\n! Format\n! Category\n! Reference\n|-\n| United States\n| P. W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd.\n| [[Phonograph record|Double LP]], [[Digital distribution|Digital Download]]\n| ELV040\n|<ref name=\"pwelverumandsun\">{{cite web|title=A Crow Looked At Me by Mount Eerie|url=http://www.pwelverumandsun.com/store#mounteerie|website=P.W. Elverum And Sun|accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Japan\n| P. W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd.\n| [[CD]]\n| EPCD101\n|<ref name=\"pwelverumandsun\"/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs master|1154519|A Crow Looked at Me}}\n\n{{Mount Eerie}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crow Looked at Me}}\n[[Category:2017 albums]]\n[[Category:Mount Eerie albums]]\n[[Category:P. W. Elverum & Sun albums]]\n[[Category:Concept albums]]\n[[Category:Works about cancer]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = A Crow Looked at Me\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Mount Eerie]]\n| cover      = Mount Eerie - A Crow Looked at Me.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        = Male hand holding [[Joanne Kyger]] poem \"Night Palace\" in the foreground. Background is of a house illuminated by an orange light\n| released   = {{startdate|2017|3|24}}\n| recorded   = August 31&nbsp;\u2013 December 6, 2016\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Home recording]], [[Anacortes, Washington]]<ref name=\"now\"/>\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Indie folk]]}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=41|s=30}}\n| label      = P.W. Elverum & Sun\n| producer   = [[Phil Elverum]]\n| prev_title = [[Sauna (Mount Eerie album)|Sauna]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = [[Now Only]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = A Crow Looked at Me\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Real Death\n | single1date = January 18, 2017\n | single2     = Ravens\n | single2date = February 15, 2017\n}}\n}}\n'''''A Crow Looked at Me''''' is the eighth studio album by [[Mount Eerie]], the solo project of American musician [[Phil Elverum]]. The album is a [[concept album]] about the death of Elverum's wife, the Canadian cartoonist and musician [[Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e]]. The album was written and produced entirely by Elverum, who recorded the album using mostly Castr\u00e9e's instruments in the room in which she died and features minimal production and sparse instrumentation which was a departure from Elverum's previous work. ''A Crow Looked at Me'' was released on March 24, 2017 on Elverum's own label, P.W. Elverum & Sun.\n\nPrior to the release of the album, Elverum released two singles, \"Real Death\" and \"Ravens\", released on January 18, 2017, and February 15, 2017, respectively. Both songs deal with Castr\u00e9e's death and Elverum dealing with the aftermath. Both songs received critical acclaim each earning best new track by [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] with \"Real Death\" being number three on the \"100 Best Songs of 2017\" list. ''A Crow Looked at Me'' was an immediate and widespread critical success, appearing on numerous best of year lists. In the years following its release, the album has appeared in multiple best of decade lists. Some critics found that due to the nature of the album, reviewing it was difficult and disrespectful.\n\n==Background and composition==\n[[File:Gary Snyder, Mark Kozelek, Julie Doiron, Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd.jpg|thumb|250x250px|left|From left to right: Poet Gary Snyder, American musician Mark Kozelek, Norwegian writter Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd and Canadian singer-songwriter Julie Doiron all of which Phil Elverum took inspiration from]]\n\nIn 2015, [[Phil Elverum]]'s wife, Canadian cartoonist and musician [[Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e]], was diagnosed with [[pancreatic cancer]] four months after the birth of their first child. Castr\u00e9e died at their home on July 9, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yoo|first1=Noah|title=Genevi\u00e8ve Elverum Has Died|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/66697-genevieve-elverum-has-died|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=July 10, 2016|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Taking inspiration from the [[Gary Snyder]] poem \"Go Now\",<ref name=\"exclaim_gormely\">{{cite web |last1=Gormely |first1=Ian |title=Microphones, Mount Eerie and Melancholy: The Career of Phil Elverum |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/microphones_mount_eerie_and_melancholy_the_career_of_phil_elverum |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate= November 16, 2018 |date=November 5, 2018}}</ref> Elverum realised that he did not have to find any meaning in Castr\u00e9e's death but could write songs that described the experience.<ref name=\"atlantic\">{{cite web |last1=Kornhaber |first1=Spencer |title=The Pointlessness and Promise of Art After Death |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/03/mount-eerie-now-only-interview-phil-elverum/555485/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> He also found inspiration in the work of Canadian singer-songwriter [[Julie Doiron]], American rock band [[Sun Kil Moon]] and Norwegian author [[Karl Ove Knausg\u00e5rd]].<ref name=\"pearce\">{{cite web |last1=Pearce |first1=Sheldon |title=Mount Eerie Announces New Album, Shares New Song \"Real Death\" |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/70642-mount-eerie-announces-new-album-shares-new-song-real-death-listen/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=November 21, 2018 |date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Elverum recorded the album from August 31, 2016 to December 6 of the same year.<ref name=\"Folk radio\"/> He wrote the songs over a six-week period<ref name=\"bandcamp\"/> starting in September 2016.<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\">{{cite web |last1=Greene |first1=Jayson |title=Death Is Real: Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Copes With Unspeakable Tragedy |url=https://pitchfork.com/features/profile/10034-death-is-real-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-copes-with-unspeakable-tragedy/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 13, 2017}}</ref> Utilising some notes that he had written during Castr\u00e9e's illness and treatment,<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/> He wrote the lyrics down longhand on her notepaper<ref name=\"tmt\">{{cite web |last1=Lin |first1=Marvin |title=Mount Eerie - A Crow Looked At Me |url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/music-review/mount-eerie-crow-looked-me |website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]| date=2017 |accessdate=November 28, 2018}}</ref> and recorded the songs in the room where she died using an acoustic guitar, one microphone and a laptop computer<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/> alongside some of Castr\u00e9e's own instruments.<ref name=\"cos\"/> Since he had become the primary carer for his daughter, Elverum recorded the songs at night while his daughter was asleep or during times when she was visiting friends.<ref name=\"pitchfork_profile\"/> Elverum recorded the songs from August 31, to December 6, 2016.<ref name=\"Folk radio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.folkradio.co.uk/2017/01/mount-eerie-real-death/|title=Mount Eerie Shares Song From New Album: Real Death|website=Folk Radio|last=Gallacher|first=Alex|date=January 26, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> He stated that the songs \"poured out quickly in the fall, watching the days grey over and watching the neighbors across the alley tear down and rebuild their house\", making and releasing the record in order to \"multiply my voice saying that I love her. I want it known.\"<ref name=\"fact_announce\">{{cite web |last1=Bowe |first1=Miles |title=Mount Eerie addresses his wife's death on new album A Crow Looked At Me |url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/01/25/mount-eerie-phil-elverum-crow-looked-at-me-real-death/ |website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=January 25, 2017}}</ref> Elverum found recording process as positive, calling it \"therapeutic\" and saying it felt as if he was \"hanging out with her [Castr\u00e9e]\" and feeling by the end as if he had healed.<ref name=\"Mtv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2997421/phil-elverum-mount-eerie-interview/|title=Phil Elverum On Life, Death And Meaninglessness|publisher=[[MTV]]|last=Garvey|first=Meghan|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"kexp\">{{cite web|url=https://kexp.org/read/2020/2/13/music-heals-phil-elverum-expressing-grief-through-music-and-remembering-his-late-wife-genevieve-castree/|title=Music Heals: Phil Elverum on Expressing Grief Through Music and Remembering His Late Wife Genevi\u00e8ve Castr\u00e9e|website=Kexp|last=Fox|first=Emily|date=February 13, 2020|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n[[File:Mount_Eerie,_Real_Death.ogg|thumb|260x300px|right|The album opener introduces the theme that \"death is real\" which Elverum once said \"could be the name\" of the album.<ref name=\"fact_announce\" />]]\n\nThe lyrics are delivered in a [[Sprechgesang|speak singing]] style and conversational manner and deal with Castr\u00e9e's illness and death, and Elverum's ensuing grief, which is the thematic concept of the album.<ref name=\"exclaim_after\">{{cite web |last1=Gormely |first1=Ian |title=Phil Elverum Reveals How Mount Eerie Live Album '(After)' Puts Mourning to Rest |url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/phil_elverum_reveals_how_mount_eerie_live_album_after_puts_mourning_to_rest |website=[[Exclaim!]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=September 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/><ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|last1=Gotrich|first1=Lars|title=Stream Mount Eerie's Heartbreaking New Album, 'A Crow Looked At Me'|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/03/16/520013269/first-listen-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me |publisher=[[NPR]]|date=March 16, 2017|accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SC\"/> The words take the form of a diary with Elverum intending for each song to reflect a time in his grieving, and include references to specific events and dates throughout. Elverum said that \"each song is anchored to a very specific moment\". Writer Thomas Britt wrote that this showcases \"the way that death hangs over each day that follows\".<ref name=\"Stosuy\" /><ref name=\"popmatters\"/> Each song refers to Castr\u00e9e, sometimes directly by name, Elverum frequently uses pronouns such as \"our\" when referring to Castr\u00e9e despite her absence, one critic noted that this is because Elverum \"struggles to adjust to the undesired change\".<ref name=\"tmt\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\" /> The final song \"Crow\" is however addressed prominently to their daughter.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |last1=Caramanica |first1=Jon |title=The Sound of Sadness Overwhelms and Inspires Mount Eerie |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/22/arts/music/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review.html|website=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate= November 28, 2018 |date=March 22, 2017}}</ref> The lyrics have been described to \"combine emotional intimacy and tonal frankness to a degree rarely heard in contemporary music\" and as \"unspooling pieces of prose\"<ref name=\"New Yorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/in-a-room-listening-to-phil-elverum-sing-about-his-wifes-death|title=In A Room Listening To Phil Elverum Sing About His Wife's Death|website=[[The New Yorker]]|last=Baker|first=Peter C|date=September 6, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/nov/14/mount-eerie-review-phil-elverum|title=Mount Eerie review \u2013 truth defeats beauty on stark songs of death|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Hann|first=Michael|date=November 14, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref> The songwriting has been described as \"brilliant examples of breaking the fourth wall\" and that the term itself does not align with the style of the material claiming it's \"too precise\", noting the blurred lines \"between singing, speaking and raw emotional data dump.\"<ref name=\"berkle\">{{cite web|url=https://online.berklee.edu/takenote/mount-eerie-expressing-emptiness-in-songwriting/|title=Death is Real: Mount Eerie and the Art of Expressing 'Emptiness' through Songwriting|publisher=[[Berklee]]|last=Zavada|first=Eric|date=2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"nyt\"/>\n\nOpening track \"Real Death\" features spoken-word Esque vocals which are \"whispered from a void of hurt\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.treblezine.com/34446-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review/|title=Mount Eerie A Crow Looked At Me Review|website=Treblezine|last=Roesler|first=Brian|date=2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The opening lyrics are \"death is real\" and this theme continues throughout the record, as well as the theme of the album not being an artistic statement, with Phillip Green of Cisternyard Media speculating the reason behinds Elverum's aversion is that to do so \"would be taking advantage of Genevieve\u2019s passing\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/><ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\" /> The song also refers to Elverum opening mail packages addressed to Castr\u00e9e that were delivered after her death, with one critic saying that the moment \"limns the space between the living and the dead\"<ref name=\"nyt\"/> Elverum discusses scattering Castr\u00e9e's ashes and the house they intended to build on \"Seaweed\". The song also introduces the theme of Castr\u00e9e's \"Spiritual omnipresence\" and Elverum remembering her beyond the physical, choosing to immortalize her as the sunset, instead of as ashes.<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> Writer Molly Beauchemin stated that the song \"stands apart for its crushing invocation of nature as a place of solace and refuge\u2013 a place to see purpose in the midst of loss\"<ref name=\"Garden\">{{cite web|url=https://gardencollage.com/heal/mind-spirit/mount-eeries-seaweed-heartbreaking-reflection-love-death-nature/|title=Mount Eerie\u2019s \"Seaweed\" Is A Heartbreaking Reflection on Love, Death, and Nature|magazine=Garden Collage|last=Beauchemin|first=Molly|date=May 28, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> \"Ravens\" describes Elverum giving away Castr\u00e9e's clothes.<ref name=\"nyt\"/> \"Ravens\" standing apart from the other songs features multiple tempo changes.{{efn|\"Soria Moria\" also features tempo changes.<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/>}}<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> Sam Sodomsky of Pitchfork called the song a \"seven-minute exploration of the horrors of this world\".<ref name=\"pitchfork ravens\" /> The track \"Forest Fire\" describes Elverum's feelings of death, decay, and absurdity in relation to the world around him. As well as apologizing to Castr\u00e9e for attempting to move on.<ref name=\"nyt2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/04/magazine/new-sentences-from-forest-fire-by-mount-eerie.html|title=New Sentences: From 'Forest Fire,' by Mount Eerie|website=[[The New York Times]]|last=Abebe|first=Nitsuh|date=April 4, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"No ripcord\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.noripcord.com/reviews/music/mount-eerie/crow-looked-me|title=A Crow Looked at Me|website=No Ripcord|last=Smith|first=Matthew|date=March 23, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> \"Swims\" details Elverum's experiences with [[grief counseling]] and the sudden death of his counselor in light of Castr\u00e9e's death. It features minimal guitars, simple piano chords and what has been described as \"Elverum's most naked vocal performance\".<ref name=\"npr\" /> \n\n[[Image:Theodor Kittelsen, Soria Moria.jpg|right|thumb|260x280px|''Soria Moria'' by [[Theodor Kittelsen]] (1881) inspired the track by the same name]]\n\n\"My Chasm\" describe Elverum's difficulty in talking about his loss in public which has been described as \"a tribute to their everlasting love\".<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"fact_announce\" /> \"When I Take the Garbage Out At Night\" invokes mundane imagery with one writer drawing comparisons to [[Sun Kil Moon]]'s ''[[Benji (album)|Benji]]''.<ref name=\"SC\"/> \"Emptiness pt. 2\" deals with the idea of \"conceptual emptiness\". Thomas Britt of [[PopMatters]] wrote that \"This self-reflexive commentary reframes even the most powerful pictures of wind-hewn, frosted, blackened solitude in the past Microphones/Mount Eerie songbook as products of comparative comfort; luxuries of imagination\".<ref name=\"now\">{{cite news|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/mount-eerie-album-review/|title=Mount Eerie's A Crow Looked At Me is unsettlingly personal| newspaper=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]|last=Greene|first=Sarah|date=March 27, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"popmatters\" /> Elverum discusses the fading familiar memories of Castr\u00e9e on the song \"Toothbrush/Trash\" which has been described as a \"horrible realization that time will not relent\".<ref name=\"nyt\"/> Its sudden sound cue of a door closing (which elverum recorded himself) was described by Brian Roesler as \"a haunted chamber of memory and connection that now seems more real than ever\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/> The track \"Soria Moria\" takes its name from a painting of the [[Soria Moria Castle|same name]] by [[Theodor Kittelsen]], incorporates elements of [[black metal]]<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> and details Elverum's relationship with Castr\u00e9e before her death as well as referencing Elverum's time in a Norwegian cabin, in which he wrote his 2008 album [[Dawn (Mount Eerie album)|Dawn]].<ref name=\"brainwashed\">{{cite web|url=https://brainwashed.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7529:phil-elverum-qdawn-winter-journalq&catid=17:books&Itemid=134|title=Phil Elverum, \"Dawn: Winter Journal\"|website=Brainwash|last=Spencer|first=Matthew|date=May 2, 2009|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"npr\" /> The final song \"Crow\" is addressed to his daughter as Elverum ponders all the ways in which Castr\u00e9e lives on, such as a crow that was following them on a hike in the Pacific Northwest. It's the only song to have references to events beyond Elverum's life, as he describes the world as \"Smoldering and fascist\", comments which were inspired by the [[2016 United States presidential election]].<ref name=\"Mtv\"/> The song has been described as an \"epilogue of sorts\" which \"offers a new and hopeful perspective\" and as \"One of the more poetic tracks on the album\"<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"cisternyard\">{{cite web|url=https://cisternyard.com/2017/03/30/24689/|title=\"A Crow Looked at Me\" By Mount Eerie-An Album Review|website=Cistern Yard|last=Greene|first=Phillip|date=March 30, 2017|accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> \n\nMany of the lyrics feature references to nature<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> with one reviewer noting that \"tragedy hasn't stopped [Elverum] from noticing the world; if anything, it seems to have pried his eyes open for good.\"<ref name=\"Powell\"/> Musically, the album is reminiscent of his 2008 work ''[[Lost Wisdom]]''<ref name=\"now\" /> with the songs featuring sparse instrumentation with acoustic guitar and simple percussion<ref name=\"portlandmercury\">{{cite web |last1=Salmon |first1=Ben |title=On A Crow Looked at Me, Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Processes the Death of His Wife |url=https://www.portlandmercury.com/music/2017/04/12/18944358/on-a-crow-looked-at-me-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-processes-the-death-of-his-wife |website=[[The Portland Mercury|Portland Mercury]] |accessdate=December 18, 2018 |date=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/> which Elverum referred to as \"barely music\".<ref name=\"Powell\"/> Elverum wanted to release the album quickly, so he used minimal [[Record producer|production]].<ref name=\"beatroute\">{{cite web |title=A Crow Looked at Me Gives Mount Eerie a Worthy Eulogy |url=https://archive.beatroute.ca/2017/08/12/crow-looked-gives-mount-eerie-worthy-eulogy/ |website=Beatroute|date=August 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release and promotion==\nElverum considered not releasing the album at all, or changing his band name entirely but ultimately decided to do neither.<ref name=\"Stosuy\">{{cite web |last1=Stosuy |first1=Brandon |title=Phil Elverum on creating art from grief |url=https://thecreativeindependent.com/people/phil-elverum-on-creating-art-from-grief/ |website=The Creative Independent |accessdate=December 10, 2018 |date=March 15, 2017}}</ref> He had originally planned for a small scale release of the record on his own website, but as the album took shape he felt that it was good and wanted it to reach a wider audience.<ref name=\"noisey\">{{cite web |last1=Currin |first1=Grayson |title=How Mount Eerie's Phil Elverum Faced Grief on His Devastating New Album |url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_uk/article/wn9z54/a-conversation-with-mount-eeries-phil-elverum-on-his-devastating-new-album |website=[[Vice_(magazine)#Website|Vice]]|date=March 28, 2017 |accessdate=November 19, 2018}}</ref> Despite this he still found releasing the album and promoting it to be \"gross and weird from a lot of perspectives\".<ref name=\"Stosuy\" /> On January 5, 2017, he announced that he would go on tour, and release a new album.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yoo|first1=Noah|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/70707-phil-elverum-please-dont-come-to-tomorrows-mount-eerie-show/|title=Phil Elverum: \"Please Don't Come\" to Tomorrow's Mount Eerie Show|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=January 5, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> The next day, he played his first concert since September 2014 at a record store in [[Anacortes, Washington]]. Elverum, while choosing to perform, also asked fans to stay away as the response was \"overwhelming\" and the store could only hold 50 people.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Strauss|first1=Matthew|title=Mount Eerie Performing New Music at First Show in 2 Years|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/70637-mount-eerie-performing-new-music-at-first-show-in-2-years/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=December 30, 2016|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Elverum performed the show with his eyes closed and left immediately afterwards.<ref name=\"larecord\">{{cite web |last1=Child |first1=Tom |title=Mount Eerie: Stay Sincere |url=http://larecord.com/archive/2017/04/10/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-phil-elverum-interview |website=[[L.A. Record]] |accessdate= November 21, 2018 |date=April 10, 2017}}</ref> The first single from ''A Crow Looked at Me'', \"Real Death\", was released on P.W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd.'s [[SoundCloud]] page on January 18, 2017, to widespread acclaim, netting the \"Best New Track\" distinction from [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Currin|first1=Grayson|title=\"Real Death\" by Mount Eerie Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/18708-mount-eerie-real-death/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"paste single\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/music/mount-eerie/mount-eerie-releases-music-video-for-ravens-announ/|title=Mount Eerie Releases Devastating \"Ravens\" Video, Announces West Coast Tour Dates|website=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|last=Rohrback|first=Paul|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref> The second single, \"Ravens\", was released on February 15, 2017, alongside a music video uploaded to Mount Eerie's official [[YouTube]] account, again earning the \"Best New Track\" distinction from ''Pitchfork'', writing that \"Elverum makes no attempts to find metaphor or meaning; when he sees two ravens flying overhead, he knows it's an omen, but he can't say what for.\"<ref name=\"pitchfork ravens\">{{cite web|last1=Sodomsky|first1=Sam|title=\"Ravens\" by Mount Eerie Review|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/18780-mount-eerie-ravens/|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=February 15, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"paste single\"/> The cover of the album features a photograph of the [[Joanne Kyger]]{{efn|Kyger would die of lung cancer two days before the album's release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/books/article/Joanne-Kyger-trailblazing-Beat-poet-dies-at-82-11021799.php|title=Joanne Kyger, trailblazing Beat poet, dies at 82|author=John McMurtie|accessdate=March 25, 2017|date=March 23, 2017|publisher=[[San Francisco Gate]]}}</ref>}} poem \"Night Palace\", which Castr\u00e9e had pinned above her desk.<ref name=\"observer\">{{cite web |last1=Joffe |first1=Justin |title=Beyond Grief: How Mount Eerie Made an Album About His Wife's Death |url=https://observer.com/2017/03/mount-eerie-phil-elverum-interview/ |website=[[observer.com|Observer]] |accessdate=November 19, 2018 |date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> Elverum had taken the photograph while he was cleaning out her room after she died and realised that the poem encapsulated the theme of the album. Castr\u00e9e's copy of [[Herg\u00e9]]'s ''[[Tintin in Tibet]]'' can be seen in the background.<ref name=\"bandcamp\">{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Erin Lyndal |title=Mount Eerie on Intimate Grief and the Creative Impulse |url=https://daily.bandcamp.com/2017/03/21/mount-eerie-interview/ |publisher=[[Bandcamp]] |accessdate=November 29, 2018|date=March 21, 2017}}</ref> \n\nFollowing the release of the album, Elverum embarked on a North American tour in September 2017, playing solo shows accompanied only by his acoustic guitar in intimate venues that included \"concert halls, churches, and theaters\".<ref name=\"geslani\">{{cite web |last1=Geslani |first1=Michelle |title=Mount Eerie announces North American tour dates |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/05/mount-eerie-announces-north-american-tour-dates/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=May 31, 2017}}</ref> The tour was extended to include Europe in November 2017.<ref name=\"TMTsmart\">{{cite web |last1=Smart |first1=Dan |title=Mount Eerie announces European tour dates in November |url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/news/mount-eerie-announces-european-tour-dates-november |website=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=September 20, 2017}}</ref> While performing at [[Jacobikerk]] as part of [[Le Guess Who?]] festival in [[Utrecht]], a sound engineer recorded Elverum's set without his knowledge. Elverum liked the recording so much that it was subsequently released as the live album ''[[(after)]]'' in 2018.<ref name=\"pitchforkafter\">{{cite web |last=Reese |first=Nathan |title=Mount Eerie: (after) |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/mount-eerie-after/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |date=October 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Critical Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 8.8/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/8559/Mount-Eerie-A-Crow-Looked-at-Me.aspx|title=A Crow Looked at Me by Mount Eerie reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| MC = 93/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/a-crow-looked-at-me/mount-eerie|title=Reviews and Tracks for A Crow Looked at Me by Mount Eerie|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/a-crow-looked-at-me-mw0003032380|title=A Crow Looked at Me \u2013 Mount Eerie|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Phares|first=Heather|date=2017|accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score = A\u2212<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/live/craig-finn-mount-eerie-pallbearer-and-more-weeks-m-252416|title=Mount Eerie confronts death on its saddest album to date|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Corcoran|first=Nina|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev3score = A\u2212<ref name=\"cos\">{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2017/03/album-review-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie \u2013 A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Sackllah|first=David|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| rev4score = 9/10<ref name=\"exclaimfenech\">{{cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/mount_eerie-a_crow_looked_at_me|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[Exclaim!]]|last=Fenech|first=Zach|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|last=Male|first=Andrew|issue=284|date=July 2017|page=91}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n| rev6score = 9.2/10<ref name=\"paste\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2017/03/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me-review.html|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked At Me Review|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|last=Fink|first=Matt|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 9.0/10<ref name=\"Powell\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22970-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked At Me|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Powell|first=Mike|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev8Score = 10/10<ref name=\"popmatters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|work=[[PopMatters]]|last=Britt|first=Thomas|date=March 20, 2017|accessdate=March 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev9score = 9/10<ref>{{cite journal|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|journal=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|issue=240|date=May 2017|page=35}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]''\n| rev10score = A<ref>{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/8xvyqv/expert-witness-with-robert-christgau-mount-eerie-a-crow-looked-at-me|title=Robert Christgau on Mount Eerie's 'A Crow Looked at Me,' a Brutal Listen|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=January 27, 2018|accessdate=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''A Crow Looked at Me'' received widespread critical acclaim upon release. At ''[[Metacritic]]'', which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from [[music critic]]s, the album has received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 93, indicating \"universal acclaim\", based on 18 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> Aggregator ''[[AnyDecentMusic?]]'' gave ''A Crow Looked At Me'' 8.8 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref name=\"adm\"/> Elverum found this \"reaffirming\" although was frustrated by those who viewed it as a tribute.<ref name=\"atlantic\"/> Heather Phares from [[AllMusic]] called the album \"remarkably powerful and pure\".<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''{{'}}s David Sackllah said that it was \"overwhelming and humbling\" and wrote that \"A Crow Looked at Me stands as a remarkable example of the restorative power of music, an intimate display of love, daring both in concept and execution.\"<ref name=\"cos\"/> Zack Fenech from ''[[Exclaim!]]'' said that \"this record possesses immense power to make listeners reflect on their own relationships and mortality. A Crow Looked at Me is a grim memento of the grand injustice of losing those most precious to us.\"<ref name=\"exclaimfenech\"/> ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''{{'}}s Matt Fink said that it was \"beautifully and simply arranged, but it is not an entertaining album to listen to in any conventional sense, nor can it be shaken off easily. It is, however, the kind of album that makes all others seem frivolous\" and that \"there is no album quite like it.\"<ref name=\"paste\"/>\n\nBen Malkin from GIGsoup described the album \"art in its most pure, human form\", a \"showcase of weakness and cruel reality, prose of lost love,\" and \"perhaps the saddest album ever made\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gigsoupmusic.com/reviews/album-reviews/mount-eerie-crow-looked/|title=Mount Eerie 'A Crow Looked at Me'|website=Gigsoup|last=Malkin|first=Ben|date=April 3, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> In his review for ''[[Spectrum Culture]]'' John Paul said that \"Heartbreaking doesn\u2019t even begin to describe ''A Crow Looked at Me''\" and described the album as \"pure grief delivered in a voice in which you can hear the weight of loss\".<ref name=\"SC\">{{Cite web|url=https://spectrumculture.com/2017/03/28/mount-eerie/|title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me|website=[[Spectrum Culture]]|last=Paul|first=John|date=March 28, 2017|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Sarah Greene, writing for ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now Toronto]]'' described ''A Crow Looked At Me'' as \"a lovingly crafted album, with gentle melodies that linger in the air, pretty, memorable guitar lines and a subtle but persistent approach to percussion\" and concluded that despite it may being an uncomfortable and harrowing listen it was also a \"tribute to an amazing 13-year love story\".<ref name=\"now/> Brian Roesler, from Treblezine, despite enjoying the record considerably, demanded that readers \"Don\u2019t call it art. Don\u2019t call it music even. Call it a documentation of suffering and loss as an experience, and treat it as such\".<ref name=\"Treblezine\"/>{{efn|A sentiment echoed by Elverum himself.<ref name=\"Powell\"/>}} In a [[essay]] written for [[The Spinoff]], Murdoch Stephens crowned Elverum \"the saddest musician in the world\", compared ''A Crow Looked At Me'' to the poetry of [[Auschwitz]] survivor [[Primo Levi]] and pondered how the listener should interact with a piece of art of such a visceral nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/music/15-01-2018/how-to-listen-to-mount-eerie-the-saddest-musician-in-the-world/|title=How to listen to Mount Eerie, the saddest musician in the world|website=[[The Spinoff]]|last=Stephens|first=Murdoch|date=January 15, 2018|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Elverum would go on to denounce the title, calling it absurd and that he sought out to inject beauty into the record.<ref name=\"atlantic\"/>\n\nSome reviewers said that it was difficult to review the album. In his positive review for ''[[Drowned in Sound]]'', JR Moores did not give the album a score because \"even awarding this work the full ten-out-of-ten would feel too callous given the tragic circumstances of the record's gestation and its heartbreaking subject matter.\"<ref name=\"dis\">{{cite web |last1=Moores |first1=JR |title=Mount Eerie - A Crow Looked at Me |url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/19863/reviews/4150889 |website=[[Drowned in Sound]] |accessdate=November 18, 2018 |date=March 20, 2017}}</ref> Reviewer Matthew Smith of ''No Ripcord'' said that \"assigning a score to a project like this is reductive...it's almost insulting to rank something as open and raw as this.\"<ref name=\"noripcord\">{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Matthew |title=Mount Eerie: A Crow Looked at Me |url=http://www.noripcord.com/reviews/music/mount-eerie/crow-looked-me |website=No Ripcord |accessdate=December 5, 2018 |date=March 23, 2017}}</ref> ''[[PopMatters]]'' reviewer Thomas Britt called the album a \"masterpiece\" but noted that it went beyond \"the limits of conventional music criticism.\"<ref name=\"popmatters\"/> Marvin Lin from ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]'' did score the album but said that his rating meant \"absolutely nothing\".<ref name=\"tmt\"/>\n\n===Accolades===\n''A Crow Looked at Me'' appeared on numerous year-end top lists.<ref name=\"Mc3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-released-in-2017|title=The Best Albums Of 2017|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|last=Dietz|first=Jason|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Such as [[The Atlantic]],<ref name=\"atlanticbest\"/> [[Consequence of Sound]],<ref name=\"COS\"/> Earbuddy,<ref name=\"Earbuddy\"/> [[Exclaim!]],<ref name=\"Exclaim\"/> [[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]<ref name=\"paste_best\"/> and [[Tiny Mix Tapes]]<ref name=\"TMT 2\"/>. The lead single \"Real Death\" was third on Pitchfork's list of 100 \"Best Songs\" of 2017.<ref name=\"Pitchfork Best\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-100-best-songs-of-2017/?page=9|title=The 100 Best Songs of 2017|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Sodomsky|first=Sam|date=December 9, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref> Metacritic, which collates reviews of music albums, named it the second best-reviewed album of 2017<ref name=\"Mc3\"/> and the seventh best reviewed album of decade.<ref name=\"Mc2\" />{{efn|Its appearance on the list made it the highest rated [[Contemporary Folk Music|folk]] album of the decade.<ref name=\"Mc2\" />}} According to [[Acclaimed Music]], the album is eleventh most critically album of 2017, eightieth of the 2010s and eight hundred twenty-sixth of all time.<ref name=\"Acclaimed Music\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A5951.htm|title=Mount Eerie A Crow Looked at Me|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>{{efn|The tenth highest ranking for an [[Indie Folk]] album.<ref name=\"Acclaimed Music2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/genre/genre261.htm|title=Top Indie Folk Albums|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>}} The album is the eleventh highest rated album on [[AnyDecentMusic?]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/chart/AllTime.aspx|title=All Time Chart|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> \n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|+Year-end lists\n|-\n! Publication\n! Accolade\n! Rank\n|-\n|''[[The Atlantic]]''\n| The 10 Best Albums of 2017\n| 6<ref name=\"atlanticbest\">{{cite web |last1=Kornhaber |first1=Spencer |title=The 10 Best Albums of 2017 |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2017/12/best-albums-2017/547451/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]''\n| Clash Albums Of The Year 2017\n| 54<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/features/clash-albums-of-the-year-2017|title=Clash Albums Of The Year 2017|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|last1=Clash Staff|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| Top 50 Albums of 2017\n| 8<ref name=\"COS\">{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/12/top-50-albums-of-2017/5/|title=Top 50 Albums of 2017|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last1=Cos Staff|date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Earbuddy''\n| Earbuddy\u2019s 100 Best Albums of 2017\n| 1<ref name=\"Earbuddy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.earbuddy.net/70003/earbuddys-100-best-albums-of-2017.html/albums-of-the-year|title=Earbuddy\u2019s 100 Best Albums of 2017|website=Earbuddy|last=Krenn|first=Nick|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Exclaim!]]''\n| Top 10 Folk and Country Albums of 2017\n| 2<ref name=\"Exclaim\">{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/music/article/exclaim_s_top_10_folk_and_country_albums-best_of_2017/page/2|title=Top 10 Folk and Country Albums of 2017|last=Staff|first=Exclaim!|work=Exclaim!|date=December 4, 2017|accessdate=Jan 10, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 14<ref name=\"fact_best\">{{cite web |last1=Horner |first1=Al |title=The 50 best albums of 2017 |url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/12/20/best-albums-2017/ |website=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]] |accessdate=November 22, 2018 |date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Guardian]]''\n| The Best Albums Of 2017\n| 47<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/dec/05/the-best-albums-of-2017|last1=Guardian staff|title=The Best Albums Of 2017|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 5, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 9<ref name=\"paste_best\">{{cite web |last1=Paste staff |title=The 50 Best Albums of 2017 |url