te web|url=https://spectrumculture.com/2017/12/19/top-20-albums-2017/2/|title=Top 20 Albums of 2017|website=[[Spectrum Culture]]|last1=Spectrum Culture Staff|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| 50 Best Album of 2016\n| 23<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/featured/50-best-albums-2017/|title=50 Best Album of 2016|website=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|last=Berman|first=Judy|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Sputnikmusic]]''\n| Staff\u2019s Top 50 Albums of 2017\n| 14<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/blog/2017/12/21/staffs-top-50-albums-of-2017-30-11/|title=Staff\u2019s Top 50 Albums of 2017: 30 \u2013 11|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|last=Robertson|first=Alex|date=December 21, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Stereogum]]''\n| The 50 Best Albums of 2017\n| 10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/featured/the-50-best-albums-of-2017/|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2017|author=''Stereogum'' Staff|work=[[Stereogum]]|date=December 5, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]''\n| 2017: Favorite 50 Music Releases\n| 1<ref name=\"TMT 2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/features/2017-favorite-50-music-releases?page=4|title=2017: Favorite 50 Music Releases|last1=TMT Staff|work=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]|date= December 18, 2017|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]''\n| Under the Radar\u2019s Top 100 Albums of 2017\n| 19<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.undertheradarmag.com/lists/under_the_radar_top_100_albums_of_2017/|title=Under the Radar\u2019s Top 100 Albums of 2017|website=[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]]|last=Wyatt|first=Stephen|date=December 30, 2017|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| The Top 100 Albums of 2017\n| 15<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2018/01/22/pazz-jop-the-top-albums-and-singles-of-2017/|title=Pazz & Jop: It\u2019s Kendrick\u2019s and Cardi\u2019s World. We\u2019re All Just Living in It|website=[[The Village Voice]]|last1=The Editors|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|+Decade-end lists\n|-\n! Publication\n! List\n! Rank\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| ''Pitchfork''\n| The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s\n| {{center|45}}\n| {{center|<ref name=\"pitchfork2\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/the-200-best-albums-of-the-2010s/|title=The 200 Best Albums of the 2010s|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=October 8, 2019|accessdate=October 24, 2019}}</ref>}}\n|-\n| ''Metacritic''\n| The Best Albums of the Decade (2010\u20132019)\n|{{center|7}}\n| {{center|<ref name=\"Mc2\">{{cite web |last1=Dietz |first1=Jason |title=The Best Albums of the Decade (2010-19) |url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-of-the-decade-2010s |publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 7, 2020 |date=November 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115223758/https://www.metacritic.com/feature/best-albums-of-the-decade-2010s |archive-date=February 7, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n|- \n|''Tiny Mix Tapes''\n| 2010s: Favorite 100 Music Releases of the Decade\n|{{center|22}}\n| {{center|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tinymixtapes.com/features/2010s-favorite-100-music-releases-decade?page=3|title=2010s: Favorite 100 Music Releases of the Decade|last1=TMT Staff|work=[[Tiny Mix Tapes]]|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks are written and produced by Phil Elverum.<ref name=\"dis\"/>\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = 41:30\n| title1 = Real Death\n| length1 = 2:27\n| title2 = Seaweed\n| length2 = 3:01\n| title3 = Ravens\n| length3 = 6:39\n| title4 = Forest Fire\n| length4 = 4:15\n| title5 = Swims\n| length5 = 4:07\n| title6 = My Chasm\n| length6 = 2:22\n| title7 = When I Take Out the Garbage at Night\n| length7 = 2:25\n| title8 = Emptiness pt. 2\n| length8 = 3:28\n| title9 = Toothbrush/Trash\n| length9 = 3:52\n| title10 = Soria Moria\n| length10 = 6:33\n| title11 = Crow\n| length11 = 2:21\n}}\n\n==Personnel== \nCredits adapted from the album's liner notes.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|others=Phil Elverum|title=A Crow Looked at Me|year=2017|publisher=[[Phil Elverum #Career|P. W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd]]}}</ref>\n*Phil Elverum{{spaced en dash}} songwriting{{spaced en dash}} vocals{{spaced en dash}} production{{spaced en dash}}  acoustic guitar{{spaced en dash}} electric guitar{{spaced en dash}} drum machine{{spaced en dash}} bass{{spaced en dash}} piano{{spaced en dash}} accordion\n\n==Release history==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Region\n! Label\n! Format\n! Category\n! Reference\n|-\n| United States\n| P. W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd.\n| [[Phonograph record|Double LP]], [[Digital distribution|Digital Download]]\n| ELV040\n|<ref name=\"pwelverumandsun\">{{cite web|title=A Crow Looked At Me by Mount Eerie|url=http://www.pwelverumandsun.com/store#mounteerie|website=P.W. Elverum And Sun|accessdate=October 27, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Japan\n| P. W. Elverum & Sun, Ltd.\n| [[CD]]\n| EPCD101\n|<ref name=\"pwelverumandsun\"/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Discogs master|1154519|A Crow Looked at Me}}\n\n{{Mount Eerie}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crow Looked at Me}}\n[[Category:2017 albums]]\n[[Category:Mount Eerie albums]]\n[[Category:P. W. Elverum & Sun albums]]\n[[Category:Concept albums]]\n[[Category:Works about cancer]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Template without correct end - Unbalanced quotes in ref name or illegal character. - Whitespace characters after heading)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Crow_Looked_at_Me"}
{"title_page": "MyNetworkTV telenovelas", "text_new": "{{short description|US television program}}\n{{Infobox television\n|italic_title=no\n| show_name          = The MyNetworkTV Telenovelas \n| image              = MNTVHDIdent.jpg\n| caption            = MyNetworkTV widescreen logo used during telenovelas\n| camera             = [[Multi-camera setup]]\n| picture_format     = [[SDTV]]\n| location           = [[San Diego]], [[Imperial Beach, California|Imperial Beach]] and [[Del Mar, California|Del Mar]], [[California]]\n| runtime            = 60 Minutes\n| creator            = {{Plainlist|\n* '''''Desire'''''\n* Orlando Jim\u00e9nez\n* '''''Fashion House'''''\n* Colet Abedi\n* '''''Wicked Wicked Games'''''\n* Jos\u00e9 Sim\u00f3n Escalona\n* Salvador Garmendia\n* Martin Hahn\n* '''''Watch Over Me'''''\n* Gustavo Belatti\n* Mario Segade\n* '''''American Heiress'''''\n* Colet Abedi\n* '''''Saints & Sinners'''''\n* Christian Bach\n* Humberto Zurita\n* Gerardo Zurita\n}}\n| developer          = {{Plainlist|\n* Paul Buccieri\n* Colet Abedi\n}}\n| executive_producer = Various\n| starring           = {{Plainlist|\n* '''''Desire'''''\n* [[Nate Haden]]\n* [[Zack Silva]]\n* [[Michelle Belegrin]]\n* [[Tommy Dunster]]\n* Kelly Albanese\n* '''''Fashion House'''''\n* [[Bo Derek]]\n* [[Natalie Martinez]]\n* [[Taylor Kinney]]\n* [[Mini Anden]]\n* [[Joel Berti]]\n* '''''Wicked Wicked Games'''''\n* [[Tatum O'Neal]]\n* [[Clive Robertson (actor)|Clive Robertson]]\n* [[Jack Krizmanich]]\n* [[David Smith (actor)|David Smith]]\n* [[Jessie Ward (actress)|Jessie Ward]]\n* [[Kate French]]\n* '''''Watch Over Me'''''\n* [[Dayanara Torres]]\n* [[Todd Cahoon]]\n* [[Marc Menard]]\n* '''''American Heiress'''''\n* [[Alicia Leigh Willis]]\n* [[Carter MacIntyre]]\n* [[Theresa Russell]]\n* Race Owen\n* '''''Saints & Sinners'''''\n* [[Scott Bailey (actor)|Scott Bailey]]\n* [[Tyler Kain]]\n}}\n| narrated           =\n| theme_music_composer =\n| opentheme          = {{Plainlist|\n* '''''Desire'''''\n* \"[[Always on Your Side]]\" by [[Sheryl Crow]]\n* '''''Fashion House'''''\n* \"Good at Being Bad\"\n* '''''Wicked Wicked Games'''''\n* \"Think Again\" by Blond Mafia\n* '''''Watch Over Me'''''\n* Sung by The Transcenders\n}}\n| country            = United States\n| company            = [[Stu Segall Productions]]\n| network            = [[MyNetworkTV]]\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2006|9|5}}\n| last_aired         = {{End date|2007|7|18}}\n| num_series          = 6\n| num_episodes       = 392 Total (78 Unaired)\n| website            =\n}}\nThe '''MyNetworkTV telenovelas''' were [[Fox Television Stations|Fox Television]]'s attempt to create a successful low-cost programming franchise by adapting [[Spanish language|Spanish-language]] [[telenovela]]s for U.S. viewers.  While originally planned for syndication, the format became the original lineup of [[MyNetworkTV]] in 2006.  Six limited-run serials were produced, each running about 65 episodes, and at least three others were halted in development.\n\nNew episodes aired from Monday to Friday \u2013 and weekend clip shows recapped the shows' storylines.   Producers planned continuous cycles of thirteen-week serials with no repeats.  Once one series ended, another unrelated melodrama would begin the following week.  In total, MyNetworkTV planned to air 600 hours of original dramatic programming in HDTV every year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.convergenceculture.org/weblog/2006/08/mynetworktv_first_broadcast_ne.php|title=Futures of Entertainment: Archives|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastdialogue.com/pdfs/newsletters/2006/nl20060817_14_11.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927063853/http://www.broadcastdialogue.com/pdfs/newsletters/2006/nl20060817_14_11.pdf |archivedate=2007-09-27 }}</ref>\n\nThe telenovela format was unsuccessful and ratings were unexpectedly low.  An average of about 781,000 people tuned in to watch the telenovelas, according to Nielsen Media Research.<ref>MyNetworkTV will try Plan B\nDeseret News (Salt Lake City),  Mar 27, 2007  by Scott D. Pierce</ref> Parent company [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corp.]] said MyNetworkTV lost two million dollars per week with the all-telenovela lineup.<ref>Heat Index; weekly rating (0-10) of sizzle & fizzle Advertising Age February 12, 2007</ref>\n\nUnder new network president [[Greg Meidel]], production and development stopped in early 2007. \"Trying to get people to watch serialized dramas every night on MyNetworkTV was asking the impossible,\" he remarked.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117958532.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 | work=Variety | title=Soaps not sudsy for MyNetwork TV | first=John | last=Dempsey | date=February 1, 2007}}</ref>  The novelas premiered on September 5, 2006 and last aired on July 18, 2007.\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n\n====Syndication plans====\nPaul Buccieri, Twentieth Television's programming chief, became fascinated by telenovelas in the 1990s, inspired by his Latina mother-in-law's devotion to such shows.<ref name=autogenerated2>[http://www.multichannel.com/article/CA6380533.html Plot Twists for Genre - 10/16/2006 - Multichannel News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He said that the nightly soap concept would work in the U.S. if given sufficient time.<ref name=autogenerated2 />  Along with colleagues Stephen Brown and Jack Abernathy, he started discussing the telenovela format in 2005.\n\nBefore it announced MyNetworkTV, Fox offered the telenovelas in syndication under as an anthology titled ''Desire'', which would air one hour each weeknight starting in the fall of 2006. It originally planned to air three serials per season.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117947630.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 | work=Variety | title=MyNetwork turns up heat on spicy telenovas | first=Michael | last=Learmonth | date=July 30, 2006}}</ref> They were originally intended to air as late night time programming.  In December 2005, Bucceri said the company had already bought enough novela formats to air original shows for five years.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvweek.com/news/2005/12/novelas_hot_new_format.php|title=Novelas\u2019 Hot New Format  -  TVWeek|accessdate=27 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219050526/http://www.tvweek.com/news/2005/12/novelas_hot_new_format.php|archive-date=19 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFox then added a second hour and planned to use two umbrella titles: ''Desire'' and ''Secret Obsessions''.<ref>[http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6355180.html MNT: All Novelas, All the Time - 7/21/2006 7:01:00 AM - Broadcasting & Cable<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> After receiving lukewarm response from stations not owned by Fox, Twentieth Television decided to pitch the show for June 2006. It argued that teenagers are out of school and planted in front of their TV sets, while reruns dominate network schedules. The telenovelas were also briefly considered for placement on [[The CW Television Network|The CW]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n\n====MyNetworkTV====\nFox Television Stations chairman [[Roger Ailes]] greenlit the format as a contingency plan for Fox-owned [[UPN]] stations.  Then MyNetworkTV was introduced to advertisers on February 22, 2006, as a reaction to the demise of UPN and The WB. The telenovelas became the new network's weeknight lineup, along with clip shows on Saturdays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvweek.com/news/2006/05/upfront_navigator_mynetworktv.php|title=Upfront Navigator: MYNETWORKTV: Breaking New Programming Ground with Telenovelas  -  TVWeek|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nMyNetworkTV targeted the telenovelas at the \"Adults 18-49\" demographic, which is a general audience. While the novelas had a few takers for a planned summer syndication run, Twentieth made those stations surrender the shows, thanks to a contract clause that let Fox take away the show if it is carried by a network.\n\nAs MyNetworkTV's debut grew closer, Fox dropped the idea of using two umbrella titles for its telenovelas. ''Desire'' became the title of the first series aired. The two umbrella titles reappeared in 2007, showing up during opening credits and on the network's Web site.\n\n===Budgets===\nJack Abernethy, chief executive of Fox Television Stations, said before launch that MyNetworkTV's six-day-per-week format was the wave of the future because a traditional schedule costs too much.<ref name=\"wsj0185\">{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB115698811194650185| title=With sexy story lines, low budgets, News Corp. will launch MyNetworkTV| author=Brooke Barnes| accessdate=2006-12-13| work=The Wall Street Journal Online| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314093050/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB115698811194650185| archivedate=2016-03-14}} </ref>  Each episode was said to cost about one-tenth the budget of traditional prime-time shows,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.philly.com/mld/philly/entertainment/columnists/jonathan_storm/15121967.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311001822/http://www.philly.com/mld/philly/entertainment/columnists/jonathan_storm/15121967.htm |archivedate=2007-03-11 }}</ref> and even less than the typical daytime soap.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117934563.html?categoryid=1952&cs=1 | work=Variety | title=20Th Gets Soaped Up | first=Elizabeth | last=Guider | date=December 13, 2005}}</ref> Another estimate said the serials cost $200,000 to $500,000, compared to the $2 million to $3 million cost of a mainstream primetime drama.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i841febf193b813600009c75ffb60970a|title=Entertainment/Hollywood News|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnfortunately, ad revenue was not sufficient for the format to succeed. At the 2006 upfront season, MyNetworkTV secured less than $50 million in ad deals, compared to $640 million for the new CW network.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> National advertising spots sold for between $20,000 and $35,000 for a 30-second spot as of September 2006.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06269/724946-237.stm | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | title=TV Notes: \"Grey's\" Beats \"CSI\" in First Face-Off | date=September 26, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Writers\u2019 dispute===\nAt first, MyNetworkTV called its soap writers \"translators\" since the projects were adaptations of existing Spanish telenovelas. These people were also non-union, which soon led to a labor dispute.<ref>[http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-5784762/MyNetworkTV-Nears-WGA-Deal-Telenovela.html MyNetworkTV Nears WGA Deal; Telenovela 'Translators' to Gain Writer Status.(TV Currents)(Writers Guild of America) Industry & Business Article - Research, News, Information, Contacts, Divisions, Subsidiaries, Business Associations<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The eventual settlement with the [[Writers Guild of America]] led to higher-than-expected programming costs.<ref>[http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6366088.html Murdoch\u2019s Next Bet - 8/28/2006 - Broadcasting & Cable<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nMyNetworkTV\u2019s union deals doubled its programming costs to more than $1 million per week for each series.  This significantly affected the telenovelas' bottom line. Before the dispute, News Corp. President-COO Peter Chernin said the format could \"be profitable from day one.\"<ref>[http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6400418.html My Network TV Mulls Change To Programming Strategy - 12/15/2006 2:13:00 PM - Broadcasting & Cable<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe shows were shot at [[Stu Segall Productions|Stu Segall Studios]] in [[San Diego, California|San Diego]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/tv/ci_4274070 |title=LA Daily News - Fox-owned \"MyNetworkTV\" set to launch<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-07-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930184448/http://www.dailynews.com/tv/ci_4274070 |archive-date=2007-09-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The facility, built by a former porn producer, specializes in low-budget productions. Since Segall rented part of the lot to the U.S. government, the telenovelas were shot near a mock Iraqi village used to train military personnel.<ref>[http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/features/20061008-9999-lz1c08stu.html SignOnSanDiego.com > News > Features - Modest mogul<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nAs a cost-saving measure, producers tend to hire performers with limited acting experience.<ref name=\"wsj0185\" /> The same sets were reused in multiple shows.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1198883-2,00.html | work=Time | title=Television: A Telenovela Revolution | date=May 28, 2006 | accessdate=May 19, 2010 | first=Jyoti | last=Thottam}}</ref> Producers built 53 shared living-room sets, which were repurposed by changing colors and camera angles to give them a different look.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://newsgroups.derkeiler.com/Archive/Rec/rec.arts.tv/2006-04/msg04657.html MyNetworkTV soaps race against time, low budgets]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Also, scripts were finished before taping started, so that all scenes on the same set were filmed at the same time, out of episode order.<ref name=\"wsj0185\" /> Up to three shows were filmed at once.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117949195.html?categoryid=2168&cs=1 | work=Variety | title=MyNet counts on telenovelas to fill programming pipeline | first=Thomas | last=McLean | date=August 28, 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe production model resembled that of movies more than normal US television series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/departments/features/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003119348|title=Home Page|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> Each complete series \u2014 equivalent to three seasons of conventional dramas \u2014 was filmed in about four months, as nine crews worked simultaneously,<ref>[http://www.courierpress.com/news/2006/sep/07/mynetworktv-to-offer-series-of-telenovelas/ MyNetworkTV to offer series of 'telenovelas' : Entertainment : Evansville Courier Press<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> For example, ''Desire'' used three directors, 50 cast members, 200 bit players, 2,000 extras and 2,800 script pages (compared to 120 pages for features and 45 for dramas).<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n \nTwo main groups worked on the novelas, one for the ''Desire'' brand and one for ''Secret Obsessions'' serials. The ''Desire'' shows, such as ''[[Watch Over Me]]'', were more action-oriented to attract more male viewers. All of the telenovelas used the same narrators, actor [[Ray Van Ness|Ray Van Ness III]] for the Secret Obsessions, and an uncredited female actor for the Desire brand.\n\nThe telenovelas are broadcast in [[high-definition television|high definition]] where available \u2013 and in letterbox format on standard definition broadcasts. During the all-novela period, MyNetworkTV promoted itself as \"the first all HDTV network.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pappastv.com/pressdetail.php?id=80&prYr=2006 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928031749/http://www.pappastv.com/pressdetail.php?id=80&prYr=2006 |archivedate=2007-09-28 }}</ref> In addition, early shows carried a [[Second audio program|SAP]] signal carrying a Spanish audio track, but an alternate [[closed captioning]] channel with Spanish translation was not used; in execution as most affiliates of the network never utilized SAP channels due to a lack of programming requiring it, and outside of major markets, the Spanish dub was never heard.\n\n===Comparison with Spanish telenovelas===\nMyNetworkTV\u2019s telenovelas were much shorter than the originals: about 65 episodes, rather than 120 to 180 hours. Each show was scripted, filmed and completed as a whole. The network could not shorten or lengthen shows.\n\nIn familiar [[telenovela]] form, shows often began with the tag \u201cMyNetworkTV Presents.\u201d Yet the beginnings of shows featured long flashbacks intended to refresh viewers. The first two rotations also added titles to each episode.\n\nThe daily format also featured the \u201cStory\u201d episode. These were clip shows that outlined the development of a major character.  They were used in lieu of reruns. In addition, MyNetworkTV's shows featured white, black and Hispanic actors in prominent roles and often showed interracial couples, along with gay subplots. These English novelas also toned down the high pitched emotionalism of conventional telenovelas.\n\nThe producers said they needed to account for the cultural differences with Latin countries.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/25/arts/television/25nove.html?pagewanted=2&ei=5090&en=1b28c85d194b6ce4&ex=1303617600&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss | work=The New York Times | title=Telenovelas to Deliver La Pasi\u00f3n in English | first=Mireya | last=Navarro | date=April 25, 2006 | accessdate=May 19, 2010}}</ref> So while these serials were said to add campiness, cat-fights and gay sensibility,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.advocate.com/print_article_ektid40796.asp |title=Print this Article: Love, Latin American style |work= Advocate.com |access-date= 2007-07-22 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070930154737/http://www.advocate.com/print_article_ektid40796.asp |archive-date=2007-09-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> they were also seen to lack the \"cultural depth\" and \"raw passion\" of the Spanish originals.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.today.com/popculture/telenovelas-make-leap-english-wbna14586450 |title= \u2018Telenovelas\u2019 make the leap into English |date= 30 August 2006 |publisher= |accessdate= 27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nCamilo Cano, the VP of [[Caracol TV|Caracol Television International]], which sold two telenovela formats to MyNetworkTV, said he was satisfied with the English versions. \u201cThe basic elements of the novela were respected,\u201d he said, \u201cwhich is what concerns us the most.\u201d He said Caracol worked to ensure the adaptations were faithful to the original serials.<ref>[http://www.worldscreen.com/featurescurrent.php?filename=novelas0407.htm World Screen - Home<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Broadcast rotations===\nAll times are [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]] and [[Pacific Time zone|Pacific]] (subtract one hour for [[Central Time zone|Central]] and [[Mountain Time Zone|Mountain]] time)\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!\n!  style=\"width:15%; background:silver;\"|Telenovela\n!  style=\"width:7%; background:silver;\"|Time\n!  style=\"width:15%; background:silver;\"|Premiere Date\n!  style=\"width:15%; background:silver;\"|Finale Date\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Fall 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[Desire (TV series)|Desire]]''\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|8:00 P.M.\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|September 5, 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|December 5, 2006\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Fall 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[Fashion House]]''\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|9:00 P.M.\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|September 5, 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|December 5, 2006\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Winter 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[Wicked Wicked Games]]'' \n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|8:00 P.M.\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|December 6, 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|March 6, 2007\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Winter 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[Watch Over Me]]''\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|9:00 P.M.\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|December 6, 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|March 6, 2007\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Spring 2007\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[American Heiress]]''\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|Weekly\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|March 13, 2007\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|July 18, 2007\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Spring 2007\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[Saints & Sinners (2007 TV series)|Saints & Sinners]]''\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|Weekly\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|March 14, 2007\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|July 18, 2007\n|}\n\nHad the daily format continued, ''[[Friends with Benefits (telenovela)|Friends with Benefits]]'' and ''Rules of Deception'' would have debuted on June 5, 2007.  ''[[Crossed Loves]]'' would likely have begun the second season in early September. It could have been joined in the Fall lineup by ''Friends & Enemies'', which was announced in the 2006 pre-season upfront presentation (in the third-quarter slot taken by ''Friends with Benefits'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/news/spotlight/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002503467|title=Home Page|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===International broadcasts===\n[[Image:foxtelenovela.png|right|thumb|Australian logo]]\nThe MyNetworkTV serial lineup was broadcast in Australia as ''FOXTELENOVELA'' on the [[W. Channel]].\n\n[[CKXT-DT|CKXT-TV]], an independent station in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada showed ''Desire'' and ''Fashion House'', airing them in the afternoon time slot traditionally held by daytime [[soap opera]]s. However, the station elected not to air any of the other telenovelas after the first cycle.\n\n==Reaction==\n\n===Campy melodramas===\nMyNetwork promoted its telenovelas as trashy melodramas, resembling [[prime time]] soap operas like ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'' and ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]''. Paul Buccieri called them \"guilty pleasures\" and compared them to beach novels.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> While these shows attempted to adhere to the [[telenovela]] format and tone, the network's executives and producers developed their own campy interpretation of the genre. They added characters and situations that differed from the Latin American originals. As telenovelas are inherently implausible and cartoonish, both Hispanic and non-Hispanic audiences scorned the new adaptations.<ref>Plot Twists for Genre By Luis Clemens -- Multichannel News, 10/16/2006</ref>\n\nReviewers were resoundingly negative. For example, ''TV Guide''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Matt Roush called one \"something worse than nothing.\"<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Robert P. Laurence of the ''San Diego Union-Tribune'' complained of \"amateurish acting, cheap sets and tedious scripts.\"<ref>[http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/features/20061106-9999-mz1c06remote.html SignOnSanDiego.com > News > Features - Telenovelas haven't lured viewers; San Diego channel not losing hope<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Robert Bianco of ''USA Today'' remarked, \"Think of the most incompetent soap opera you've ever seen, imagine something even worse, and there you have MyNetworkTV.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/2006-08-31-my-network_x.htm | work=USA Today | title=MyNetwork doesn't translate | first=Robert | last=Bianco | date=September 4, 2006 | accessdate=May 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\nPaul Buccieri said that English-speaking audiences needed time to understand the genre. \"We're sticking with it\u2014we believe in this product,\" he said.<ref name=\"miamibetty\" /> Roger Ailes brought up MyNetworkTV in a ''[[Financial Times]]'' interview. \"You should have seen us at [[Fox News Channel]] one year into it,\" he said. \"I've had this job for a year and it takes a little time to get these things off the runway.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/5b77af92-548c-11db-901f-0000779e2340|title=Interview transcript: Rupert Murdoch and Roger Ailes|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> Also, an executive of another television network told ''TV Week'' magazine that the existence of MNTV was \"a miracle\" because it went from concept to reality in only six months' time.<ref>[http://www.tvweek.com/news/2006/12/mynetworktv_executives_plot_sc.php MyNetworkTV Executives Plot Schedule Changes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930030054/http://www.tvweek.com/news/2006/12/mynetworktv_executives_plot_sc.php |date=2007-09-30 }}, ''TV Week'', December 15, 2006</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\nMyNetworkTV's debut was far from successful. ''Desire'' scored a 1.1 household rating/2 share; ''Fashion House'' went up to 1.3/2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticleHomePage&art_aid=47801|title=MediaPost - News and Conferences for Media, Advertising and Marketing Professionals|accessdate=27 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310152213/http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticleHomePage&art_aid=47801|archivedate=10 March 2007}}</ref>\nFox had sold about half of its projections of $50 million in advance commercial sales.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-0609030319sep03,1,390611.story?coll=chi-business-hed&ctrack=1&cset=true | work=Chicago Tribune | title=Topic Galleries - chicagotribune.com }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe first two telenovelas averaged a 0.5 rating and a 2 share in the key 18-49 demographic. It averaged just over one million total viewers. The numbers dropped each night, according to Nielsen Media Research.<ref>[http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/article/ds37089.html US TV - News - Low-rated start for MyNetworkTV - Digital Spy<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> These numbers were significantly lower than the programming that aired a year before, mostly UPN and WB programming.<ref>[http://www.tvweek.com/news/2006/09/no_ratings_increase_for_mynetw.php No Ratings Increase for MyNetworkTV Dramas], ''TV Week'', September 12, 2006</ref> The telenovelas showed more hopeful ratings in markets like Miami, with large Hispanic populations.<ref name=\"miamibetty\">{{cite web |url=http://www.miami.com/mld/miamiherald/entertainment/television/15618090.htm |title='Ugly Betty' producer grows into his role |work=MiamiHerald.com |date=September 28, 2006 |accessdate=2006-12-13 |author=Glenn Garvin |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061106054813/http://www.miami.com/mld/miamiherald/entertainment/television/15618090.htm |archivedate=2006-11-06 }}</ref>\n\nThe second set of telenovelas premiered to even lower numbers than the first pair. ''[[Wicked Wicked Games]]'' premiered to a 0.8 rating/1 share overnight rating during its first three nights, while ''[[Watch Over Me]]'' pulled a 0.7 rating/1 share.  Both shows dropped by a 0.1 rating during the Monday-Wednesday period of their second week. The network sought better debuts for the shows since they premiered in December, while the major networks usually air reruns and the viewer presumably would sample programming on other networks.\n\nMyNetworkTV's 200 affiliates struggled to promote the new format\u2014and ratings dropped in some markets as much as 90 percent. Even Los Angeles was an under-performing market.  One success story was Miami, where ratings more than doubled MyNetwork's national average.<ref>[http://www.redorbit.com/news/technology/752880/a_hot_love_affair_with_telenovelas/index.html?source=r_technology A Hot Love Affair With Telenovelas]</ref>\n\n===Cancellation===\nReports surfaced in December 2006, about a coming shift in MyNetworkTV's programming strategy.<ref>[http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6400418.html?display=Breaking+News MyNetworkTV Mulls Change to Programming Strategy] ''Broadcasting & Cable'' December 15, 2006</ref> Greg Meidel became the network's first president in January;<ref>{{cite web |last=Sternberg |first=Steve |url=http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle&art_aid=53940 |title=MediaPost - News and Conferences for Media, Advertising and Marketing Professionals |publisher=Publications.mediapost.com |accessdate=October 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060226131140/http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle |archive-date=February 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> he explained the low ratings as a result of viewers' difficulty to commit to the same program every night, especially with higher-rated serialized programming on other networks. Another issue was that the typical MyNetworkTV telenovela viewer was 44 years old.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-03-16-my-network-tv_N.htm MyNetworkTV tries, tries again], ''USA Today'', March 16, 2007</ref>\n\nOn February 3, 2007, the Saturday night clip shows vanished and were replaced by feature films. Then on March 1, 2007, MyNetworkTV announced that it quit developing scripted content altogether, putting an end to its slate of telenovelas.<ref>[http://www.tvweek.com/news/2007/03/mynetwork_tv_no_more_scripted.php TVWeek.com ~ \"MyNetwork TV: No More Scripted\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930030329/http://www.tvweek.com/news/2007/03/mynetwork_tv_no_more_scripted.php |date=2007-09-30 }}, ''TV Week'', March 1, 2007</ref> The network had at least three more serials in development, ''[[Friends with Benefits (telenovela)|Friends with Benefits]]'', ''Rules of Deception'', and ''[[Crossed Loves]]''. It tentatively planned to cut their schedule to one night a week by fall before announcing that all such projects were scrapped.\n\nUnder the revised schedule, two hour installments of ''[[American Heiress]]'' and ''[[Saints & Sinners (2007 TV series)|Saints & Sinners]]'' aired on Tuesday and Wednesday evenings through March and April. MyNetworkTV switched to one hour of each on Wednesdays for sweeps and never switched back. Meidel, the new network president, decided that the mixed martial arts ''IFC Battleground'' broadcasts on Monday would not deliver an audience to telenovelas the next night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/news/networktv/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003575924 |title=Home Page |accessdate=27 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008104110/http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/news/networktv/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003575924 |archivedate=8 October 2007 }}</ref> In addition, the last set of telenovelas were preempted several times for reality specials and other programming before being dropped altogether.\n\nMyNetworkTV previously announced plans to run the shows until October.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i91266009d4f35a6c1368f78df3983489 No upfront presentation from MyNetworkTV], ''Hollywood Reporter'', April 25, 2007</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-06-10-mynetwork_N.htm MyNetwork takes it on the chin, rebounds], ''USA Today'', June 11, 2007</ref> After that, the remaining episodes were to appear online.<ref>[http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117963744.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 MyNet nixes glitzy makeover], ''Variety.com'', April 24, 2007</ref> Meidel previously said the network would air the complete runs of both shows.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i119db77792cbaa01c3aea7c87504cc77, MyNetTV execs, affils: Change is good] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930224347/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i119db77792cbaa01c3aea7c87504cc77, |date=2007-09-30 }}, ''Hollywood Reporter'', March 9, 2007</ref> However, the telenovelas vanished without fanfare after their July 18, 2007 broadcast; only 26 out of each show's 65 hours were broadcast. (In addition, [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] has not announced plans to release any of these serials on [[DVD]].)\n\nMyNetworkTV's new fall 2007 lineup did not fare substantially better than the canceled telenovelas, however. The mix of reality shows and movies averaged a .7 household rating during September.<ref>[http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle&art_aid=68669 MyNetworkTV Regroups, Results Mixed] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060226131140/http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle |date=2006-02-26 }}, ''Media Post Publications'', October 5, 2007</ref> In addition, Paul Buccieri, the executive who championed the all-telenovela format, left Fox and became president and chief executive of [[ITV (TV network)|Granada America]] in December 2007.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[The Jay Leno Show]]'', a later attempt to strip the same show in prime time five nights a week\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{MyNetworkTV telenovelas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mynetworktv Telenovelas}}\n[[Category:MyNetworkTV original programming|Telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2000s American television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by 20th Century Fox Television]]\n[[Category:2006 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2007 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:American telenovelas]]\n[[Category:American television series based on telenovelas| ]]\n[[Category:2006 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2007 American television series endings]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|US television program}}\n{{Infobox television\n|italic_title=no\n| show_name          = The MyNetworkTV Telenovelas \n| image              = MNTVHDIdent.jpg\n| caption            = MyNetworkTV widescreen logo used during telenovelas\n| camera             = [[Multi-camera setup]]\n| picture_format     = [[SDTV]]\n| location           = [[San Diego]], [[Imperial Beach, California|Imperial Beach]] and [[Del Mar, California|Del Mar]], [[California]]\n| runtime            = 60 Minutes\n| creator            = {{Plainlist|\n* '''''Desire'''''\n* Orlando Jim\u00e9nez\n* '''''Fashion House'''''\n* Colet Abedi\n* '''''Wicked Wicked Games'''''\n* Jos\u00e9 Sim\u00f3n Escalona\n* Salvador Garmendia\n* Martin Hahn\n* '''''Watch Over Me'''''\n* Gustavo Belatti\n* Mario Segade\n* '''''American Heiress'''''\n* Colet Abedi\n* '''''Saints & Sinners'''''\n* Christian Bach\n* Humberto Zurita\n* Gerardo Zurita\n}}\n| developer          = {{Plainlist|\n* Paul Buccieri\n* Colet Abedi\n}}\n| executive_producer = Various\n| starring           = {{Plainlist|\n* '''''Desire'''''\n* [[Nate Haden]]\n* [[Zack Silva]]\n* [[Michelle Belegrin]]\n* [[Tommy Dunster]]\n* Kelly Albanese\n* '''''Fashion House'''''\n* [[Bo Derek]]\n* [[Natalie Martinez]]\n* [[Taylor Kinney]]\n* [[Mini Anden]]\n* [[Joel Berti]]\n* '''''Wicked Wicked Games'''''\n* [[Tatum O'Neal]]\n* [[Clive Robertson (actor)|Clive Robertson]]\n* [[Jack Krizmanich]]\n* [[David Smith (actor)|David Smith]]\n* [[Jessie Ward (actress)|Jessie Ward]]\n* [[Kate French]]\n* '''''Watch Over Me'''''\n* [[Dayanara Torres]]\n* [[Todd Cahoon]]\n* [[Marc Menard]]\n* '''''American Heiress'''''\n* [[Alicia Leigh Willis]]\n* [[Carter MacIntyre]]\n* [[Theresa Russell]]\n* [[Race Owen]]\n* '''''Saints & Sinners'''''\n* [[Scott Bailey (actor)|Scott Bailey]]\n* [[Tyler Kain]]\n}}\n| narrated           =\n| theme_music_composer =\n| opentheme          = {{Plainlist|\n* '''''Desire'''''\n* \"[[Always on Your Side]]\" by [[Sheryl Crow]]\n* '''''Fashion House'''''\n* \"Good at Being Bad\"\n* '''''Wicked Wicked Games'''''\n* \"Think Again\" by Blond Mafia\n* '''''Watch Over Me'''''\n* Sung by The Transcenders\n}}\n| country            = United States\n| company            = [[Stu Segall Productions]]\n| network            = [[MyNetworkTV]]\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2006|9|5}}\n| last_aired         = {{End date|2007|7|18}}\n| num_series          = 6\n| num_episodes       = 392 Total (78 Unaired)\n| website            =\n}}\nThe '''MyNetworkTV telenovelas''' were [[Fox Television Stations|Fox Television]]'s attempt to create a successful low-cost programming franchise by adapting [[Spanish language|Spanish-language]] [[telenovela]]s for U.S. viewers.  While originally planned for syndication, the format became the original lineup of [[MyNetworkTV]] in 2006.  Six limited-run serials were produced, each running about 65 episodes, and at least three others were halted in development.\n\nNew episodes aired from Monday to Friday \u2013 and weekend clip shows recapped the shows' storylines.   Producers planned continuous cycles of thirteen-week serials with no repeats.  Once one series ended, another unrelated melodrama would begin the following week.  In total, MyNetworkTV planned to air 600 hours of original dramatic programming in HDTV every year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.convergenceculture.org/weblog/2006/08/mynetworktv_first_broadcast_ne.php|title=Futures of Entertainment: Archives|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastdialogue.com/pdfs/newsletters/2006/nl20060817_14_11.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927063853/http://www.broadcastdialogue.com/pdfs/newsletters/2006/nl20060817_14_11.pdf |archivedate=2007-09-27 }}</ref>\n\nThe telenovela format was unsuccessful and ratings were unexpectedly low.  An average of about 781,000 people tuned in to watch the telenovelas, according to Nielsen Media Research.<ref>MyNetworkTV will try Plan B\nDeseret News (Salt Lake City),  Mar 27, 2007  by Scott D. Pierce</ref> Parent company [[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corp.]] said MyNetworkTV lost two million dollars per week with the all-telenovela lineup.<ref>Heat Index; weekly rating (0-10) of sizzle & fizzle Advertising Age February 12, 2007</ref>\n\nUnder new network president [[Greg Meidel]], production and development stopped in early 2007. \"Trying to get people to watch serialized dramas every night on MyNetworkTV was asking the impossible,\" he remarked.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117958532.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 | work=Variety | title=Soaps not sudsy for MyNetwork TV | first=John | last=Dempsey | date=February 1, 2007}}</ref>  The novelas premiered on September 5, 2006 and last aired on July 18, 2007.\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n\n====Syndication plans====\nPaul Buccieri, Twentieth Television's programming chief, became fascinated by telenovelas in the 1990s, inspired by his Latina mother-in-law's devotion to such shows.<ref name=autogenerated2>[http://www.multichannel.com/article/CA6380533.html Plot Twists for Genre - 10/16/2006 - Multichannel News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He said that the nightly soap concept would work in the U.S. if given sufficient time.<ref name=autogenerated2 />  Along with colleagues Stephen Brown and Jack Abernathy, he started discussing the telenovela format in 2005.\n\nBefore it announced MyNetworkTV, Fox offered the telenovelas in syndication under as an anthology titled ''Desire'', which would air one hour each weeknight starting in the fall of 2006. It originally planned to air three serials per season.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117947630.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 | work=Variety | title=MyNetwork turns up heat on spicy telenovas | first=Michael | last=Learmonth | date=July 30, 2006}}</ref> They were originally intended to air as late night time programming.  In December 2005, Bucceri said the company had already bought enough novela formats to air original shows for five years.<ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvweek.com/news/2005/12/novelas_hot_new_format.php|title=Novelas\u2019 Hot New Format  -  TVWeek|accessdate=27 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219050526/http://www.tvweek.com/news/2005/12/novelas_hot_new_format.php|archive-date=19 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFox then added a second hour and planned to use two umbrella titles: ''Desire'' and ''Secret Obsessions''.<ref>[http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6355180.html MNT: All Novelas, All the Time - 7/21/2006 7:01:00 AM - Broadcasting & Cable<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> After receiving lukewarm response from stations not owned by Fox, Twentieth Television decided to pitch the show for June 2006. It argued that teenagers are out of school and planted in front of their TV sets, while reruns dominate network schedules. The telenovelas were also briefly considered for placement on [[The CW Television Network|The CW]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n\n====MyNetworkTV====\nFox Television Stations chairman [[Roger Ailes]] greenlit the format as a contingency plan for Fox-owned [[UPN]] stations.  Then MyNetworkTV was introduced to advertisers on February 22, 2006, as a reaction to the demise of UPN and The WB. The telenovelas became the new network's weeknight lineup, along with clip shows on Saturdays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvweek.com/news/2006/05/upfront_navigator_mynetworktv.php|title=Upfront Navigator: MYNETWORKTV: Breaking New Programming Ground with Telenovelas  -  TVWeek|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nMyNetworkTV targeted the telenovelas at the \"Adults 18-49\" demographic, which is a general audience. While the novelas had a few takers for a planned summer syndication run, Twentieth made those stations surrender the shows, thanks to a contract clause that let Fox take away the show if it is carried by a network.\n\nAs MyNetworkTV's debut grew closer, Fox dropped the idea of using two umbrella titles for its telenovelas. ''Desire'' became the title of the first series aired. The two umbrella titles reappeared in 2007, showing up during opening credits and on the network's Web site.\n\n===Budgets===\nJack Abernethy, chief executive of Fox Television Stations, said before launch that MyNetworkTV's six-day-per-week format was the wave of the future because a traditional schedule costs too much.<ref name=\"wsj0185\">{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB115698811194650185| title=With sexy story lines, low budgets, News Corp. will launch MyNetworkTV| author=Brooke Barnes| accessdate=2006-12-13| work=The Wall Street Journal Online| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314093050/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB115698811194650185| archivedate=2016-03-14}} </ref>  Each episode was said to cost about one-tenth the budget of traditional prime-time shows,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.philly.com/mld/philly/entertainment/columnists/jonathan_storm/15121967.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311001822/http://www.philly.com/mld/philly/entertainment/columnists/jonathan_storm/15121967.htm |archivedate=2007-03-11 }}</ref> and even less than the typical daytime soap.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117934563.html?categoryid=1952&cs=1 | work=Variety | title=20Th Gets Soaped Up | first=Elizabeth | last=Guider | date=December 13, 2005}}</ref> Another estimate said the serials cost $200,000 to $500,000, compared to the $2 million to $3 million cost of a mainstream primetime drama.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i841febf193b813600009c75ffb60970a|title=Entertainment/Hollywood News|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnfortunately, ad revenue was not sufficient for the format to succeed. At the 2006 upfront season, MyNetworkTV secured less than $50 million in ad deals, compared to $640 million for the new CW network.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> National advertising spots sold for between $20,000 and $35,000 for a 30-second spot as of September 2006.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06269/724946-237.stm | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | title=TV Notes: \"Grey's\" Beats \"CSI\" in First Face-Off | date=September 26, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Writers\u2019 dispute===\nAt first, MyNetworkTV called its soap writers \"translators\" since the projects were adaptations of existing Spanish telenovelas. These people were also non-union, which soon led to a labor dispute.<ref>[http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-5784762/MyNetworkTV-Nears-WGA-Deal-Telenovela.html MyNetworkTV Nears WGA Deal; Telenovela 'Translators' to Gain Writer Status.(TV Currents)(Writers Guild of America) Industry & Business Article - Research, News, Information, Contacts, Divisions, Subsidiaries, Business Associations<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The eventual settlement with the [[Writers Guild of America]] led to higher-than-expected programming costs.<ref>[http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6366088.html Murdoch\u2019s Next Bet - 8/28/2006 - Broadcasting & Cable<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nMyNetworkTV\u2019s union deals doubled its programming costs to more than $1 million per week for each series.  This significantly affected the telenovelas' bottom line. Before the dispute, News Corp. President-COO Peter Chernin said the format could \"be profitable from day one.\"<ref>[http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6400418.html My Network TV Mulls Change To Programming Strategy - 12/15/2006 2:13:00 PM - Broadcasting & Cable<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nThe shows were shot at [[Stu Segall Productions|Stu Segall Studios]] in [[San Diego, California|San Diego]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailynews.com/tv/ci_4274070 |title=LA Daily News - Fox-owned \"MyNetworkTV\" set to launch<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-07-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930184448/http://www.dailynews.com/tv/ci_4274070 |archive-date=2007-09-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The facility, built by a former porn producer, specializes in low-budget productions. Since Segall rented part of the lot to the U.S. government, the telenovelas were shot near a mock Iraqi village used to train military personnel.<ref>[http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/features/20061008-9999-lz1c08stu.html SignOnSanDiego.com > News > Features - Modest mogul<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nAs a cost-saving measure, producers tend to hire performers with limited acting experience.<ref name=\"wsj0185\" /> The same sets were reused in multiple shows.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1198883-2,00.html | work=Time | title=Television: A Telenovela Revolution | date=May 28, 2006 | accessdate=May 19, 2010 | first=Jyoti | last=Thottam}}</ref> Producers built 53 shared living-room sets, which were repurposed by changing colors and camera angles to give them a different look.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://newsgroups.derkeiler.com/Archive/Rec/rec.arts.tv/2006-04/msg04657.html MyNetworkTV soaps race against time, low budgets]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Also, scripts were finished before taping started, so that all scenes on the same set were filmed at the same time, out of episode order.<ref name=\"wsj0185\" /> Up to three shows were filmed at once.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117949195.html?categoryid=2168&cs=1 | work=Variety | title=MyNet counts on telenovelas to fill programming pipeline | first=Thomas | last=McLean | date=August 28, 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe production model resembled that of movies more than normal US television series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/departments/features/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003119348|title=Home Page|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> Each complete series \u2014 equivalent to three seasons of conventional dramas \u2014 was filmed in about four months, as nine crews worked simultaneously,<ref>[http://www.courierpress.com/news/2006/sep/07/mynetworktv-to-offer-series-of-telenovelas/ MyNetworkTV to offer series of 'telenovelas' : Entertainment : Evansville Courier Press<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> For example, ''Desire'' used three directors, 50 cast members, 200 bit players, 2,000 extras and 2,800 script pages (compared to 120 pages for features and 45 for dramas).<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n \nTwo main groups worked on the novelas, one for the ''Desire'' brand and one for ''Secret Obsessions'' serials. The ''Desire'' shows, such as ''[[Watch Over Me]]'', were more action-oriented to attract more male viewers. All of the telenovelas used the same narrators, actor [[Ray Van Ness|Ray Van Ness III]] for the Secret Obsessions, and an uncredited female actor for the Desire brand.\n\nThe telenovelas are broadcast in [[high-definition television|high definition]] where available \u2013 and in letterbox format on standard definition broadcasts. During the all-novela period, MyNetworkTV promoted itself as \"the first all HDTV network.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pappastv.com/pressdetail.php?id=80&prYr=2006 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928031749/http://www.pappastv.com/pressdetail.php?id=80&prYr=2006 |archivedate=2007-09-28 }}</ref> In addition, early shows carried a [[Second audio program|SAP]] signal carrying a Spanish audio track, but an alternate [[closed captioning]] channel with Spanish translation was not used; in execution as most affiliates of the network never utilized SAP channels due to a lack of programming requiring it, and outside of major markets, the Spanish dub was never heard.\n\n===Comparison with Spanish telenovelas===\nMyNetworkTV\u2019s telenovelas were much shorter than the originals: about 65 episodes, rather than 120 to 180 hours. Each show was scripted, filmed and completed as a whole. The network could not shorten or lengthen shows.\n\nIn familiar [[telenovela]] form, shows often began with the tag \u201cMyNetworkTV Presents.\u201d Yet the beginnings of shows featured long flashbacks intended to refresh viewers. The first two rotations also added titles to each episode.\n\nThe daily format also featured the \u201cStory\u201d episode. These were clip shows that outlined the development of a major character.  They were used in lieu of reruns. In addition, MyNetworkTV's shows featured white, black and Hispanic actors in prominent roles and often showed interracial couples, along with gay subplots. These English novelas also toned down the high pitched emotionalism of conventional telenovelas.\n\nThe producers said they needed to account for the cultural differences with Latin countries.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/25/arts/television/25nove.html?pagewanted=2&ei=5090&en=1b28c85d194b6ce4&ex=1303617600&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss | work=The New York Times | title=Telenovelas to Deliver La Pasi\u00f3n in English | first=Mireya | last=Navarro | date=April 25, 2006 | accessdate=May 19, 2010}}</ref> So while these serials were said to add campiness, cat-fights and gay sensibility,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.advocate.com/print_article_ektid40796.asp |title=Print this Article: Love, Latin American style |work= Advocate.com |access-date= 2007-07-22 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070930154737/http://www.advocate.com/print_article_ektid40796.asp |archive-date=2007-09-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> they were also seen to lack the \"cultural depth\" and \"raw passion\" of the Spanish originals.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.today.com/popculture/telenovelas-make-leap-english-wbna14586450 |title= \u2018Telenovelas\u2019 make the leap into English |date= 30 August 2006 |publisher= |accessdate= 27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nCamilo Cano, the VP of [[Caracol TV|Caracol Television International]], which sold two telenovela formats to MyNetworkTV, said he was satisfied with the English versions. \u201cThe basic elements of the novela were respected,\u201d he said, \u201cwhich is what concerns us the most.\u201d He said Caracol worked to ensure the adaptations were faithful to the original serials.<ref>[http://www.worldscreen.com/featurescurrent.php?filename=novelas0407.htm World Screen - Home<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Broadcast rotations===\nAll times are [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern]] and [[Pacific Time zone|Pacific]] (subtract one hour for [[Central Time zone|Central]] and [[Mountain Time Zone|Mountain]] time)\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\"\n!\n!  style=\"width:15%; background:silver;\"|Telenovela\n!  style=\"width:7%; background:silver;\"|Time\n!  style=\"width:15%; background:silver;\"|Premiere Date\n!  style=\"width:15%; background:silver;\"|Finale Date\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Fall 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[Desire (TV series)|Desire]]''\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|8:00 P.M.\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|September 5, 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|December 5, 2006\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Fall 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[Fashion House]]''\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|9:00 P.M.\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|September 5, 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|December 5, 2006\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Winter 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[Wicked Wicked Games]]'' \n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|8:00 P.M.\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|December 6, 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|March 6, 2007\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Winter 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[Watch Over Me]]''\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|9:00 P.M.\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|December 6, 2006\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|March 6, 2007\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Spring 2007\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[American Heiress]]''\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|Weekly\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|March 13, 2007\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|July 18, 2007\n|-\n!  style=\"width:10%; background:silver;\"|Spring 2007\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|''[[Saints & Sinners (2007 TV series)|Saints & Sinners]]''\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|Weekly\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|March 14, 2007\n|  style=\"background:#fff; text-align:center;\"|July 18, 2007\n|}\n\nHad the daily format continued, ''[[Friends with Benefits (telenovela)|Friends with Benefits]]'' and ''Rules of Deception'' would have debuted on June 5, 2007.  ''[[Crossed Loves]]'' would likely have begun the second season in early September. It could have been joined in the Fall lineup by ''Friends & Enemies'', which was announced in the 2006 pre-season upfront presentation (in the third-quarter slot taken by ''Friends with Benefits'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/news/spotlight/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1002503467|title=Home Page|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===International broadcasts===\n[[Image:foxtelenovela.png|right|thumb|Australian logo]]\nThe MyNetworkTV serial lineup was broadcast in Australia as ''FOXTELENOVELA'' on the [[W. Channel]].\n\n[[CKXT-DT|CKXT-TV]], an independent station in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada showed ''Desire'' and ''Fashion House'', airing them in the afternoon time slot traditionally held by daytime [[soap opera]]s. However, the station elected not to air any of the other telenovelas after the first cycle.\n\n==Reaction==\n\n===Campy melodramas===\nMyNetwork promoted its telenovelas as trashy melodramas, resembling [[prime time]] soap operas like ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'' and ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]''. Paul Buccieri called them \"guilty pleasures\" and compared them to beach novels.<ref name=autogenerated4 /> While these shows attempted to adhere to the [[telenovela]] format and tone, the network's executives and producers developed their own campy interpretation of the genre. They added characters and situations that differed from the Latin American originals. As telenovelas are inherently implausible and cartoonish, both Hispanic and non-Hispanic audiences scorned the new adaptations.<ref>Plot Twists for Genre By Luis Clemens -- Multichannel News, 10/16/2006</ref>\n\nReviewers were resoundingly negative. For example, ''TV Guide''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Matt Roush called one \"something worse than nothing.\"<ref name=autogenerated4 /> Robert P. Laurence of the ''San Diego Union-Tribune'' complained of \"amateurish acting, cheap sets and tedious scripts.\"<ref>[http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/features/20061106-9999-mz1c06remote.html SignOnSanDiego.com > News > Features - Telenovelas haven't lured viewers; San Diego channel not losing hope<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Robert Bianco of ''USA Today'' remarked, \"Think of the most incompetent soap opera you've ever seen, imagine something even worse, and there you have MyNetworkTV.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/2006-08-31-my-network_x.htm | work=USA Today | title=MyNetwork doesn't translate | first=Robert | last=Bianco | date=September 4, 2006 | accessdate=May 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\nPaul Buccieri said that English-speaking audiences needed time to understand the genre. \"We're sticking with it\u2014we believe in this product,\" he said.<ref name=\"miamibetty\" /> Roger Ailes brought up MyNetworkTV in a ''[[Financial Times]]'' interview. \"You should have seen us at [[Fox News Channel]] one year into it,\" he said. \"I've had this job for a year and it takes a little time to get these things off the runway.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/5b77af92-548c-11db-901f-0000779e2340|title=Interview transcript: Rupert Murdoch and Roger Ailes|publisher=|accessdate=27 October 2016}}</ref> Also, an executive of another television network told ''TV Week'' magazine that the existence of MNTV was \"a miracle\" because it went from concept to reality in only six months' time.<ref>[http://www.tvweek.com/news/2006/12/mynetworktv_executives_plot_sc.php MyNetworkTV Executives Plot Schedule Changes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930030054/http://www.tvweek.com/news/2006/12/mynetworktv_executives_plot_sc.php |date=2007-09-30 }}, ''TV Week'', December 15, 2006</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\nMyNetworkTV's debut was far from successful. ''Desire'' scored a 1.1 household rating/2 share; ''Fashion House'' went up to 1.3/2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticleHomePage&art_aid=47801|title=MediaPost - News and Conferences for Media, Advertising and Marketing Professionals|accessdate=27 October 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310152213/http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticleHomePage&art_aid=47801|archivedate=10 March 2007}}</ref>\nFox had sold about half of its projections of $50 million in advance commercial sales.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-0609030319sep03,1,390611.story?coll=chi-business-hed&ctrack=1&cset=true | work=Chicago Tribune | title=Topic Galleries - chicagotribune.com }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe first two telenovelas averaged a 0.5 rating and a 2 share in the key 18-49 demographic. It averaged just over one million total viewers. The numbers dropped each night, according to Nielsen Media Research.<ref>[http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/article/ds37089.html US TV - News - Low-rated start for MyNetworkTV - Digital Spy<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> These numbers were significantly lower than the programming that aired a year before, mostly UPN and WB programming.<ref>[http://www.tvweek.com/news/2006/09/no_ratings_increase_for_mynetw.php No Ratings Increase for MyNetworkTV Dramas], ''TV Week'', September 12, 2006</ref> The telenovelas showed more hopeful ratings in markets like Miami, with large Hispanic populations.<ref name=\"miamibetty\">{{cite web |url=http://www.miami.com/mld/miamiherald/entertainment/television/15618090.htm |title='Ugly Betty' producer grows into his role |work=MiamiHerald.com |date=September 28, 2006 |accessdate=2006-12-13 |author=Glenn Garvin |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061106054813/http://www.miami.com/mld/miamiherald/entertainment/television/15618090.htm |archivedate=2006-11-06 }}</ref>\n\nThe second set of telenovelas premiered to even lower numbers than the first pair. ''[[Wicked Wicked Games]]'' premiered to a 0.8 rating/1 share overnight rating during its first three nights, while ''[[Watch Over Me]]'' pulled a 0.7 rating/1 share.  Both shows dropped by a 0.1 rating during the Monday-Wednesday period of their second week. The network sought better debuts for the shows since they premiered in December, while the major networks usually air reruns and the viewer presumably would sample programming on other networks.\n\nMyNetworkTV's 200 affiliates struggled to promote the new format\u2014and ratings dropped in some markets as much as 90 percent. Even Los Angeles was an under-performing market.  One success story was Miami, where ratings more than doubled MyNetwork's national average.<ref>[http://www.redorbit.com/news/technology/752880/a_hot_love_affair_with_telenovelas/index.html?source=r_technology A Hot Love Affair With Telenovelas]</ref>\n\n===Cancellation===\nReports surfaced in December 2006, about a coming shift in MyNetworkTV's programming strategy.<ref>[http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA6400418.html?display=Breaking+News MyNetworkTV Mulls Change to Programming Strategy] ''Broadcasting & Cable'' December 15, 2006</ref> Greg Meidel became the network's first president in January;<ref>{{cite web |last=Sternberg |first=Steve |url=http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle&art_aid=53940 |title=MediaPost - News and Conferences for Media, Advertising and Marketing Professionals |publisher=Publications.mediapost.com |accessdate=October 27, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060226131140/http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle |archive-date=February 26, 2006 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> he explained the low ratings as a result of viewers' difficulty to commit to the same program every night, especially with higher-rated serialized programming on other networks. Another issue was that the typical MyNetworkTV telenovela viewer was 44 years old.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-03-16-my-network-tv_N.htm MyNetworkTV tries, tries again], ''USA Today'', March 16, 2007</ref>\n\nOn February 3, 2007, the Saturday night clip shows vanished and were replaced by feature films. Then on March 1, 2007, MyNetworkTV announced that it quit developing scripted content altogether, putting an end to its slate of telenovelas.<ref>[http://www.tvweek.com/news/2007/03/mynetwork_tv_no_more_scripted.php TVWeek.com ~ \"MyNetwork TV: No More Scripted\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930030329/http://www.tvweek.com/news/2007/03/mynetwork_tv_no_more_scripted.php |date=2007-09-30 }}, ''TV Week'', March 1, 2007</ref> The network had at least three more serials in development, ''[[Friends with Benefits (telenovela)|Friends with Benefits]]'', ''Rules of Deception'', and ''[[Crossed Loves]]''. It tentatively planned to cut their schedule to one night a week by fall before announcing that all such projects were scrapped.\n\nUnder the revised schedule, two hour installments of ''[[American Heiress]]'' and ''[[Saints & Sinners (2007 TV series)|Saints & Sinners]]'' aired on Tuesday and Wednesday evenings through March and April. MyNetworkTV switched to one hour of each on Wednesdays for sweeps and never switched back. Meidel, the new network president, decided that the mixed martial arts ''IFC Battleground'' broadcasts on Monday would not deliver an audience to telenovelas the next night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/news/networktv/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003575924 |title=Home Page |accessdate=27 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008104110/http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/news/networktv/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003575924 |archivedate=8 October 2007 }}</ref> In addition, the last set of telenovelas were preempted several times for reality specials and other programming before being dropped altogether.\n\nMyNetworkTV previously announced plans to run the shows until October.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i91266009d4f35a6c1368f78df3983489 No upfront presentation from MyNetworkTV], ''Hollywood Reporter'', April 25, 2007</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-06-10-mynetwork_N.htm MyNetwork takes it on the chin, rebounds], ''USA Today'', June 11, 2007</ref> After that, the remaining episodes were to appear online.<ref>[http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117963744.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 MyNet nixes glitzy makeover], ''Variety.com'', April 24, 2007</ref> Meidel previously said the network would air the complete runs of both shows.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i119db77792cbaa01c3aea7c87504cc77, MyNetTV execs, affils: Change is good] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930224347/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i119db77792cbaa01c3aea7c87504cc77, |date=2007-09-30 }}, ''Hollywood Reporter'', March 9, 2007</ref> However, the telenovelas vanished without fanfare after their July 18, 2007 broadcast; only 26 out of each show's 65 hours were broadcast. (In addition, [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] has not announced plans to release any of these serials on [[DVD]].)\n\nMyNetworkTV's new fall 2007 lineup did not fare substantially better than the canceled telenovelas, however. The mix of reality shows and movies averaged a .7 household rating during September.<ref>[http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle&art_aid=68669 MyNetworkTV Regroups, Results Mixed] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060226131140/http://publications.mediapost.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=Articles.showArticle |date=2006-02-26 }}, ''Media Post Publications'', October 5, 2007</ref> In addition, Paul Buccieri, the executive who championed the all-telenovela format, left Fox and became president and chief executive of [[ITV (TV network)|Granada America]] in December 2007.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[The Jay Leno Show]]'', a later attempt to strip the same show in prime time five nights a week\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{MyNetworkTV telenovelas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mynetworktv Telenovelas}}\n[[Category:MyNetworkTV original programming|Telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2000s American television series]]\n[[Category:Television series by 20th Century Fox Television]]\n[[Category:2006 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2007 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:American telenovelas]]