/2019/06/09/chillin-voice-actors-panelists-join-ax-2019/|title=\"Chillin' With Voice Actors\" Panelists Join AX 2019!|date=June 9, 2019}}</ref> Julian Lai-Hung, Junichi Yamamoto, Kanae Yumemiya, [[Karen Kahler]], [[Karen Strassman]], [[Katsuhiro Otomo]], [[Keith Silverstein]], Keven Ouellet, [[Kunihiko Yuyama]], [[Laura Post]], [[Makoto Kimura]], [[Mamoru Miyano]], Manabu Ono, Manabu Otsuka, [[Marianne Miller]], [[Max Mittelman]], Miya Kimino, [[Mona Marshall]], Motonori Sakakibara, Nobuhiro Osawa, PICPICGRAM, Q-Gaku, Rachelle Heger, [[Range Murata]], [[Ray Chase (voice actor)|Ray Chase]], [[Rica Matsumoto]], [[Robbie Daymond]], Ryo Kitamura, Ryota Kosawa, Saya Horigome, Sayori, Shingo Adachi,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anime-expo.org/2019/06/11/sword-art-online-alicization-director-manabu-ono-character-designerchief-animation-director-shingo-adachi-join-ax-2019-guests-honor/|title=Sword Art Online Alicization Director Manabu Ono and Character Designer/Chief Animation Director Shingo Adachi Join AX 2019 as Guests of Honor!|date=June 11, 2019}}</ref> Shinnosuke, Shinya Sugai, Suzu Momoi, Taichiro Miyazaki, Takamitsu Sueyoshi, [[Takuma Terashima]], Takumi Saito, Tetsuya Fukuhara, Toshinobu Kondo, Utako Yukihiro, [[Yoshihiro Ike]], Yoshihisa Hashimoto, [[Yoshinori Ono (game producer)|Yoshinori Ono]], [[Yoshiyuki Sadamoto]], Yuito Kimura,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anime-expo.org/guests/|title=Guests Archive}}</ref> Yuji Matsukura<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SentaiFilmworks/status/1138522446120837130|title=Mark your #AX2019 calendars, friends... Arrow of the Orion will PREMIERE at @AnimeExpo with special guests that include the original creator and anime producers! (Did we mention there's an exclusive Q&A after????)|first=|last=Sentai Filmworks|date=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Convention list\n| date       = July 2\u20135, 2020<ref>{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/13753/anime-expo-2020 | title = Anime Expo 2020 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2020-03-10}}</ref> \n| venue      = Los Angeles Convention Center\n| location   = Los Angeles, California\n| attendance = \n| guests     = \n}}\n|}\n\n===Other Anime Expos===\nThe SPJA has twice run conventions outside California: '''Anime Expo New York''' in 2002, and '''Anime Expo Tokyo''' in 2004.\n\n====Anime Expo New York====\n'''Anime Expo New York''' (AXNY) was held in 2002 in the [[Times Square]] district of [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\"AC-2002NY\" />  The event was originally a joint effort with [[Central Park Media]] and its industry event, [[Big Apple Anime Fest]] (BAAF). Due to differences, the event ran as separate entities within the same time frame and venues, with BAAF hosting the theatrical film screenings, and Anime Expo New York hosting the convention. The events shared some resources, with notable guests listed in the program guides of both events.\nThe SPJA ran the event in order to demonstrate that it could run events outside its home state of California. The event was a precursor to Anime Expo Tokyo which ran in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] in 2004.<ref name=\"AC-2004T\" />\nThe SPJA has not run any events outside California since 2004.\n\n=====Convention locations=====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Dates !! Location !! Atten. !! Guests\n{{Convention list\n| date       = August 31\u2013September 2, 2002\n| venue      = [[New York Marriott Marquis|Marriott New York Marquis]]\n| location   = [[New York City|New York, New York]]\n| attendance = 5,500\n| guests     = [[Akitaro Daichi|Akitaroh Daichi]], Noboru Ishiguro, Yoko Kanno, Toshihiro Kawamoto, [[Takao Koyama]], Taro Maki, [[Chris McKay]], Koji Sugiura, Atsushi Takeuchi, Yoshiyuki Tomino, and [[Shinichir\u014d Watanabe|Shinichiro Watanabe]].<ref name=\"AC-2002NY\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/296/anime-expo-new-york-2002 | title = Anime Expo New York 2002 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref>\n}}\n|}\n\n====Anime Expo Tokyo====\n<!-- This section is linked from Fred Gallagher -->\n'''Anime Expo Tokyo''' (AX Tokyo) was held in 2004 at the [[Sunshine City, Tokyo|Sunshine City Convention Center]] in [[Ikebukuro]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]].<ref name=\"AC-2004T\" /> It was not technically organized directly by the SPJA, but rather was organized by the Japanese Association for Science Fiction International Communication (www.jasfic.or.jp)(JASFIC) with assistance from the SPJA. JASFIC had two goals for Anime Expo Tokyo. The first goal was to establish in Japan a non-corporate sponsored convention dedicated to anime. The second goal was to demonstrate to the organizers of the World Science Fiction Convention ([[WorldCon]]) that Japan could serve as a suitable venue for conventions that attract foreigners. Although Anime Expo Tokyo did not go on to a second year, JASFIC was ultimately successful in attracting the [[65th World Science Fiction Convention]] to Japan in 2007.\n\nAnime Expo Tokyo had a staggering list of over 40 guests such as manga artist [[Ken Akamatsu]], MiQ, [[Under17]], [[Hiroshi Aro]], and many others, although a small handful had to make last minute cancellations. Anime Expo Tokyo was also the very first Anime Expo that officially hosted guests from the U.S. anime industry such as webcomic artist [[Fred Gallagher (cartoonist)|Fred Gallagher]] and voice actor [[Crispin Freeman]].<ref name=\"AC-2004T\" />\n\nOf Anime Expo Tokyo's 4,249 attendees, approximately 300 of that number were estimated to have traveled from abroad. In addition to the attendance numbers were 240 members of the press, 40 of which were from overseas. An additional 430 people were composed of dealers, guests, or staff.\n\nNo plans to host another official Anime Expo outside California have been announced.\n\n=====Convention locations=====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Dates !! Location !! Atten. !! Guests\n{{Convention list\n| date       = January 16\u201318, 2004\n| venue      = Sunshine City Convention Center\n| location   = [[Tokyo|Tokyo, Japan]]\n| attendance = 4,919\n| guests     = [[Sh\u014d Aikawa (screenwriter)|Sho Aikawa]], [[Ken Akamatsu]], [[Hiroshi Aro]], Crispin Freeman, Fred Gallagher, Yuichi Hasegawa, Saki Hijiri, [[Ry\u016bsuke Hikawa|Ryusuke Hikawa]], Hiroyuki Imaishi, [[Imai toonz|Imaitoonz]], [[Isamu Imakake]], [[Mutsumi Inomata]], Noboru Ishiguro, Mitsuhisa Ishikawa, [[Takehiko It\u014d|Takehiko Ito]], Yutaka Izubuchi, Toshihiro Kawamoto, Hiroyuki Kitazume, Satomi Kodama, [[Rie Kugimiya]], [[Akira Kushida]], Tomomi Michizuki, MIQ, [[Nao Nagasawa]], Hiroshi Negishi, [[Tetsuya Nishio]], [[Hiroyuki Okiura]], [[Romi Park]], Akemi Takada, [[Nozomu Tamaki]], [[Kana Ueda]], [[Under17]], [[Yoshihiro Yonezawa]], and Reina Yoshimura.<ref name=\"AC-2004T\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/4/anime-expo-tokyo-2004 | title = Anime Expo Tokyo 2004 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n===Other Conventions===\n====Anime Conji====\n{{main|Anime Conji}}\nIn 2010, [[Anime Conji]] began as an annual anime convention in [[San Diego]].<ref name=\"AC-Conji2010\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/1932/anime-conji-2010 | title = Anime Conji 2010 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Yee |first=Michelle |date=1 April 2015 |title=Get Your Con on This Weekend |url=http://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/get-your-con-on-this-weekend/ |newspaper=Los Angeles Magazine |access-date=1 June 2015 }}</ref> In 2013, it began to be run by SPJA.<ref name=\"AC-SPJA\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/organizer/2/society-for-the-promotion-of-japanese-animation | title = Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref><ref name=\"AC-Conji2013\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/3577/anime-conji-2013 | title = Anime Conji 2013 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldofanime760.com/post/22786802882/newsbyte-anime-conji-transfers-to-spja |title=NEWSBYTE: Anime Conji Transfers To SPJA |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=10 May 2012 |website=World of Anime 760 |access-date=1 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051256/http://www.worldofanime760.com/post/22786802882/newsbyte-anime-conji-transfers-to-spja |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.spja.org/about-us/ |title=About Us |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2013 |website=Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation |access-date=1 June 2015 |quote=In June 2012, the SPJA adopted Anime Conji, the anime convention of San Diego. 2013 marked the first Anime Conji to be hosted by the SPJA. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802104139/http://www.spja.org/about-us/ |archive-date=2 August 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Anime Conji 2016 was cancelled due to event quality concerns.<ref name=ac2016canceled>{{cite web|title=Anime Conji has been canceled|url=https://animecons.com/news/post/1483/anime-conji-has-been-canceled|publisher=AnimeCons.com|accessdate=6 June 2018|date=December 18, 2015}}</ref> The convention returned in 2018 under its original organizers, the San Diego Speculative Fiction Society (SanSFiS).<ref name=\"AC-Conji2018\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/10766/anime-conji-2018 | title = Anime Conji 2018 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref><ref name=\"spjaconji2018\">{{cite web|title=SanSFiS Resumes Operation of Anime Conji|url=https://www.spja.org/sansfis-resumes-operation-of-anime-conji/|website=Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation (SPJA)|accessdate=28 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328231255/https://www.spja.org/sansfis-resumes-operation-of-anime-conji/|archive-date=28 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Organizational structure==\nThe Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation (SPJA), the parent organization which produces Anime Expo, is a federal and California state registered 501(c)(6) non-profit corporation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.spja.org/about-us/ |title=About The Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation |access-date=2014-02-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301063516/http://www.spja.org/about-us/ |archive-date=2014-03-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The operation of Anime Expo is divided into two groups: Entertainment & Operations.\n\nEntertainment has the following divisions: AV Tech, Entertainment Hall, Guest Relations, Interactive Events and Programming. Operations has the following divisions: Exhibit Hall & Registration and Facilities. As of 2013, the SPJA employed 11 employees and over 1,000 volunteers for Anime Expo.\n\nAnime Expo's parent company, the SPJA, has a number of additional paid positions whose roles are to conduct the organization's year-round operations. \nSuch positions also include the: Administration Director, Chief Executive Officer, Finance Manager, HR Director, Marketing Director, and Technology Director. \nThe SPJA also hires consultants for outsourced functions such as: Marketing consultation, Governance & Strategic training, Legal representation, Exhibit sales, and as needed program assistance.\n\n==Notes==\n* The 2009 event donated over $29,000 to the [[Children's Hospital of Orange County]] (CHOC) from the SPJA Charity Auction, announced during closing ceremonies on Sunday, July 5, 2009<ref name=\"expo09\">[http://www.axbackstage.org/2009/07/05/anime-expo-2009-continues-to-hold-the-title-of-nations-largest-anime-and-manga-event-with-a-record-number-of-over-44000-in-attendance/ Anime Expo 2009 Continues to Hold the Title of Nation's Largest Anime and Manga Event with a Record Number of Over 44,000 in Attendance], July 5, 2009</ref>\n* Masquerade main event was attended by a standing-room only crowd with over 7,200 seats available.<ref>[http://www.axbackstage.org/2009/07/05/anime-expo-2009-continues-strong-into-day-4-as-the-nations-largest-anime-and-manga-convention/ Anime Expo 2009 Continues Strong into Day 4 as the Nation's Largest Anime and Manga Convention], July 5, 2009</ref>\n* Total 2010 through-the-doors attendance achieved 105,000 (turnstile), compared to 2009's attendance of 109,000 (turnstile). This was Anime Expo's second attendance decline since its inception.<ref>Carlo Santos, [http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/convention/2010/anime-expo/spja-open-board-meeting SPJA Open Board Meeting], ''Anime News Network'', July 4, 2010</ref>\n* Anime Expo's 20th Anniversary was celebrated in 2011.\n* July 4, 2011 \u2013 Nearly $30,000 dollars raised at the SPJA Charity Auction for the Japanese [[Red Cross]] Society to aid in disaster relief.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Los Angeles|Anime and manga}}\n{{commons category|Anime Expo}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.anime-expo.org/}}\n\n\n{{Anime conventions in North America}}\n\n[[Category:Anime conventions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Culture of Anaheim, California]]\n[[Category:Culture of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:1992 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Conventions in Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Convention\n| name       = Anime Expo\n| image      = Anime Expo logo.svg\n| status     = Active\n| genre      = [[Anime]], [[Manga]], [[Video games]]\n| venue      = [[Los Angeles Convention Center]]\n| location   = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| coordinates = {{coord|34.039737|-118.270293|display=title,inline}}\n| country    = United States\n| first      = {{start date and age|1992|7|3}}\n| last       = {{start date and age|2019|7|4}}\n| next       = {{start date and age|2020|7|2}}\n| organizer  = Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation\n| filing     = Non-profit\n| attendance = {{increase}} 115,000 (2019)\n| website    = {{url|http://www.anime-expo.org}}\n}}\n[[File:Cosplayers of Saint Seiya at Anime Expo 2016-07-01.jpg|thumb|240px|[[Saint Seiya]] style Inner Senshi from [[Sailor Moon]]\n[[cosplayers]] at Anime Expo 2016]]\n[[File:AX Models Outside.jpg|thumb|240px|Cosplayers outside the Los Angeles Convention Center]]\n[[File:Anime Expo South Hall Lobby 2016.jpg|thumb|240px|Attendees gather at the Los Angeles Convention Center's South Hall during Anime Expo 2016]]\n\n'''Anime Expo''', abbreviated '''AX''', is an American [[anime convention]] held in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] and organized by the non-profit '''Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation''' (SPJA). With rare exceptions, the convention is traditionally held on the first weekend in July, which typically coincides with the [[4th of July]], and lasts for four days. While currently hosted at the [[Los Angeles Convention Center]], in the past Anime Expo has been held in other locations such as Anaheim, San Jose, New York, and Tokyo. Anime Expo is the largest North American anime convention as of 2017.<ref name=aclargest2017>{{cite web|last1=Delahanty|first1=Patrick|title=Largest North American Anime Conventions of 2017|url=https://animecons.com/news/post/1516/largest-north-american-anime-conventions-of-2017|publisher=AnimeCons.com|accessdate=6 June 2018|date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Events and programming==\nAnime Expo features many events and activities during the convention for attendees to take part in such as guest panels, table top gaming, competitions, an arcade, and concerts.\n\nTop attractions include events such as the Masquerade [[cosplay]] contest, the [[Anime Music Video]] (AMV) competition, Battle of the Bands, and SPJA's Charity Auction. In addition, Anime Expo hosts a multitude of industry Guests of Honor (GoH), including notable music artists who often hold large concerts at AX. Anime Expo also has a large variety of focus panels, workshops, and events, some of which are fan or industry sponsored. Finally, there are also a number of film and video rooms presenting anime screenings that run all day and night.\n\nMuch like other conventions, Anime Expo also features a large scale exhibit hall where attendees can purchase a variety of products from a wide range of exhibitors. This exhibit hall also features an artist alley where attendees can purchase fan-created art work, as well as other varieties of crafts such as wigs, pins, and [[cosplay]] material.\n\n==Convention history==\n\n===History===\n[[File:Cosplayers of Naruto at Anime Expo 2006-07-02.jpg|thumb|240px|[[Naruto]] cosplayers at Anime Expo 2006]]\nAnime Expo began as an anime and manga convention in Northern California. Many of its original staff came from [[Anime Con]], an anime convention held in [[San Jose, California]] in 1991, and later absorbed by the SPJA in 1992. In 1994, Anime Expo made a strategic relocation to Southern California and has resided there since.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yYInVE6OLiQC&pg=PA153&lpg=PA153&dq=anime+expo+moved+to+southern+california#v=onepage&q=anime%20expo%20moved%20to%20southern%20california&f=false|title=Demanding Respect: The Evolution of the American Comic Book|last=Lopes|first=Paul|date=2009-04-07|publisher=Temple University Press|isbn=9781592134441|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe convention continues to thrive due to the growing popularity of anime and Japanese popular culture and maintains a strong draw due to the many notable Japanese guests it has been known for. It currently holds the title of North America's largest anime convention, a title which it has consistently held every year except 2003 in which its attendance was slightly edged out by east coast convention [[Otakon]].<ref name=\"AC2003\">{{cite web| last=Delahanty|first=Patrick| url = https://animecons.com/news/post/410/ten-largest-north-american-anime-conventions-of-2003 | title = Ten largest North American anime conventions of 2003 | work = AnimeCons.com | date = 2007-01-09 | accessdate = 2018-06-06}}</ref> From 1,750 attendees in 1992, Anime Expo's size has increased to over 107,658 in 2017, which makes Anime Expo the largest anime and manga convention in [[North America]].<ref name=aclargest2017/>\n\nAs of March 2009, Chief Executive Officer Trulee Karahashi, who had been a part of Anime Expo and the SPJA in various capacities for 11 years, left the organization.<ref>[http://www.spja.org/ To: SPJA Executive Members, Convention Committee, Anime Expo Managers, Staff and Volunteers], March 28, 2009</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spja.org/career/chief-executive-officer-ceo-for-the-society-for-the-promotion-of-japanese-animation-spja/|title=Chief Executive Officer (CEO) for The Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation \"(SPJA)\"}}</ref> Former Universal Studios executive Michael Lattanzio was hired as the SPJA's new CEO in September.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://spja.org/news/?p=29|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728045413/http://spja.org/news/?p=29|url-status=dead|title=The Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation Announces New President and Chief Executive Officer|archivedate=July 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.japanator.com/spja-announces-new-ceo-michael-lattanzio-11293.phtml|title=SPJA announces new CEO, Michael Lattanzio|website=Japanator}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2010, eight members of Anime Expo's upper management team (ConCom) publicly resigned over irreconcilable disagreements over the direction of the organization set forth by the SPJA's new CEO. One significant point of contention was the new CEO's decision to refocus and restructure the SPJA's marketing efforts starting with the dismissal of a PR and marketing contractor that the organization had a close working relationship with since 2004. Additionally, two other personnel had already left for other reasons, leaving only the vice chair and two others as returning members of the previous year's team.<ref>[http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-01-11/multiple-anime-expo-staffers-resign-in-board-dispute Multiple Anime Expo Staffers Resign in Board Dispute] January 11, 2010</ref>\n\nAs of September 2010, Michael Lattanzio was released from his CEO position.<ref>[http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-09-25/anime-expo-parent-ceo-michael-lattanzio-steps-down] September 25, 2010</ref> Then SPJA Chairman of the Board Marc Perez, became acting-CEO; In August 2011 he stepped down from the Board of Directors to take over as a full-time CEO (as required by the SPJA bylaws).\n\nIn early 2012, [[Anime News Network]] reported that Anime Expo suffered a $1.2 million loss in 2010.<ref>[http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-02-03/exclusive/anime-expo-2010-lost-us$1.2-million-idg-to-boost-involvement-in-2012 Exclusive: AX 2010 Lost $1.2 Million; IDG to Boost Involvement], Animenewsnetwork, February 3, 2012</ref> The 2011 convention saw a $100,000 profit and reduced the outstanding debt to $700,000. The article also stated that one of the creditors, [[IDG World Expo]], will be taking over several aspects of the organization, with guest selection and programming to remain under SPJA control. Additionally, Takayuki Karahashi<ref name=\"Otakon Parent Elects New Board of Directors\">{{cite web | url = http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-10-19/otakon-parent-elects-new-board-of-directors | title = Otakon Parent Elects New Board of Directors | publisher = animenewsnetwork.com | accessdate = 2012-02-15}}</ref><ref name=\"AX Parent Reveals Board of Directors Election Results\">{{cite web | url = http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-11-01/ax-parent-reveals-board-of-directors-election-results | title = AX Parent Reveals Board of Directors Election Results | publisher = animenewsnetwork.com | accessdate = 2012-02-15}}</ref> has been elected to Chairman of the Board of Directors.<ref name=\"Exclusive: AX 2010 Lost $1.2 Million; IDG to Boost Involvement\">{{cite web | url = http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-02-03/exclusive/anime-expo-2010-lost-us$1.2-million-idg-to-boost-involvement-in-2012 | title = Exclusive: AX 2010 Lost $1.2 Million; IDG to Boost Involvement | publisher = animenewsnetwork.com | accessdate = 2012-02-15}}</ref>\n\nThe convention will continue to be located at the Los Angeles Convention Center through 2019.<ref name=ann06272015>{{cite news|title=Anime Expo to Stay in Los Angeles for 5 More Years|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2015-06-27/anime-expo-to-stay-in-los-angeles-for-5-more-years/.89722|accessdate=6 July 2015|work=Anime News Network|date=June 27, 2015}}</ref> In April 2016, Marc Perez left the company, with Ray Chiang becoming acting CEO of SPJA.<ref name=\"ann04072016perez\">{{cite news|title=CEO Marc Perez Leaves Anime Expo's Parent Company SPJA|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-04-07/ceo-marc-perez-leaves-anime-expo-parent-company-spja/.100738|accessdate=8 April 2016|work=Anime News Network|date=April 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 30, 2017, the first Pre-Show Night was added to the Anime Expo, which included the Neon District, hosting the World Cosplay Summit U.S. Finals, and premieres.\n\nAs the convention's attendance has grown, it's seen long lines for entry into the convention hall, which organizers said was due to safety and security concerns.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://kotaku.com/anime-expo-2017-is-this-weekend-and-the-line-to-get-in-1796579356 |title=Anime Expo 2017 Is This Weekend And The Line To Get In Is A Special Kind Of Hell UPDATE|work=[[Kotaku]]|access-date=November 17, 2019|date=July 1, 2017 | first=Ethan| last=Gach}}</ref>\n\n===Convention locations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Dates !! Location !! Atten. !! Guests\n{{Convention list\n| date       = July 3\u20136, 1992\n| venue      = Red Lion Hotel\n| location   = [[San Jose, California]]\n| attendance = 1,750<ref>{{cite news |last1=Solomon |first1=Charles |title=Mainstream call of anime; The annual Anime Expo expects to draw an ever-growing demographic of fans to Anaheim. |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jul/01/entertainment/et-solomon1 |accessdate=23 Oct 2018 |publisher=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n| guests     = Jerry Beck, L. Lois Buhalis, [[Ben Dunn]], Robert Fenelon, [[Lea Hernandez]], Seiji Horibuchi, Ken Iyadomi, [[Shawne Kleckner]], Trish Ledoux, [[Carl Macek]], Luke Menichelli, [[Haruhiko Mikimoto]], [[Keiji Nakazawa]], Robert Napton, John O'Donnell, Claude J. Pelletier, David Keith Riddick, [[Frederik L. Schodt]], [[Buichi Terasawa]], Jeff Thompson, [[Yoshiyuki Tomino]], [[Steve Wang]], [[Robert Woodhead]], and Toshifumi Yoshida.<ref name=\"AC-1992\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/137/anime-expo-1992 | title = Anime Expo 1992 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Convention list\n| date       = July 2\u20134, 1993\n| venue      = Parc Oakland Hotel and <br /> Oakland Convention Center\n| location   = [[Oakland, California]]\n| attendance = 1,693\n| guests     = [[Keita Amemiya]], Robert DeJesus, Doug Dlin, Robert Fenelon, Peter Goll, Kenji Goto, David Ho, Seiji Horibuchi, Leo Hourvitz, [[Yasuhiro Imagawa]], Junco Ito, [[Kia Asamiya|Michitaka Kikuchi]], [[Hiroyuki Kitazume]], [[Makoto Kobayashi (artist)|Makoto Kobayashi]], Steve Kyte, Trish Ledoux, Carl Macek, [[Helen McCarthy]], Haruhiko Mikimoto, Robert Napton, [[Yasushi Nirasawa]], Martin Oulette, [[Wil Overton]], Claude J. Pelletier, [[Jeff Pidgeon]], Frederik L. Schodt, Jan Scott-Frazier, Masatoshi Tahara, Takayuki Takeya, and Toshifumi Yoshida.<ref name=\"AC-1993\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/147/anime-expo-1993 | title = Anime Expo 1993 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Convention list\n| date       = July 1\u20133, 1994\n| venue      = Anaheim Marriott Hotel and <br /> [[Anaheim Convention Center