e Anime Fest]] (BAAF). Due to differences, the event ran as separate entities within the same time frame and venues, with BAAF hosting the theatrical film screenings, and Anime Expo New York hosting the convention. The events shared some resources, with notable guests listed in the program guides of both events.\nThe SPJA ran the event in order to demonstrate that it could run events outside its home state of California. The event was a precursor to Anime Expo Tokyo which ran in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]] in 2004.<ref name=\"AC-2004T\" />\nThe SPJA has not run any events outside California since 2004.\n\n=====Convention locations=====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Dates !! Location !! Atten. !! Guests\n{{Convention list\n| date       = August 31\u2013September 2, 2002\n| venue      = [[New York Marriott Marquis|Marriott New York Marquis]]\n| location   = [[New York City|New York, New York]]\n| attendance = 5,500\n| guests     = [[Akitaro Daichi|Akitaroh Daichi]], Noboru Ishiguro, Yoko Kanno, Toshihiro Kawamoto, [[Takao Koyama]], Taro Maki, [[Chris McKay]], Koji Sugiura, Atsushi Takeuchi, Yoshiyuki Tomino, and [[Shinichir\u014d Watanabe|Shinichiro Watanabe]].<ref name=\"AC-2002NY\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/296/anime-expo-new-york-2002 | title = Anime Expo New York 2002 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref>\n}}\n|}\n\n====Anime Expo Tokyo====\n<!-- This section is linked from Fred Gallagher -->\n'''Anime Expo Tokyo''' (AX Tokyo) was held in 2004 at the [[Sunshine City, Tokyo|Sunshine City Convention Center]] in [[Ikebukuro]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]].<ref name=\"AC-2004T\" /> It was not technically organized directly by the SPJA, but rather was organized by the Japanese Association for Science Fiction International Communication (www.jasfic.or.jp)(JASFIC) with assistance from the SPJA. JASFIC had two goals for Anime Expo Tokyo. The first goal was to establish in Japan a non-corporate sponsored convention dedicated to anime. The second goal was to demonstrate to the organizers of the World Science Fiction Convention ([[WorldCon]]) that Japan could serve as a suitable venue for conventions that attract foreigners. Although Anime Expo Tokyo did not go on to a second year, JASFIC was ultimately successful in attracting the [[65th World Science Fiction Convention]] to Japan in 2007.\n\nAnime Expo Tokyo had a staggering list of over 40 guests such as manga artist [[Ken Akamatsu]], MiQ, [[Under17]], [[Hiroshi Aro]], and many others, although a small handful had to make last minute cancellations. Anime Expo Tokyo was also the very first Anime Expo that officially hosted guests from the U.S. anime industry such as webcomic artist [[Fred Gallagher (cartoonist)|Fred Gallagher]] and voice actor [[Crispin Freeman]].<ref name=\"AC-2004T\" />\n\nOf Anime Expo Tokyo's 4,249 attendees, approximately 300 of that number were estimated to have traveled from abroad. In addition to the attendance numbers were 240 members of the press, 40 of which were from overseas. An additional 430 people were composed of dealers, guests, or staff.\n\nNo plans to host another official Anime Expo outside California have been announced.\n\n=====Convention locations=====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Dates !! Location !! Atten. !! Guests\n{{Convention list\n| date       = January 16\u201318, 2004\n| venue      = Sunshine City Convention Center\n| location   = [[Tokyo|Tokyo, Japan]]\n| attendance = 4,919\n| guests     = [[Sh\u014d Aikawa (screenwriter)|Sho Aikawa]], [[Ken Akamatsu]], [[Hiroshi Aro]], Crispin Freeman, Fred Gallagher, Yuichi Hasegawa, Saki Hijiri, [[Ry\u016bsuke Hikawa|Ryusuke Hikawa]], Hiroyuki Imaishi, [[Imai toonz|Imaitoonz]], [[Isamu Imakake]], [[Mutsumi Inomata]], Noboru Ishiguro, Mitsuhisa Ishikawa, [[Takehiko It\u014d|Takehiko Ito]], Yutaka Izubuchi, Toshihiro Kawamoto, Hiroyuki Kitazume, Satomi Kodama, [[Rie Kugimiya]], [[Akira Kushida]], Tomomi Michizuki, MIQ, [[Nao Nagasawa]], Hiroshi Negishi, [[Tetsuya Nishio]], [[Hiroyuki Okiura]], [[Romi Park]], Akemi Takada, [[Nozomu Tamaki]], [[Kana Ueda]], [[Under17]], [[Yoshihiro Yonezawa]], and Reina Yoshimura.<ref name=\"AC-2004T\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/4/anime-expo-tokyo-2004 | title = Anime Expo Tokyo 2004 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n===Other Conventions===\n====Anime Conji====\n{{main|Anime Conji}}\nIn 2010, [[Anime Conji]] began as an annual anime convention in [[San Diego]].<ref name=\"AC-Conji2010\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/1932/anime-conji-2010 | title = Anime Conji 2010 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Yee |first=Michelle |date=1 April 2015 |title=Get Your Con on This Weekend |url=http://www.lamag.com/culturefiles/get-your-con-on-this-weekend/ |newspaper=Los Angeles Magazine |access-date=1 June 2015 }}</ref> In 2013, it began to be run by SPJA.<ref name=\"AC-SPJA\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/organizer/2/society-for-the-promotion-of-japanese-animation | title = Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref><ref name=\"AC-Conji2013\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/3577/anime-conji-2013 | title = Anime Conji 2013 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldofanime760.com/post/22786802882/newsbyte-anime-conji-transfers-to-spja |title=NEWSBYTE: Anime Conji Transfers To SPJA |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=10 May 2012 |website=World of Anime 760 |access-date=1 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051256/http://www.worldofanime760.com/post/22786802882/newsbyte-anime-conji-transfers-to-spja |archive-date=2016-03-04 |url-status=dead }}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.spja.org/about-us/ |title=About Us |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2013 |website=Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation |access-date=1 June 2015 |quote=In June 2012, the SPJA adopted Anime Conji, the anime convention of San Diego. 2013 marked the first Anime Conji to be hosted by the SPJA. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802104139/http://www.spja.org/about-us/ |archive-date=2 August 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Anime Conji 2016 was cancelled due to event quality concerns.<ref name=ac2016canceled>{{cite web|title=Anime Conji has been canceled|url=https://animecons.com/news/post/1483/anime-conji-has-been-canceled|publisher=AnimeCons.com|accessdate=6 June 2018|date=December 18, 2015}}</ref> The convention returned in 2018 under its original organizers, the San Diego Speculative Fiction Society (SanSFiS).<ref name=\"AC-Conji2018\">{{cite web | url = https://animecons.com/events/info/10766/anime-conji-2018 | title = Anime Conji 2018 Information | publisher = AnimeCons.com | accessdate = 2018-06-25}}</ref><ref name=\"spjaconji2018\">{{cite web|title=SanSFiS Resumes Operation of Anime Conji|url=https://www.spja.org/sansfis-resumes-operation-of-anime-conji/|website=Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation (SPJA)|accessdate=28 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328231255/https://www.spja.org/sansfis-resumes-operation-of-anime-conji/|archive-date=28 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Organizational structure==\nThe Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation (SPJA), the parent organization which produces Anime Expo, is a federal and California state registered 501(c)(6) non-profit corporation.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.spja.org/about-us/ |title=About The Society for the Promotion of Japanese Animation |access-date=2014-02-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301063516/http://www.spja.org/about-us/ |archive-date=2014-03-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The operation of Anime Expo is divided into two groups: Entertainment & Operations.\n\nEntertainment has the following divisions: AV Tech, Entertainment Hall, Guest Relations, Interactive Events and Programming. Operations has the following divisions: Exhibit Hall & Registration and Facilities. As of 2013, the SPJA employed 11 employees and over 1,000 volunteers for Anime Expo.\n\nAnime Expo's parent company, the SPJA, has a number of additional paid positions whose roles are to conduct the organization's year-round operations. \nSuch positions also include the: Administration Director, Chief Executive Officer, Finance Manager, HR Director, Marketing Director, and Technology Director. \nThe SPJA also hires consultants for outsourced functions such as: Marketing consultation, Governance & Strategic training, Legal representation, Exhibit sales, and as needed program assistance.\n\n==Notes==\n* The 2009 event donated over $29,000 to the [[Children's Hospital of Orange County]] (CHOC) from the SPJA Charity Auction, announced during closing ceremonies on Sunday, July 5, 2009<ref name=\"expo09\">[http://www.axbackstage.org/2009/07/05/anime-expo-2009-continues-to-hold-the-title-of-nations-largest-anime-and-manga-event-with-a-record-number-of-over-44000-in-attendance/ Anime Expo 2009 Continues to Hold the Title of Nation's Largest Anime and Manga Event with a Record Number of Over 44,000 in Attendance], July 5, 2009</ref>\n* Masquerade main event was attended by a standing-room only crowd with over 7,200 seats available.<ref>[http://www.axbackstage.org/2009/07/05/anime-expo-2009-continues-strong-into-day-4-as-the-nations-largest-anime-and-manga-convention/ Anime Expo 2009 Continues Strong into Day 4 as the Nation's Largest Anime and Manga Convention], July 5, 2009</ref>\n* Total 2010 through-the-doors attendance achieved 105,000 (turnstile), compared to 2009's attendance of 109,000 (turnstile). This was Anime Expo's second attendance decline since its inception.<ref>Carlo Santos, [http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/convention/2010/anime-expo/spja-open-board-meeting SPJA Open Board Meeting], ''Anime News Network'', July 4, 2010</ref>\n* Anime Expo's 20th Anniversary was celebrated in 2011.\n* July 4, 2011 \u2013 Nearly $30,000 dollars raised at the SPJA Charity Auction for the Japanese [[Red Cross]] Society to aid in disaster relief.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Los Angeles|Anime and manga}}\n{{commons category|Anime Expo}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.anime-expo.org/}}\n\n\n{{Anime conventions in North America}}\n\n[[Category:Anime conventions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Culture of Anaheim, California]]\n[[Category:Culture of Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:1992 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Conventions in Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Race Owenclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anime_Expo"}
{"title_page": "American Heiress", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name = American Heiress\n| image = American Heiress143.jpg\n| caption =\n| starring = [[Alicia Leigh Willis]]\n| opentheme =\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| network = [[MyNetworkTV]]\n| company = [[20th Century Fox Television]]\n| distributor = [[20th Television]]\n| location = [[San Diego]], [[California]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2007|3|13}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2007|7|18}}\n| num_seasons = 5\n| num_episodes = 65 (39 unaired)\n| website =\n}}\n'''''American Heiress''''' is a [[telenovela]] which debuted on March 13, 2007 at 8 p.m. ET/7 p.m. CT on the [[United States|American]] [[television network]] [[MyNetworkTV]]. This romantic melodrama tells the story of a roughneck pilot and a pampered heiress who survive a plane crash.  The show was produced by [[Fox Television Studios|Twentieth Television]], based on the 2004 [[TV Azteca]] series ''[[La Heredera]]'' (\"''The Heiress''\").\n\n''Heiress'' was the last series produced for [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|MyNetworkTV]]'s original all-telenovela format.  When the network dropped the serial after the July 18, 2007 broadcast, most episodes were left unaired. [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] has not announced plans to release this series on [[DVD]] and/or [[Blu-ray]]. All 65 episodes aired overseas.\n\n==Story==\n{{main|List of American Heiress episodes}}\nThis limited-run serial follows the title character, Elizabeth Wakefield, played by [[Alicia Leigh Willis]], from steamy rain forests to the high-stakes business world.  After a terrifying crash in the family jet, the heiress falls in love with a fellow survivor, a hard-edged former [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] pilot named JD Bruce ([[Carter MacIntyre]]).\n\nThe new couple then must struggle to survive in the lost jungles of [[Guatemala]]. Once back in civilization, the heiress soon finds herself in another tough situation. Against her family's wishes, she fights to keep the flames of passion burning.  Meanwhile, her brother Damian makes deals with an arms dealer; he will do anything to protect his secret.\n\n==Production ==\nHead writer Colet Abedi said she added \"bitchy dialogue and fight scenes\" to the original Mexican story.<ref>[http://www.out.com/detail.asp?id=22384 A Summer of Camp], ''Out.com'', April 1, 2007</ref>  Late in production, about six episodes\u2019 worth of scenes were never shot due to budget concerns. In addition, about 75 minutes of program were stretched to fill the two-hour weekly timeslot.<ref>[http://www.southflorida.com/movies/sfl-tvtjmynetmar12,0,469232.column?coll=sfe-tv-headlines]</ref> Fox also received promotional consideration for this series from several automakers, including Cadillac, Jaguar and Lexus.\n\n[[MyNetworkTV]] prepared to air this serial as 65 one-hour episodes on weekdays with a Saturday night recap.  The network, facing low ratings, stopped development on future [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|telenovelas]].<ref>[http://www.tvweek.com/news.cms?newsId=11637 MyNetwork TV: No More Scripted] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070303074204/http://www.tvweek.com/news.cms?newsId=11637 |date=2007-03-03 }}, ''TV Week'', March 1, 2007</ref> ''American Heiress'' had already finished shooting at [[Stu Segall Productions]] in San Diego before the decision was announced.\n\n''Heiress'' was originally intended to run in syndication as ''To Love & Die'' under the \"Secret Obsessions\" umbrella title.  The [[MyNetworkTV]] Web site listed the show as \"part of the ''[[Desire (TV series)|Desire]]'' series,\" however, referring to its other [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|telenovela]] brand.\n\nTwo-hour installments aired on Wednesday evenings through April, when the show switched to a one-hour slot.  [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|MyNetworkTV]] announced plans to run this show and ''[[Saints & Sinners (2007 TV series)|Saints & Sinners]]'' once per week until October,<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i91266009d4f35a6c1368f78df3983489 No upfront presentation from MyNetworkTV], ''Hollywood Reporter'', April 25, 2007</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-06-10-mynetwork_N.htm MyNetwork takes it on the chin, rebounds], ''USA Today'', June 11, 2007</ref> with the remaining episodes appearing online.<ref>[http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117963744.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 MyNet nixes glitzy makeover], ''Variety.com'', April 24, 2007</ref>  [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|MyNetworkTV]]  President Greg Meidel previously said the network would air the complete runs of both shows.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i119db77792cbaa01c3aea7c87504cc77, MyNetTV execs, affils: Change is good] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930224347/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i119db77792cbaa01c3aea7c87504cc77, |date=2007-09-30 }}, ''Hollywood Reporter'', March 9, 2007</ref>  However, the network unceremoniously yanked both telenovelas after the July 18, 2007 broadcast.  Only 26 out of 65 hours aired.\n\n==Cast==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! Actor !! Role\n|-\n| [[Alicia Leigh Willis]] ||  Elizabeth Wakefield\n|-\n| [[Carter MacIntyre]] || Captain JD Bruce\n|-\n| [[Theresa Russell]] || Jordan Wakefield\n|-\n| Race Owen || Damian Wakefield\n|-\n| [[AnnaLynne McCord]] || Loren Wakefield\n|-\n| [[Robert Buckley]] || Matthew Wakefield\n|}\n* [[Robert Buckley]] was also in the [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|MyNetworkTV telenovela]] ''[[Fashion House]]''.\n* [[AnnaLynne McCord]] was also cast in the unproduced telenovela ''Rules of Deception''.\n* The [[Elizabeth Wakefield]] character in this series is not the same one played by [[Cynthia Daniel]] in ''[[Sweet Valley High (TV Series)|Sweet Valley High]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0884294|title=American Heiress}}\n*{{tv.com show|american-heiress|American Heiress}}\n\n{{MyNetworkTV telenovelas}}\n\n[[Category:2000s American television series]]\n[[Category:2007 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2007 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2007 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American telenovelas]]\n[[Category:American television series based on telenovelas]]\n[[Category:MyNetworkTV original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by 20th Century Fox Television]]\n[[Category:American television series based on Mexican television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name = American Heiress\n| image = American Heiress143.jpg\n| caption =\n| starring = [[Alicia Leigh Willis]]\n| opentheme =\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| network = [[MyNetworkTV]]\n| company = [[20th Century Fox Television]]\n| distributor = [[20th Television]]\n| location = [[San Diego]], [[California]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|2007|3|13}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2007|7|18}}\n| num_seasons = 5\n| num_episodes = 65 (39 unaired)\n| website =\n}}\n'''''American Heiress''''' is a [[telenovela]] which debuted on March 13, 2007 at 8 p.m. ET/7 p.m. CT on the [[United States|American]] [[television network]] [[MyNetworkTV]]. This romantic melodrama tells the story of a roughneck pilot and a pampered heiress who survive a plane crash.  The show was produced by [[Fox Television Studios|Twentieth Television]], based on the 2004 [[TV Azteca]] series ''[[La Heredera]]'' (\"''The Heiress''\").\n\n''Heiress'' was the last series produced for [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|MyNetworkTV]]'s original all-telenovela format.  When the network dropped the serial after the July 18, 2007 broadcast, most episodes were left unaired. [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] has not announced plans to release this series on [[DVD]] and/or [[Blu-ray]]. All 65 episodes aired overseas.\n\n==Story==\n{{main|List of American Heiress episodes}}\nThis limited-run serial follows the title character, Elizabeth Wakefield, played by [[Alicia Leigh Willis]], from steamy rain forests to the high-stakes business world.  After a terrifying crash in the family jet, the heiress falls in love with a fellow survivor, a hard-edged former [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] pilot named JD Bruce ([[Carter MacIntyre]]).\n\nThe new couple then must struggle to survive in the lost jungles of [[Guatemala]]. Once back in civilization, the heiress soon finds herself in another tough situation. Against her family's wishes, she fights to keep the flames of passion burning.  Meanwhile, her brother Damian makes deals with an arms dealer; he will do anything to protect his secret.\n\n==Production ==\nHead writer Colet Abedi said she added \"bitchy dialogue and fight scenes\" to the original Mexican story.<ref>[http://www.out.com/detail.asp?id=22384 A Summer of Camp], ''Out.com'', April 1, 2007</ref>  Late in production, about six episodes\u2019 worth of scenes were never shot due to budget concerns. In addition, about 75 minutes of program were stretched to fill the two-hour weekly timeslot.<ref>[http://www.southflorida.com/movies/sfl-tvtjmynetmar12,0,469232.column?coll=sfe-tv-headlines]</ref> Fox also received promotional consideration for this series from several automakers, including Cadillac, Jaguar and Lexus.\n\n[[MyNetworkTV]] prepared to air this serial as 65 one-hour episodes on weekdays with a Saturday night recap.  The network, facing low ratings, stopped development on future [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|telenovelas]].<ref>[http://www.tvweek.com/news.cms?newsId=11637 MyNetwork TV: No More Scripted] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070303074204/http://www.tvweek.com/news.cms?newsId=11637 |date=2007-03-03 }}, ''TV Week'', March 1, 2007</ref> ''American Heiress'' had already finished shooting at [[Stu Segall Productions]] in San Diego before the decision was announced.\n\n''Heiress'' was originally intended to run in syndication as ''To Love & Die'' under the \"Secret Obsessions\" umbrella title.  The [[MyNetworkTV]] Web site listed the show as \"part of the ''[[Desire (TV series)|Desire]]'' series,\" however, referring to its other [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|telenovela]] brand.\n\nTwo-hour installments aired on Wednesday evenings through April, when the show switched to a one-hour slot.  [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|MyNetworkTV]] announced plans to run this show and ''[[Saints & Sinners (2007 TV series)|Saints & Sinners]]'' once per week until October,<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/news/e3i91266009d4f35a6c1368f78df3983489 No upfront presentation from MyNetworkTV], ''Hollywood Reporter'', April 25, 2007</ref><ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-06-10-mynetwork_N.htm MyNetwork takes it on the chin, rebounds], ''USA Today'', June 11, 2007</ref> with the remaining episodes appearing online.<ref>[http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117963744.html?categoryid=14&cs=1 MyNet nixes glitzy makeover], ''Variety.com'', April 24, 2007</ref>  [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|MyNetworkTV]]  President Greg Meidel previously said the network would air the complete runs of both shows.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i119db77792cbaa01c3aea7c87504cc77, MyNetTV execs, affils: Change is good] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930224347/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/television/news/e3i119db77792cbaa01c3aea7c87504cc77, |date=2007-09-30 }}, ''Hollywood Reporter'', March 9, 2007</ref>  However, the network unceremoniously yanked both telenovelas after the July 18, 2007 broadcast.  Only 26 out of 65 hours aired.\n\n==Cast==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! Actor !! Role\n|-\n| [[Alicia Leigh Willis]] ||  Elizabeth Wakefield\n|-\n| [[Carter MacIntyre]] || Captain JD Bruce\n|-\n| [[Theresa Russell]] || Jordan Wakefield\n|-\n| [[Race Owen]] || Damian Wakefield\n|-\n| [[AnnaLynne McCord]] || Loren Wakefield\n|-\n| [[Robert Buckley]] || Matthew Wakefield\n|}\n* [[Robert Buckley]] was also in the [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas|MyNetworkTV telenovela]] ''[[Fashion House]]''.\n* [[AnnaLynne McCord]] was also cast in the unproduced telenovela ''Rules of Deception''.\n* The [[Elizabeth Wakefield]] character in this series is not the same one played by [[Cynthia Daniel]] in ''[[Sweet Valley High (TV Series)|Sweet Valley High]]''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[MyNetworkTV telenovelas]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0884294|title=American Heiress}}\n*{{tv.com show|american-heiress|American Heiress}}\n\n{{MyNetworkTV telenovelas}}\n\n[[Category:2000s American television series]]\n[[Category:2007 telenovelas]]\n[[Category:2007 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2007 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American telenovelas]]\n[[Category:American television series based on telenovelas]]\n[[Category:MyNetworkTV original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by 20th Century Fox Television]]\n[[Category:American television series based on Mexican television series]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Race Owenclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Heiress"}
{"title_page": "QP (video game)", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n|title         = QP\n|image         = QP (video game) title screen.jpg\n|caption       = [[Title screen]]\n|developer     = [[Success (company)|Success]]\n|publisher     = Success\n|platforms     = [[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[Neo Geo CD]]\n|released      = Unreleased\n|genre         = [[Party video game|Party]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]]\n|arcade system = [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo MVS]]\n|cpu           = [[Motorola 68000|M68000]] (@ 12 [[Hertz|MHz]]),<br />[[Zilog Z80|Z80A]] (@ 4 MHz)\n|sound         = [[Yamaha YM2610|YM2610]] (@ 8 MHz)<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=869&page=6#18491|title=SNK NeoGeo MVS Hardware (SNK)|website=system16.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 304 \u00d7 224 pixels (Horizontal), 4096 [[color]]s\n}}\n\n'''''QP''''' is an unreleased [[1997 in video gaming|1997]] [[Party video game|party]] [[Arcade game|arcade]] [[video game]] that was in development and planned to be published by [[Success (company)|Success]] for both the [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo MVS]] (arcade) and [[Neo Geo CD]] [[Video game#Platforms|platforms]].<ref name=\"NGF1\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/neogeofreak0001#page/n112/mode/1up|title=NEO\u2022GEOCD|magazine=Neo Geo Freak|issue=1|publisher=Geibunsha|date=May 1995|page=111|lang=ja}}</ref><ref name=\"NGF22a\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Neo-Geo_Freak_1997-03_Geibunsha_JP#page/n59/mode/1up|title=New Game - QP|magazine=Neo Geo Freak|issue=22|publisher=Geibunsha|date=March 1997|pages=58-61|lang=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Reynolds|first=Stuart|url=http://www.neogeoforlife.com/articles.php?article_id=5|title=Neo Geo Prototypes|website=neogeoforlife.com|date=December 25, 2006|access-date=2020-01-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231071451/http://www.neogeoforlife.com/articles.php?article_id=5|archive-date=2018-12-31|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|url=http://neogeocdworld.free.fr/dossiers/Protos/arcade/ProtosZ.htm|title=Protos et Rumeurs Sur la Neo Geo CD|website=Neo\u2022Geo CD World|accessdate=2020-01-20|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Xacrow|url=http://unibios.free.fr/xacrow/unrelease.txt|title=NEO GEO UNRELEASE TITLE LIST|website=unibios.free.fr|access-date=2020-01-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231071320/http://unibios.free.fr/xacrow/unrelease.txt|archive-date=2018-12-31|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> \n\nIn ''QP'', players can choose between one of eight characters and participate against [[AI]]-controlled opponents or against other players across [[minigame]]s on a traditional-style [[board game]] map. Although previewed across a few [[video game magazine]]s, the game was ultimately shelved for unknown reasons.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.culturaneogeo.com/protos1#qp|title=Juegos Prototipo - Q.P.|publisher=Cultura Neo Geo|accessdate=2019-11-24|language=es}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:NEOGEO QP (Quality People).jpg|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot.]]\n''QP'' is a multiplayer party game featuring eight playable characters where players participate against AI-controlled or other human opponents across minigames, while [[gameplay]] is presented in the form of a [[game show]]-themed traditional-style board map.<ref name=\"NGF22a\"/><ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\"NGF23\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Neo-Geo_Freak_1997-04_Geibunsha_JP#page/n71/mode/2up|title=New Game - QP|magazine=Neo Geo Freak|issue=23|publisher=Geibunsha|date=April 1997|pages=70-71|lang=ja}}</ref><ref name=\"G199\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Gamest/Gamest_JP_199#page/n217/mode/1up|title=New Game First Rip Open - QP|magazine=[[Gamest]]|issue=199|publisher=[[Shinseisha]]|date=August 15, 1997|page=214|lang=ja}}</ref> Besides minigames, players would also participate on other events to test their skills.<ref name=\"NGF23\"/>\n\n== History ==\n''QP'' was first announced across various Japanese publications such as ''Neo Geo Freak'' as a Neo Geo CD title for a January [[1996 in video gaming|1996]] launch.<ref name=\"NGF1\"/> Although its production number during development remains unknown, it is generally believed to be assigned with either number 104 or 204.<ref>{{cite web|last=Giles|first=Aaron|url=https://github.com/mamedev/mame/blob/f15313bc070231f7fe13b2b63bf3d0ae55793171/src/mame/arcade.lst|title=arcade.lst|publisher=[[GitHub]]|accessdate=2020-01-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231021824/https://github.com/mamedev/mame/blob/f15313bc070231f7fe13b2b63bf3d0ae55793171/src/mame/arcade.lst|archive-date=2018-12-31|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cannarsi|first=Gualtiero|url=http://castleofcollectibles.com/U-List.txt|title=NEO\u2022GEO AES UNRELEASED LIST|website=castleofcollectibles.com|date=September 5, 2004|access-date=2020-01-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316032349/http://castleofcollectibles.com/U-List.txt|archivedate=March 16, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cannarsi|first=Gualtiero|url=http://www.neo-geo.com/forums/showthread.php?117868-NEOGEO-PROTOS-breakdown-list|title=NEOGEO PROTOS breakdown list|website=neo-geo.com|date=April 22, 2005|access-date=2020-01-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405223836/http://www.neo-geo.com/forums/showthread.php?117868-NEOGEO-PROTOS-breakdown-list|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=q.p.&page=detail&id=4241|title=Q.P.|website=arcade-history.com|access-date=2020-01-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231063854/https://www.arcade-history.com/?n=q.p.&page=detail&id=4241|archive-date=2018-12-31|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|last=Pitt|first=Billy|url=http://www.neogeoprotos.com/games/qp.htm|title=Q.P. (Quality People) by Success - NEO GEO MVS NGM-104|website=neogeoprotos.com|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> \n\nThe game was also discusse by a member of the development team at Success in the March [[1997 in video gaming|1997]] issue of ''Neo Geo Freak'', in addition of being previewed and advertised via official artwork through other magazines such as ''[[Gamest]]''.<ref name=\"G199\"/><ref name=\"NGF22b\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Neo-Geo_Freak_1997-03_Geibunsha_JP#page/n87/mode/1up|title=11 - \u30b5\u30af\u30bb\u30b9|magazine=Neo Geo Freak|issue=22|publisher=Geibunsha|date=March 1997|pages=86-87|lang=ja}}</ref><ref name=\"NGF24\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Neo-Geo_Freak_1997-05_Geibunsha_JP#page/n71/mode/1up|title=QP|magazine=Neo Geo Freak|issue=24|publisher=Geibunsha|date=May 1997|page=70|lang=ja}}</ref><ref name=\"NGF25\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Neo-Geo_Freak_1997-06_Geibunsha_JP#page/n64/mode/1up|title=QP|magazine=Neo Geo Freak|issue=25|publisher=Geibunsha|date=June 1997|page=63|lang=ja}}</ref> Despite being touted for a May 1997 release, it was ultimately shelved for unknown reasons, however several possible factors have been given as to why the title was never published in recent years.<ref name=\"NGF22a\"/><ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\"NGF23\"/><ref name=\":1\"/> Though a prototype cartridge is rumored to exist, no [[ROM image]] of the title has managed to surface online.<ref>{{cite web|author=Shou|url=http://forums.gamengai.com/viewtopic.php?f=2&t=553&p=28471&hilit=Success+Neo+Geo#p28471|title=The emulation thread... (Page 19)|website=gamengai.com|date=June 28, 2016|access-date=2020-01-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200121012747/http://forums.gamengai.com/viewtopic.php?f=2&t=553&p=28471&hilit=Success+Neo+Geo|archive-date=2020-01-21|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Neo Geo}}\n{{Portal bar|1990s|Japan|Video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:QP (video game)}}\n<nowiki>[[Category:1997 video games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled arcade games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Neo Geo games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled Neo Geo CD games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Party video games]]\n[[Category:Success (company) games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games featuring female protagonists]]</nowiki>\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n|title         = QP\n|image         = QP (video game) title screen.jpg\n|caption       = [[Title screen]]\n|developer     = [[Success (company)|Success]]\n|publisher     = Success\n|platforms     = [[Arcade game|Arcade]], [[Neo Geo CD]]\n|released      = Unreleased\n|genre         = [[Party video game|Party]]\n|modes         = {{flatlist|\n*[[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n*[[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]}}\n|cabinet       = [[Arcade cabinet#Upright cabinets|Upright]]\n|arcade system = [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo MVS]]\n|cpu           = [[Motorola 68000|M68000]] (@ 12 [[Hertz|MHz]]),<br />[[Zilog Z80|Z80A]] (@ 4 MHz)\n|sound         = [[Yamaha YM2610|YM2610]] (@ 8 MHz)<ref name=\"s16\">{{cite web|url=http://www.system16.com/hardware.php?id=869&page=6#18491|title=SNK NeoGeo MVS Hardware (SNK)|website=system16.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n|display       = [[Raster graphics|Raster]], 304 \u00d7 224 pixels (Horizontal), 4096 [[color]]s\n}}\n\n'''''QP''''' is an unreleased [[1997 in video gaming|1997]] [[Party video game|party]] [[Arcade game|arcade]] [[video game]] that was in development and planned to be published by [[Success (company)|Success]] for both the [[Neo Geo (system)|Neo Geo MVS]] (arcade) and [[Neo Geo CD]] [[Video game#Platforms|platforms]].<ref name=\"NGF1\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/neogeofreak0001#page/n112/mode/1up|title=NEO\u2022GEOCD|magazine=Neo Geo Freak|issue=1|publisher=Geibunsha|date=May 1995|page=111|lang=ja}}</ref><ref name=\"NGF22a\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Neo-Geo_Freak_1997-03_Geibunsha_JP#page/n59/mode/1up|title=New Game - QP|magazine=Neo Geo Freak|issue=22|publisher=Geibunsha|date=March 1997|pages=58-61|lang=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Reynolds|first=Stuart|url=http://www.neogeoforlife.com/articles.php?article_id=5|title=Neo Geo Prototypes|website=neogeoforlife.com|date=December 25, 2006|access-date=2020-01-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231071451/http://www.neogeoforlife.com/articles.php?article_id=5|archive-date=2018-12-31|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|url=http://neogeocdworld.free.fr/dossiers/Protos/arcade/ProtosZ.htm|title=Protos et Rumeurs Sur la Neo Geo CD|website=Neo\u2022Geo CD World|accessdate=2020-01-20|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Xacrow|url=http://unibios.free.fr/xacrow/unrelease.txt|title=NEO GEO UNRELEASE TITLE LIST|website=unibios.free.fr|access-date=2020-01-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231071320/http://unibios.free.fr/xacrow/unrelease.txt|archive-date=2018-12-31|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> In the game, players can choose between one of eight characters and participate against [[AI]]-controlled opponents or against other players across [[minigame]]s on a traditional-style [[board game]] map. Although previewed across a few [[video game magazine]]s, the title was ultimately shelved for unknown reasons.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.culturaneogeo.com/protos1#qp|title=Juegos Prototipo - Q.P.|publisher=Cultura Neo Geo|accessdate=2019-11-24|language=es}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:NEOGEO QP (Quality People).jpg|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot.]]\n''QP'' is a multiplayer party game featuring eight playable characters where players participate against AI-controlled or other human opponents across minigames, while [[gameplay]] is presented in the form of a [[game show]]-themed traditional-style board map.<ref name=\"NGF22a\"/><ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\"NGF23\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Neo-Geo_Freak_1997-04_Geibunsha_JP#page/n71/mode/2up|title=New Game - QP|magazine=Neo Geo Freak|issue=23|publisher=Geibunsha|date=April 1997|pages=70-71|lang=ja}}</ref><ref name=\"G199\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Gamest/Gamest_JP_199#page/n217/mode/1up|title=New Game First Rip Open - QP|magazine=[[Gamest]]|issue=199|publisher=[[Shinseisha]]|date=August 15, 1997|page=214|lang=ja}}</ref> Besides minigames, players would also participate on other events to test their skills.<ref name=\"NGF23\"/>\n\n== History ==\n''QP'' was first announced across various Japanese publications such as ''Neo Geo Freak'' as a Neo Geo CD title for a January [[1996 in video gaming|1996]] launch.<ref name=\"NGF1\"/> Although its production number during development remains unknown, it is generally believed to be assigned with either number 104 or 204.<ref>{{cite web|last=Giles|first=Aaron|url=https://github.com/mamedev/mame/blob/f15313bc070231f7fe13b2b63bf3d0ae55793171/src/mame/arcade.lst|title=arcade.lst|publisher=[[GitHub]]|accessdate=2020-01-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181231021824/https://github.com/mamedev/mame/blob/f15313bc070231f7fe13b2b63bf3d0ae55793171/src/mame/arcade.lst|archive-date=2018-12-31|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cannarsi|first=Gualtiero|url=http://castleofcollectibles.com/U-List.txt|title=NEO\u2022GEO AES UNRELEASED LIST|website=castleofcollectibles.com|date=September 5, 2004|access-date=2020-01-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316032349/http://castleofcollectibles.com/U-List.txt|archivedate=March 16, 2016|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cannarsi|first=Gualtiero|url=http://www.neo-geo.com/forums/showthread.